Thant Peace Award]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Sri Chinmoy}}\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.srichinmoy.org/  SriChinmoy.org]\n* {{Internet Archive author}}\n* [https://www.hollywoodfringe.org/projects/5010/  Nephew of the Universe - Comedy inspired by Sri Chinmoy Path]\n{{Spirituality-related topics}} \n{{New Age Movement}}\n{{Portal bar|Hinduism|India|Religion}} \n{{Authority control}}\n\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chinmoy, Sri}}\n[[Category:Sri Chinmoy| ]]\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:Bengali Hindus]]\n[[Category:Bengali people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Bengali poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Indian spiritual teachers]]\n[[Category:Indian spiritual writers]]\n[[Category:People from Chittagong]]\n[[Category:Spiritual practice]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Bengali poets]]\n[[Category:Bengali male poets]]\n[[Category:Indian male poets]]\n", "name_user": "Doug Weller", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Reverted to revision 948277213 bySoftlavender(talk): SeeWP:EL(TW))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sri_Chinmoy"}
{"title_page": "Murder of Brooke Wilberger", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Brooke Wilberger\n| image       = Brooke_Wilberger.jpg\n| image_size  = 200px\n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Brooke Carol Wilberger \n| birth_date  = February 20, 1985\n| birth_place = [[Fresno, California|Fresno]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2004|05|25|1985|02|20}}\n| death_place = [[Corvallis, Oregon|Corvallis]], [[Oregon]], U.S.\n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| known_for   = Missing person and murder victim\n| parents     = Greg and Cammy Wilberger\n}}\n\n'''Brooke Carol Wilberger''' (February 20, 1985 \u2013 May 25, 2004) was an [[Americans|American]] student from the state of [[Oregon]] who was abducted and later murdered. Her disappearance was covered by the national media; her murder investigation was one of the most publicized in Oregon's history.<ref name=\"ERG\"/><ref name=SJ>{{cite news |url= http://www.statesmanjournal.com/article/20090921/UPDATE/90921014 |title= Brooke Wilberger's remains found in coastal range, killer sentenced to life in prison |newspaper= [[Statesman Journal]] |location= [[Salem, Oregon]] |date= September 21, 2009 |accessdate= September 22, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBrooke Wilberger was born in [[Fresno, California|Fresno]], [[California]], on February 20, 1985 to Greg and Cammy Wilberger. She had three sisters and two brothers.<ref name=\"Register-Guard\" /> Described as a devout member of the [[Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]], Wilberger was a graduate of [[Elmira High School]] near [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]], [[Oregon]].<ref name=\"amw\"/> She had just completed her [[freshman]] year at [[Brigham Young University]] in [[Provo, Utah]], at the time of her abduction.<ref name=\"amw\">{{cite web|title=Authorities Charge Man With Murder |url=http://www.amw.com/missing_persons/case.cfm?id=27071 |work=[[America's Most Wanted]] |accessdate=April 13, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026002230/http://www.amw.com/missing_persons/case.cfm?id=27071 |archivedate=October 26, 2012  }}</ref><ref name=abcnewsrecov>{{cite news\n|title=Brooke Wilberger found: Killer gives location of remains to avoid death penalty\n|website=[[ABC News]]\n|publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company]]\n|location=New York City\n|first1=Dean\n|last1=Schabner\n|first2=Sarah \n|last2=Netter\n|date=September 21, 2009\n|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/remains-brooke-wilberger-found-years-disappearance/story?id=8632233\n}}</ref> During that time, her boyfriend, Justin Blake, was serving as a [[Mormon missionary]] in [[Venezuela]].<ref name=\"20/20\">{{cite news\n|title=Vanished: Two coeds, two horrifying mysteries\n|first=Donna\n|last=Hunter\n|date=August 14, 2008\n|work=[[20/20 (US television show)|20/20]]\n|publisher=[[ABC News]]\n|location=New York City\n|url=http://abcnews.go.com/2020/Story?id=5578937\n}}</ref>\n\n==Disappearance==\nAt the time of her disappearance, Wilberger was on summer vacation, visiting and working for one of her sisters in [[Corvallis, Oregon]].<ref name=\"Register-Guard\">{{cite news|title=Waiting for Brooke|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Waiting+for+Brooke.-a0132784667|newspaper=[[The Register-Guard]]|publisher=GateHouse Media|location=Eugene, Oregon|accessdate=March 18, 2017|date=May 24, 2005}}</ref> On the morning May 24, 2004, Wilberger was last seen cleaning [[lamp post]]s in the parking lot of the Oak Park Apartments, which her sister and brother-in-law managed, on the edge of the [[Oregon State University]] campus.<ref>{{cite web | title=Suspect Charged With Murder Of Brooke Wilberger | work=[[KUTV.com]] |url=http://kutv.com/topstories/local_story_214201808.html |accessdate=April 13, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926211903/http://kutv.com/topstories/local_story_214201808.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = September 26, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Crime Alert Archive|url=https://fa.oregonstate.edu/book/export/html/3793|website=fa.oregonstate.edu|publisher=[[Oregon State University]]|accessdate=March 18, 2017|language=en|date=August 3, 2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319111949/https://fa.oregonstate.edu/book/export/html/3793|archivedate=March 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\n===Initial efforts===\n[[Image:Brooke-salem.jpg|thumb|A billboard in [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]] requesting information on Brooke Wilberger.]]\nWhen Wilberger disappeared, the police began investigating immediately \u2013 against normal procedure. Lt. Ron Noble of the Corvallis Police Department said, \"Normally, we would wait. Because adults can come and go as they please, and we would normally wait to see if she showed up maybe the next day.\" However, in this case, police officials agreed with the family that Wilberger was not the type of girl to disappear on her own.<ref name=\"20/20\"/> The Wilbergers' [[Ward (LDS Church)|LDS ward]] organized a search by citizens of Corvallis.<ref name=\"20/20\"/>\n\nThe investigation initially centered on Sung Koo Kim, who was named as \"[[person of interest]]\" in the disappearance. Kim was later dropped as a suspect, but received an 11-year prison sentence for multiple counts of [[burglary]] and theft of women's personal property in [[Yamhill County, Oregon|Yamhill County]], crimes uncovered while he was being investigated for the Wilberger disappearance.<ref>{{cite web\n|title=Sung Koo Kim gets nearly six years for underwear thefts\n| work=[[KATU.com]] \n| url=http://www.katu.com/news/3651561.html\n|accessdate=April 13, 2007\n}}</ref> He was released in December 2012 after serving about seven years.\n\n===Joel Patrick Courtney===\nOn November 30, 2004, a [[University of New Mexico]] [[foreign exchange student]] was beaten and [[rape]]d before escaping and identified Joel Patrick Courtney as her attacker. On September 12, 2007, Courtney pleaded guilty to the attack. Courtney's [[plea agreement]] called for a prison sentence of up to 18 years, plus 5 to 20 years on [[parole]].<ref name=\"KVAL\">{{cite news|title=DA: 'His intent was that no one ever find her'|url=http://www.kval.com/news/local/60012167.html|accessdate=March 18, 2017|work=[[KVAL.com]]|publisher=[[Sinclair Broadcasting|Sinclair Interactive Media]]|location=Corvallis, Oregon|date=September 21, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530125345/http://www.kval.com/news/local/60012167.html|archivedate=May 30, 2015|language=en}}</ref>\n\nPolice eventually linked Courtney, a native of [[Beaverton, Oregon]], to Wilberger's disappearance. In August 2005, he was charged on 19 counts of [[aggravated murder]], [[kidnapping]], [[sexual abuse]], rape and [[sodomy]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Joel Patrick Courtney, serial killer & rapist |url=http://www.crimelibrary.com/serial_killers/predators/joel_courtney/1.html |website=[[Crime Library]]|publisher=[[TruTV]]|location=Atlanta, Georgia|accessdate=March 8, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060303133837/http://www.crimelibrary.com/serial_killers/predators/joel_courtney/1.html |archivedate=March 3, 2006 }}</ref> Court documents released in 2008 revealed details showing that Courtney was in Corvallis when Wilberger disappeared and that a green van he was driving was spotted by several people, including an OSU employee who identified him from a photo lineup.<ref>{{cite news\n|title = Suspect's van seen in Corvallis|first = William|last = McCall|newspaper=[[Deseret News]]|publisher=[[Deseret News Publishing Company]]|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|date = April 19, 2008|url = http://www.deseretnews.com/article/695271843/Suspects-van-seen-in-Corvallis.html|access-date = June 22, 2015|agency= [[Associated Press]]}}</ref> Officials said that Wilberger's [[DNA]] was found inside the van, along with her hair.<ref>{{Cite news|title = Slain BYU student's Ore. mother grateful case over|url = http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2009/09/22/slain_byu_students_ore_mother_grateful_case_over/|website= [[Boston.com]]|agency = [[Associated Press]] |date = September 22, 2009|access-date = June 22, 2015|first = William|last = McCall}}</ref>\n\nCourtney was [[Extradition|extradited]] to [[Benton County, Oregon]] on April 8, 2008.<ref name=\"kval.com\">\n{{cite news\n|title       = Joel Courtney arrives in Oregon to face charges in Wilberger murder\n|work        = [[KVAL-TV]]\n|date        = April 8, 2008\n|location    = Corvallis, Oregon\n|accessdate  = March 18, 2017\n|url-status     = dead \n|url         = http://www.kval.com/news/local/17403709.html\n|archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20150530143017/http://www.kval.com/news/local/17403709.html\n|archivedate = May 30, 2015\n}}</ref> He was scheduled for his first appearance on April 9, 2008, at the Benton County Courthouse,<ref name=\"Oregon Live\">\n{{cite news\n|last1       =Jung\n|first1      =Helen\n|title       =Twists and turns in the Brooke Wilberger case\n|url         =http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/09/twists_and_turns_in_the_brooke.html\n|accessdate  =March 18, 2017\n|work        =OregonLive.com\n|publisher   =Oregon Live LLC.\n|date        =September 21, 2009\n|language    =en\n}}</ref>\nfacing 14 counts including aggravated murder, two counts of kidnapping and single counts of rape, sodomy and sexual abuse in connection with Wilberger's disappearance. Charges were filed despite the absence of the body of the alleged victim at the time; the [[prosecutor]] in the case announced that he would seek the [[death penalty]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n|title        =Effort begins to extradite Wilberger murder suspect\n|url          =http://www.katu.com/news/12446241.html\n|accessdate   =March 18, 2017\n|agency       =Associated Press\n|publisher    =Sinclair Interactive Media, LLC\n|date         =December 12, 2007\n|archiveurl   =https://web.archive.org/web/20150622132234/http://www.katu.com/news/12446241.html\n|archivedate  =June 22, 2015\n|location     =CORVALLIS, Ore.\n|language     =en\n}}\n</ref> The [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] had briefly considered Courtney a suspect in two to three disappearances under investigation, but have since eliminated him as a suspect.<ref>{{cite news\n|title        =FBI drops Joel Courtney as suspect in two cases\n|date         =February 23, 2006 \n|agency       =Associated Press\n|publisher    =[[KATU]]\n|first        =Joseph B.\n|last         =Frazier\n|url          =http://www.katu.com/news/3643546.html\n|accessdate   =March 18, 2017\n|url-status      =dead\n|archiveurl   =https://web.archive.org/web/20140502004237/http://www.katu.com/news/3643546.html\n|archivedate  = May 2, 2014\n|location     = Portland, Ore.\n}}</ref>\n\nIt was revealed through court [[Deposition (law)|deposition]] and Courtney's [[confession]] that he had abducted Wilberger from the Oak Park Apartments parking lot on the morning of May 24, 2004. He then drove her into the woods outside of town. He returned to town to buy food while he still had Wilberger bound in his van. According to Courtney, he kept her alive throughout the night before raping her the next morning. He then bludgeoned her to death when she tried to fight off the rape.<ref name=\"ERG\">{{cite news|url=http://www.registerguard.com/csp/cms/sites/web/updates/20477444-55/story.csp|title=Killer's guilty plea brings family closure|last=Moran|first=Jack|date=September 22, 2009|newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard|accessdate=September 22, 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Conviction====\nCourtney's attorneys worked towards a trial, as well as towards a speedier resolution. The trial was set for February 1, 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazettetimes.com/news/local/article_fb0d255e-ffc4-5673-9668-f0848e3b1117.html|title=Courtney headed for trial|last=Booth|first=Michael|date=September 5, 2009|newspaper=Corvallis Gazette-Times|accessdate=September 22, 2009}}</ref> He was expected to be charged in connection with the unrelated kidnapping, attempted [[sexual assault]] and attempted murder of two [[Oregon State University]] students, the same day Wilberger went missing.<ref name=\"kval.com\" />\n\nOn September 21, 2009, Courtney pleaded guilty to aggravated murder, the only crime subject to [[capital punishment in Oregon]], and was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] without the possibility of parole.<ref>{{cite web | last=Netter | first=Sarah | work=ABC News | title=Brooke Wilberger Found: Killer Gives Location of Remains to Avoid Death Penalty | url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/remains-brooke-wilberger-found-years-disappearance/story?id=8632233 |accessdate=September 21, 2009}}</ref> The deal spared Courtney from the death penalty, in exchange for providing information about the location of Wilberger's body.<ref name=\"ERG\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=To Avoid Death Penalty, Joel Courtney Reveals Location of Student Brooke Wilberger's Body - True Crime Report|url=http://www.truecrimereport.com/2009/09/to_avoid_death_penalty_joel_co.php|website=True Crime Report|accessdate=March 18, 2017|date=September 22, 2009}}</ref> In addition, the deal also called for Courtney to be imprisoned in his home state, [[New Mexico]], instead of Oregon where the crime was committed.\n\nThe Benton County [[District Attorney]] announced the recovery of Wilberger's body (without specifics or its location) in a press conference the day of Courtney's confession.<ref>{{cite news\n|title= Wilberger's remains recovered; Courtney pleads guilty to murder\n|first=Rachel\n|last=Beck\n|date=September 22, 2009\n|work=Corvallis Gazette-Times\n|url=http://www.gazettetimes.com/news/local/article_0ffadf0e-a70d-11de-bfd1-001cc4c03286.html\n}}</ref> It was later revealed that her remains had been concealed in the woods on an abandoned [[logging road]] between [[Blodgett, Oregon|Blodgett]] and [[Wren, Oregon|Wren]],<ref>{{cite web|work=Albany Democrat-Herald|url=http://democratherald.com/news/local/authorities-finish-recovering-remains-of-brooke-wilberger/article_9749f61e-addb-11de-94f9-001cc4c03286.html|title=Authorities finish recovering remains of Brooke Wilberger|date=September 30, 2009|location=Albany, Ore.|author=Beck, Rachel|accessdate=November 11, 2017}}</ref> located in the [[Central Oregon Coast Range|Oregon Coast Range]].<ref name=SJ/><ref>{{cite news|title=BREAKING NEWS: Press Conference - Brooke Wilberger's Remains Found |date=September 22, 2009 |first=Sabina |last=Rosu-Urdes |url=http://kezi.com/news/local/141973 |work=KEZI |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090925152340/http://kezi.com/news/local/141973 |archivedate=September 25, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Media coverage==\nThe Wilberger case was covered several times on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] television program ''[[America's Most Wanted]]'' between 2004 and 2006.<ref>\n{{Cite web\n|title        =America's Most Wanted {{!}} Missing Persons {{!}} Brooke Wilberger Case \n|url          =http://www.amw.com/missing_persons/case.cfm?id=27071 \n|date         =September 21, 2009 \n|accessdate   =June 22, 2015 \n|url-status      =dead \n|archiveurl   =https://web.archive.org/web/20120323015746/http://www.amw.com/missing_persons/case.cfm?id=27071 \n|archivedate  =March 23, 2012  \n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|title         =America's Most Wanted {{!}} Missing Data File for Brooke Carol Wilberger\n|url           =http://www2.amw.com/missing_persons/case.cfm?id=27071\n|accessdate    =March 19, 2017\n|archiveurl    =https://web.archive.org/web/20060327062207/http://www2.amw.com/missing_persons/case.cfm?id=27071\n|archivedate   =March 27, 2006\n}}</ref> ''[[The Montel Williams Show]]'' interviewed three of Wilberger's siblings, Shannon, Spencer and Jessica, which aired November 29, 2004.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title       =\"The Montel Williams Show\" {{!}} Vanished Without a Trace (TV Episode 2004)\n|url         =https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5900516/\n|website     =Internet Movie Database (IMDb)\n|accessdate  =March 19, 2017\n|date        =November 29, 2004\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|title        =CBS Television Distribution - Best of Montel\n|url          =http://www.montelshow.com/show/upcoming_detail.htm?index=0\n|website      =www.montelshow.com\n|accessdate   =March 19, 2017\n|archiveurl   =https://web.archive.org/web/20041205003616/http://www.montelshow.com/show/upcoming_detail.htm?index=0\n|archivedate  =December 5, 2004\n|date         =November 29, 2004\n}}</ref> The [[ABC News]] program ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'' examined Wilberger's disappearance along with that of [[Disappearance of Maura Murray|Maura Murray]] on March 17, 2006.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|title        =20/20 {{!}} Vanished: Two Coeds, Two Horrifying Mysteries\n|url          =http://abcnews.go.com/2020/story?id=1734155&page=1\n|accessdate   =March 19, 2017\n|work         =20/20\n|publisher    =ABC News\n|date         =  March 17, 2006\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|title        =20/20 {{!}} Vanished: Two Coeds, Two Horrifying Mysteries\n|url          =https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2370114/?ref_=ttep_ep2\n|website      =Internet Movie Database (IMDb)\n|accessdate   =  March 16, 2017\n|date         =March 17, 2006\n}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Investigation Discovery]] Channel portrayed the Wilberger story on three different series:\n{{bulleted list\n|The first showing was on the crime examination series \"[[On the Case with Paula Zahn]]\", Season 1, Episode 14 ''Beauty and the Beast'' first aired: April 18, 2010.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title        =On the Case With Paula Zahn {{!}} Beauty and the Beast\n|url          =http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/on-the-case-with-paula-zahn/episode-14-season-1/beauty-and-the-beast/298996/\n|website      =TVGuide.com\n|accessdate   =March 18, 2017\n|language     =en\n|date         =April 18, 2010\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n |title       = One the Case with Paula Zahn {{!}} Beauty and the Beast\n |url         = http://www.investigationdiscovery.com/tv-shows/on-the-case-with-paula-zahn/videos/on-the-case-with-paula-zahn-season-2-beauty-and-the-beast/\n |website     = Investigation Discovery\n |accessdate  = March 18, 2017\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170319111422/http://www.investigationdiscovery.com/tv-shows/on-the-case-with-paula-zahn/videos/on-the-case-with-paula-zahn-season-2-beauty-and-the-beast/\n |archivedate = March 19, 2017\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n|The second showing was on the documentary series \"FBI: Criminal Pursuit\", titled  ''Predator'', Season 2, Episode 10, original air date April 29, 2011.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title        =FBI: Criminal Pursuit {{!}} Predator\n|url          =https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1875293/?ref_=ttrel_rel_tt\n|publisher    =Investigation Discovery\n|accessdate   =March 18, 2017\n|date         =April 29, 2011\n}}</ref>\n|The third documentary was the Season 5, Episode 5, titled: ''An Angel Taken'', of the series \"Motives & Murders: Cracking The Case\", premiered March 31, 2016.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title         =Motives & Murders: Cracking the Case {{!}} An Angel Taken\n|url           =http://www.investigationdiscoverygo.com/motives-murders-cracking-the-case/\n|website       =Investigation Discovery\n|accessdate    =March 18, 2017\n|language      =en-us\n|date          =March 31, 2016\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|title         =Motives & Murders: Cracking The Case {{!}} An Angel Taken\n|url           =http://mytvee.ga/episodes/13364/motives_and_murders_cracking_the_case_s6_e5\n|website       =mytvee.ga\n|accessdate    =March 18, 2017\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''[[Dateline NBC]]'' aired a two-hour special on the case on February 4, 2011.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|last1        =Raskauskas\n|first1       =Nancy\n|title        =Brooke Wilberger back in TV spotlight\n|url          =http://www.gazettetimes.com/news/local/brooke-wilberger-back-in-tv-spotlight/article_e0372760-2dbf-11e0-8c00-001cc4c002e0.html\n|accessdate   =March 18, 2017\n|work         =Corvallis Gazette Times\n|publisher    =Gazette Times\n|date         =January 31, 2011\n|language     =en\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n|title        =Full Episode: Bringing Brooke Home\n|url          =http://www.nbcnews.com/dateline/video/full-episode--bringing-brooke-home-515002435992\n|accessdate   =March 18, 2017\n|work         =NBC News\n|language     =en\n}}</ref> The [[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]] channel documentary series ''It Takes A Killer'' also covered the case on January 6, 2017.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title         =In Search of a Kill\n|url           =http://www.oxygen.com/it-takes-a-killer/season-1/in-search-of-a-kill\n|website       =Oxygen Official Site\n|accessdate    =March 18, 2017\n|date          =January 6, 2017\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|title         =Shows A-Z - It Takes A Killer on Oxygen {{!}} TheFutonCritic.com\n|url           =http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/it-takes-a-killer/listings/\n|website       =www.thefutoncritic.com\n|accessdate    =March 18, 2017\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|title         =Brooke Wilberger\n|url           =http://wn.com/brooke_wilberger\n|website       =World News\n|accessdate    =March 19, 2017\n|language      =en\n}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of solved missing persons cases]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.inarchive.com/com/a/amw.com/7941/2011-11-13-description/74/AMW_Report_a_Tip_Brooke_Wilberger/ America's Most Wanted {{!}} Brooke Wilberger] at inarchive.com\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140403043410/http://www.crimelibrary.com/serial_killers/predators/joel_courtney/1.html Joel Courtney Predator Writing] at crimelibrary.com (archived)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilberger, Brooke}}\n[[Category:2004 in Oregon]]\n[[Category:2004 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Corvallis, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Deaths by beating in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by person in the United States]]\n[[Category:Incidents of violence against women]]\n[[Category:Kidnappings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Murder in Oregon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Brooke Wilberger\n| image       = Brooke_Wilberger.jpg\n| image_size  = 200px\n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Brooke Carol Wilberger \n| birth_date  = February 20, 1985\n| birth_place = [[Fresno, California|Fresno]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2004|05|25|1985|02|20}}\n| death_place = [[Corvallis, Oregon|Corvallis]], [[Oregon]], U.S.\n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| known_for   = Missing person and murder victim\n| parents     = Greg and Cammy Wilberger\n}}\n\n'''Brooke Carol Wilberger''' (February 20, 1985 \u2013 May 25, 2004) was an [[Americans|American]] student from the state of [[Oregon]] who was abducted and later murdered. Her disappearance was covered by the national media; her murder investigation was one of the most publicized in Oregon's history.<ref name=\"ERG\"/><ref name=SJ>{{cite news |url= http://www.statesmanjournal.com/article/20090921/UPDATE/90921014 |title= Brooke Wilberger's remains found in coastal range, killer sentenced to life in prison |newspaper= [[Statesman Journal]] |location= [[Salem, Oregon]] |date= September 21, 2009 |accessdate= September 22, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBrooke Wilberger was born in [[Fresno, California|Fresno]], [[California]], on February 20, 1985 to Greg and Cammy Wilberger. She had three sisters and two brothers.<ref name=\"Register-Guard\" /> Described as a devout member of the [[Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]], Wilberger was a graduate of [[Elmira High School]] near [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]], [[Oregon]].<ref name=\"amw\"/> She had just completed her [[freshman]] year at [[Brigham Young University]] in [[Provo, Utah]], at the time of her abduction.<ref name=\"amw\">{{cite web|title=Authorities Charge Man With Murder |url=http://www.amw.com/missing_persons/case.cfm?id=27071 |work=[[America's Most Wanted]] |accessdate=April 13, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026002230/http://www.amw.com/missing_persons/case.cfm?id=27071 |archivedate=October 26, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name=abcnewsrecov>{{cite news\n|title=Brooke Wilberger found: Killer gives location of remains to avoid death penalty\n|website=[[ABC News]]\n|publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company]]\n|location=New York City\n|first1=Dean\n|last1=Schabner\n|first2=Sarah \n|last2=Netter\n|date=September 21, 2009\n|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/remains-brooke-wilberger-found-years-disappearance/story?id=8632233\n}}</ref> During that time, her boyfriend, Justin Blake, was serving as a [[Mormon missionary]] in [[Venezuela]].<ref name=\"20/20\">{{cite news\n|title=Vanished: Two coeds, two horrifying mysteries\n|first=Donna\n|last=Hunter\n|date=August 14, 2008\n|work=[[20/20 (US television show)|20/20]]\n|publisher=[[ABC News]]\n|location=New York City\n|url=http://abcnews.go.com/2020/Story?id=5578937\n}}</ref>\n\n==Disappearance==\nAt the time of her disappearance, Wilberger was on summer vacation, visiting and working for one of her sisters in [[Corvallis, Oregon]].<ref name=\"Register-Guard\">{{cite news|title=Waiting for Brooke|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Waiting+for+Brooke.-a0132784667|newspaper=[[The Register-Guard]]|publisher=GateHouse Media|location=Eugene, Oregon|accessdate=March 18, 2017|date=May 24, 2005}}</ref> On the morning May 24, 2004, Wilberger was last seen cleaning [[lamp post]]s in the parking lot of the Oak Park Apartments, which her sister and brother-in-law managed, on the edge of the [[Oregon State University]] campus.<ref>{{cite web | title=Suspect Charged With Murder Of Brooke Wilberger | work=[[KUTV.com]] |url=http://kutv.com/topstories/local_story_214201808.html |accessdate=April 13, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926211903/http://kutv.com/topstories/local_story_214201808.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = September 26, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Crime Alert Archive|url=https://fa.oregonstate.edu/book/export/html/3793|website=fa.oregonstate.edu|publisher=[[Oregon State University]]|accessdate=March 18, 2017|language=en|date=August 3, 2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319111949/https://fa.oregonstate.edu/book/export/html/3793|archivedate=March 19, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\n===Initial efforts===\n[[Image:Brooke-salem.jpg|thumb|A billboard in [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]] requesting information on Brooke Wilberger.]]\nWhen Wilberger disappeared, the police began investigating immediately \u2013 against normal procedure. Lt. Ron Noble of the Corvallis Police Department said, \"Normally, we would wait. Because adults can come and go as they please, and we would normally wait to see if she showed up maybe the next day.\" However, in this case, police officials agreed with the family that Wilberger was not the type of girl to disappear on her own.<ref name=\"20/20\"/> The Wilbergers' [[Ward (LDS Church)|LDS ward]] organized a search by citizens of Corvallis.<ref name=\"20/20\"/>\n\nThe investigation initially centered on Sung Koo Kim, who was named as \"[[person of interest]]\" in the disappearance. Kim was later dropped as a suspect, but received an 11-year prison sentence for multiple counts of [[burglary]] and theft of women's personal property in [[Yamhill County, Oregon|Yamhill County]], crimes uncovered while he was being investigated for the Wilberger disappearance.<ref>{{cite web\n|title=Sung Koo Kim gets nearly six years for underwear thefts\n| work=[[KATU.com]] \n| url=http://www.katu.com/news/3651561.html\n|accessdate=April 13, 2007\n}}</ref> He was released in December 2012 after serving about seven years.\n\n===Joel Patrick Courtney===\nOn November 30, 2004, a [[University of New Mexico]] [[foreign exchange student]] was beaten and [[rape]]d before escaping and identified Joel Patrick Courtney as her attacker. On September 12, 2007, Courtney pleaded guilty to the attack. Courtney's [[plea agreement]] called for a prison sentence of up to 18 years, plus 5 to 20 years on [[parole]].<ref name=\"KVAL\">{{cite news|title=DA: 'His intent was that no one ever find her'|url=http://www.kval.com/news/local/60012167.html|accessdate=March 18, 2017|work=[[KVAL.com]]|publisher=[[Sinclair Broadcasting|Sinclair Interactive Media]]|location=Corvallis, Oregon|date=September 21, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530125345/http://www.kval.com/news/local/60012167.html|archivedate=May 30, 2015|language=en}}</ref>\n\nPolice eventually linked Courtney, a native of [[Beaverton, Oregon]], to Wilberger's disappearance. In August 2005, he was charged on 19 counts of [[aggravated murder]], [[kidnapping]], [[sexual abuse]], rape and [[sodomy]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Joel Patrick Courtney, serial killer & rapist |url=http://www.crimelibrary.com/serial_killers/predators/joel_courtney/1.html |website=[[Crime Library]]|publisher=[[TruTV]]|location=Atlanta, Georgia|accessdate=March 8, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060303133837/http://www.crimelibrary.com/serial_killers/predators/joel_courtney/1.html |archivedate=March 3, 2006 }}</ref> Court documents released in 2008 revealed details showing that Courtney was in Corvallis when Wilberger disappeared and that a green van he was driving was spotted by several people, including an OSU employee who identified him from a photo lineup.<ref>{{cite news\n|title = Suspect's van seen in Corvallis|first = William|last = McCall|newspaper=[[Deseret News]]|publisher=[[Deseret News Publishing Company]]|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|date = April 19, 2008|url = http://www.deseretnews.com/article/695271843/Suspects-van-seen-in-Corvallis.html|access-date = June 22, 2015|agency= [[Associated Press]]}}</ref> Officials said that Wilberger's [[DNA]] was found inside the van, along with her hair.<ref>{{Cite news|title = Slain BYU student's Ore. mother grateful case over|url = http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2009/09/22/slain_byu_students_ore_mother_grateful_case_over/|website= [[Boston.com]]|agency = [[Associated Press]] |date = September 22, 2009|access-date = June 22, 2015|first = William|last = McCall}}</ref>\n\nCourtney was [[Extradition|extradited]] to [[Benton County, Oregon]] on April 8, 2008.<ref name=\"kval.com\">\n{{cite news\n|title       = Joel Courtney arrives in Oregon to face charges in Wilberger murder\n|work        = [[KVAL-TV]]\n|date        = April 8, 2008\n|location    = Corvallis, Oregon\n|accessdate  = March 18, 2017\n|url-status     = dead \n|url         = http://www.kval.com/news/local/17403709.html\n|archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20150530143017/http://www.kval.com/news/local/17403709.html\n|archivedate = May 30, 2015\n}}</ref> He was scheduled for his first appearance on April 9, 2008, at the Benton County Courthouse,<ref name=\"Oregon Live\">\n{{cite news\n|last1       =Jung\n|first1      =Helen\n|title       =Twists and turns in the Brooke Wilberger case\n|url         =http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/09/twists_and_turns_in_the_brooke.html\n|accessdate  =March 18, 2017\n|work        =OregonLive.com\n|publisher   =Oregon Live LLC.\n|date        =September 21, 2009\n|language    =en\n}}</ref>\nfacing 14 counts including aggravated murder, two counts of kidnapping and single counts of rape, sodomy and sexual abuse in connection with Wilberger's disappearance. Charges were filed despite the absence of the body of the alleged victim at the time; the [[prosecutor]] in the case announced that he would seek the [[death penalty]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n|title        =Effort begins to extradite Wilberger murder suspect\n|url          =http://www.katu.com/news/12446241.html\n|accessdate   =March 18, 2017\n|agency       =Associated Press\n|publisher    =Sinclair Interactive Media, LLC\n|date         =December 12, 2007\n|archiveurl   =https://web.archive.org/web/20150622132234/http://www.katu.com/news/12446241.html\n|archivedate  =June 22, 2015\n|location     =CORVALLIS, Ore.\n|language     =en\n}}\n</ref> The [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] had briefly considered Courtney a suspect in two to three disappearances under investigation, but have since eliminated him as a suspect.<ref>{{cite news\n|title        =FBI drops Joel Courtney as suspect in two cases\n|date         =February 23, 2006 \n|agency       =Associated Press\n|publisher    =[[KATU]]\n|first        =Joseph B.\n|last         =Frazier\n|url          =http://www.katu.com/news/3643546.html\n|accessdate   =March 18, 2017\n|url-status      =dead\n|archiveurl   =https://web.archive.org/web/20140502004237/http://www.katu.com/news/3643546.html\n|archivedate  = May 2, 2014\n|location     = Portland, Ore.\n}}</ref>\n\nIt was revealed through court [[Deposition (law)|deposition]] and Courtney's [[confession]] that he had abducted Wilberger from the Oak Park Apartments parking lot on the morning of May 24, 2004. He then drove her into the woods outside of town. He returned to town to buy food while he still had Wilberger bound in his van. According to Courtney, he kept her alive throughout the night before raping her the next morning. He then bludgeoned her to death when she tried to fight off the rape.<ref name=\"ERG\">{{cite news|url=http://www.registerguard.com/csp/cms/sites/web/updates/20477444-55/story.csp|title=Killer's guilty plea brings family closure|last=Moran|first=Jack|date=September 22, 2009|newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard|accessdate=September 22, 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Conviction====\nCourtney's attorneys worked towards a trial, as well as towards a speedier resolution. The trial was set for February 1, 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazettetimes.com/news/local/article_fb0d255e-ffc4-5673-9668-f0848e3b1117.html|title=Courtney headed for trial|last=Booth|first=Michael|date=September 5, 2009|newspaper=Corvallis Gazette-Times|accessdate=September 22, 2009}}</ref> He was expected to be charged in connection with the unrelated kidnapping, attempted [[sexual assault]] and attempted murder of two [[Oregon State University]] students, the same day Wilberger went missing.<ref name=\"kval.com\" />\n\nOn September 21, 2009, Courtney pleaded guilty to aggravated murder, the only crime subject to [[capital punishment in Oregon]], and was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] without the possibility of parole.<ref>{{cite web | last=Netter | first=Sarah | work=ABC News | title=Brooke Wilberger Found: Killer Gives Location of Remains to Avoid Death Penalty | url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/remains-brooke-wilberger-found-years-disappearance/story?id=8632233 |accessdate=September 21, 2009}}</ref> The deal spared Courtney from the death penalty, in exchange for providing information about the location of Wilberger's body.<ref name=\"ERG\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=To Avoid Death Penalty, Joel Courtney Reveals Location of Student Brooke Wilberger's Body - True Crime Report|url=http://www.truecrimereport.com/2009/09/to_avoid_death_penalty_joel_co.php|website=True Crime Report|accessdate=March 18, 2017|date=September 22, 2009}}</ref> In addition, the deal also called for Courtney to be imprisoned in his home state, [[New Mexico]], instead of Oregon where the crime was committed.\n\nThe Benton County [[District Attorney]] announced the recovery of Wilberger's body (without specifics or its location) in a press conference the day of Courtney's confession.<ref>{{cite news\n|title= Wilberger's remains recovered; Courtney pleads guilty to murder\n|first=Rachel\n|last=Beck\n|date=September 22, 2009\n|work=Corvallis Gazette-Times\n|url=http://www.gazettetimes.com/news/local/article_0ffadf0e-a70d-11de-bfd1-001cc4c03286.html\n}}</ref> It was later revealed that her remains had been concealed in the woods on an abandoned [[logging road]] between [[Blodgett, Oregon|Blodgett]] and [[Wren, Oregon|Wren]],<ref>{{cite web|work=Albany Democrat-Herald|url=http://democratherald.com/news/local/authorities-finish-recovering-remains-of-brooke-wilberger/article_9749f61e-addb-11de-94f9-001cc4c03286.html|title=Authorities finish recovering remains of Brooke Wilberger|date=September 30, 2009|location=Albany, Ore.|author=Beck, Rachel|accessdate=November 11, 2017}}</ref> located in the [[Central Oregon Coast Range|Oregon Coast Range]].<ref name=SJ/><ref>{{cite news|title=BREAKING NEWS: Press Conference - Brooke Wilberger's Remains Found |date=September 22, 2009 |first=Sabina |last=Rosu-Urdes |url=http://kezi.com/news/local/141973 |work=KEZI |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090925152340/http://kezi.com/news/local/141973 |archivedate=September 25, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Media coverage==\nThe Wilberger case was covered several times on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] television program ''[[America's Most Wanted]]'' between 2004 and 2006.<ref>\n{{Cite web\n|title        =America's Most Wanted {{!}} Missing Persons {{!}} Brooke Wilberger Case \n|url          =http://www.amw.com/missing_persons/case.cfm?id=27071 \n|date         =September 21, 2009 \n|accessdate   =June 22, 2015 \n|url-status      =dead \n|archiveurl   =https://web.archive.org/web/20120323015746/http://www.amw.com/missing_persons/case.cfm?id=27071 \n|archivedate  =March 23, 2012 |df=mdy \n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|title         =America's Most Wanted {{!}} Missing Data File for Brooke Carol Wilberger\n|url           =http://www2.amw.com/missing_persons/case.cfm?id=27071\n|accessdate    =March 19, 2017\n|archiveurl    =https://web.archive.org/web/20060327062207/http://www2.amw.com/missing_persons/case.cfm?id=27071\n|archivedate   =March 27, 2006\n}}</ref> ''[[The Montel Williams Show]]'' interviewed three of Wilberger's siblings, Shannon, Spencer and Jessica, which aired November 29, 2004.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title       =\"The Montel Williams Show\" {{!}} Vanished Without a Trace (TV Episode 2004)\n|url         =https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5900516/\n|website     =Internet Movie Database (IMDb)\n|accessdate  =March 19, 2017\n|date        =November 29, 2004\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|title        =CBS Television Distribution - Best of Montel\n|url          =http://www.montelshow.com/show/upcoming_detail.htm?index=0\n|website      =www.montelshow.com\n|accessdate   =March 19, 2017\n|archiveurl   =https://web.archive.org/web/20041205003616/http://www.montelshow.com/show/upcoming_detail.htm?index=0\n|archivedate  =December 5, 2004\n|date         =November 29, 2004\n}}</ref> The [[ABC News]] program ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'' examined Wilberger's disappearance along with that of [[Disappearance of Maura Murray|Maura Murray]] on March 17, 2006.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|title        =20/20 {{!}} Vanished: Two Coeds, Two Horrifying Mysteries\n|url          =http://abcnews.go.com/2020/story?id=1734155&page=1\n|accessdate   =March 19, 2017\n|work         =20/20\n|publisher    =ABC News\n|date         =  March 17, 2006\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|title        =20/20 {{!}} Vanished: Two Coeds, Two Horrifying Mysteries\n|url          =https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2370114/?ref_=ttep_ep2\n|website      =Internet Movie Database (IMDb)\n|accessdate   =  March 16, 2017\n|date         =March 17, 2006\n}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Investigation Discovery]] Channel portrayed the Wilberger story on three different series:\n{{bulleted list\n|The first showing was on the crime examination series \"[[On the Case with Paula Zahn]]\", Season 1, Episode 14 ''Beauty and the Beast'' first aired: April 18, 2010.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title        =On the Case With Paula Zahn {{!}} Beauty and the Beast\n|url          =http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/on-the-case-with-paula-zahn/episode-14-season-1/beauty-and-the-beast/298996/\n|website      =TVGuide.com\n|accessdate   =March 18, 2017\n|language     =en\n|date         =April 18, 2010\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n |title       = One the Case with Paula Zahn {{!}} Beauty and the Beast\n |url         = http://www.investigationdiscovery.com/tv-shows/on-the-case-with-paula-zahn/videos/on-the-case-with-paula-zahn-season-2-beauty-and-the-beast/\n |website     = Investigation Discovery\n |accessdate  = March 18, 2017\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170319111422/http://www.investigationdiscovery.com/tv-shows/on-the-case-with-paula-zahn/videos/on-the-case-with-paula-zahn-season-2-beauty-and-the-beast/\n |archivedate = March 19, 2017\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n|The second showing was on the documentary series \"FBI: Criminal Pursuit\", titled  ''Predator'', Season 2, Episode 10, original air date April 29, 2011.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title        =FBI: Criminal Pursuit {{!}} Predator\n|url          =https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1875293/?ref_=ttrel_rel_tt\n|publisher    =Investigation Discovery\n|accessdate   =March 18, 2017\n|date         =April 29, 2011\n}}</ref>\n|The third documentary was the Season 5, Episode 5, titled: ''An Angel Taken'', of the series \"Motives & Murders: Cracking The Case\", premiered March 31, 2016.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title         =Motives & Murders: Cracking the Case {{!}} An Angel Taken\n|url           =http://www.investigationdiscoverygo.com/motives-murders-cracking-the-case/\n|website       =Investigation Discovery\n|accessdate    =March 18, 2017\n|language      =en-us\n|date          =March 31, 2016\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|title         =Motives & Murders: Cracking The Case {{!}} An Angel Taken\n|url           =http://mytvee.ga/episodes/13364/motives_and_murders_cracking_the_case_s6_e5\n|website       =mytvee.ga\n|accessdate    =March 18, 2017\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''[[Dateline NBC]]'' aired a two-hour special on the case on February 4, 2011.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|last1        =Raskauskas\n|first1       =Nancy\n|title        =Brooke Wilberger back in TV spotlight\n|url          =http://www.gazettetimes.com/news/local/brooke-wilberger-back-in-tv-spotlight/article_e0372760-2dbf-11e0-8c00-001cc4c002e0.html\n|accessdate   =March 18, 2017\n|work         =Corvallis Gazette Times\n|publisher    =Gazette Times\n|date         =January 31, 2011\n|language     =en\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n|title        =Full Episode: Bringing Brooke Home\n|url          =http://www.nbcnews.com/dateline/video/full-episode--bringing-brooke-home-515002435992\n|accessdate   =March 18, 2017\n|work         =NBC News\n|language     =en\n}}</ref> The [[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]] channel documentary series ''It Takes A Killer'' also covered the case on January 6, 2017.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title         =In Search of a Kill\n|url           =http://www.oxygen.com/it-takes-a-killer/season-1/in-search-of-a-kill\n|website       =Oxygen Official Site\n|accessdate    =March 18, 2017\n|date          =January 6, 2017\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|title         =Shows A-Z - It Takes A Killer on Oxygen {{!}} TheFutonCritic.com\n|url           =http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/it-takes-a-killer/listings/\n|website       =www.thefutoncritic.com\n|accessdate    =March 18, 2017\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|title         =Brooke Wilberger\n|url           =http://wn.com/brooke_wilberger\n|website       =World News\n|accessdate    =March 19, 2017\n|language      =en\n}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of solved missing persons cases]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.inarchive.com/com/a/amw.com/7941/2011-11-13-description/74/AMW_Report_a_Tip_Brooke_Wilberger/ America's Most Wanted {{!}} Brooke Wilberger] at inarchive.com\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140403043410/http://www.crimelibrary.com/serial_killers/predators/joel_courtney/1.html Joel Courtney Predator Writing] at crimelibrary.com (archived)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilberger, Brooke}}\n[[Category:2004 in Oregon]]\n[[Category:2004 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Corvallis, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Deaths by beating in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by person in the United States]]\n[[Category:Incidents of violence against women]]\n[[Category:Kidnappings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Murder in Oregon]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murder_of_Brooke_Wilberger"}
{"title_page": "2009\u201310 FIS Cross-Country World Cup", "text_new": "{{Infobox Double Wintersport World Cup\n| title=<!--[[File:F\u00e9d\u00e9ration internationale de ski (logo).svg|28px]]--> 2009\u201310 FIS Cross-Country World Cup\n| competition1=Overall\n| competition1men= {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Petter Northug]]\n| competition1ladies= {{flagicon|POL}} [[Justyna Kowalczyk]] <small>(2nd title)</small>\n| competition2=Distance\n| competition2men= {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Petter Northug]]\n| competition2ladies= {{flagicon|POL}} [[Justyna Kowalczyk]]\n| competition3=Sprint\n| competition3men= {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Emil J\u00f6nsson]]\n| competition3ladies= {{flagicon|POL}} [[Justyna Kowalczyk]] \n| competition4=Nations Cup\n| competition4men= {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Norway]]\n| competition4ladies= {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Norway]]\n| mixedcompetition1=Nations Cup Overall\n| mixedcompetition1both={{flagicon|NOR}} [[Norway]]\n| stageevent1=[[2009\u201310 Tour de Ski|Tour de Ski]]\n| stageevent1men={{flagicon|CZE}} [[Luk\u00e1\u0161 Bauer]]\n| stageevent1ladies={{flagicon|POL}} [[Justyna Kowalczyk]]\n| stageevent2=World Cup Final\n| stageevent2men={{flagicon|NOR}} [[Petter Northug]]\n| stageevent2ladies={{flagicon|NOR}} [[Marit Bj\u00f8rgen]]\n| menlocations=18 venues\n| ladieslocations=18 venues\n| menindividual=30 events\n| ladiesindividual=30 events\n| relaymen=4 events\n| relayladies=4 events\n| previous=[[2008\u201309 FIS Cross-Country World Cup|2008\u201309]]\n| next=[[2010\u201311 FIS Cross-Country World Cup|2010\u201311]]\n}}\nThe '''2009\u201310 FIS Cross-Country World Cup''' was a multi-race tournament over the season for cross-country skiers. It was the 29th official [[FIS Cross-Country World Cup|World Cup]] season in [[cross-country skiing (sport)|cross-country skiing]] for men and ladies. The season started 21 November 2009 in [[Beitost\u00f8len]], [[Norway]] and ended on 21 March 2010 in [[Falun]], [[Sweden]]. The World Cup was organised by the [[International Ski Federation|FIS]] who also run world cups and championships in [[ski jumping]], [[snowboarding]] and [[alpine skiing]] amongst others. A new website was created by the FIS for Cross-country skiing fan that was released the week of 16 November 2009.\n\n== Calendar ==\nBoth men's and women's events tended to be held at the same resorts over a 2 or 3 day period. Listed below is a list of races which equates with the points table further down this page.\n\nThe [[Tour de Ski]] was a series of events which count towards the World Cup. This started in [[Oberhof, Germany|Oberhof]] and ended in [[Val di Fiemme]].\n\n=== Men ===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"1\" style=\"background:#fff; font-size:86%; line-height:16px; border:grey solid 1px; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n|+ Key: C \u2013 Classic / F \u2013 Freestyle\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#ccc; width=20 px;\"|{{Abbr|WC|World Cup}}\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#ccc; width=30 px;\"|{{Abbr|Stage|Stage event at Tours counts only half points}}\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#ccc; width:120px;\"|Date\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#ccc; width:120px;\"|Place\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#ccc; width:120px;\"|Discipline\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#ccc; width:200px;\"|Winner\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#ccc; width:200px;\"|Second\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#ccc; width:200px;\"|Third\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#ccc; width:200px;\"|Yellow bib\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#ccc; width:10px;\" |{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}} \n|-\n| align=center|1\n| align=center|1\n| align=right|21 November 2009 &nbsp;\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Beitost\u00f8len]]\n| align=right|15&nbsp;km F &nbsp;\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ronny Hafs\u00e5s]]|NOR}}\n| {{flagathlete|[[Vincent Vittoz]]|FRA}}\n| {{flagathlete|[[Matti Heikkinen]]|FIN}}\n|\n| <ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20091121070749/http://www.fis-ski.com/uk/604/610.html?sector=CC&raceid=16143 FIS Cross-Country Skiing World Cup Beitost\u00f8len 21 November 2009 men's 15 km individual freestyle results.] - accessed 21 November 2009.</ref>\n|-\n| align=center|2\n| align=center|2\n| align=right|28 November 2009 &nbsp;\n| {{flagicon|FIN}} [[Kuusamo]]\n| align=right|Sprint C &nbsp;\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ola Vigen Hattestad]]|NOR}}\n| {{flagathlete|[[\u00d8ystein Pettersen]]|NOR}}\n| {{flagathlete|[[Nikita Kryukov]]|RUS}}\n|\n| <ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20091130032326/http://www.fis-ski.com/uk/604/610.html?sector=CC&raceid=16149 FIS Cross-Country Skiing World Cup Kussamo 28 November 2009 men's sprint classic results.] - accessed 28 November 2009.</ref>\n|-\n| align=center|3\n| align=center|3\n| align=right|29 November 2009 &nbsp;\n| {{flagicon|FIN}} [[Kuusamo]]\n| align=right|15&nbsp;km C &nbsp;\n| {{flagathlete|[[Petter Northug]]|NOR}}\n| {{flagathlete|[[Maxim Vylegzhanin]]|RUS}}\n| {{flagathlete|[[Alexander Legkov]]|RUS}}\n|\n| <ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20091130032337/http://www.fis-ski.com/uk/604/610.html?sector=CC&raceid=16151 FIS Cross-Country Skiing World Cup Kuusamo 29 November 2009 men's 15 km individual classic results.] - accessed 29 November 2009.</ref>\n|-\n| align=center|4\n| align=center|4\n| align=right|5 December 2009 &nbsp;\n| {{flagicon|GER}} [[D\u00fcsseldorf]]\n| align=right|Sprint F &nbsp;\n| {{flagathlete|[[Alexey Petukhov]]|RUS}}\n| {{flagathlete|[[Anders Gl\u00f8ersen]]|NOR}}\n| {{flagathlete|[[Eirik Brandsdal]]|NOR}}\n|\n| <ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20091208102529/http://www.fis-ski.com/uk/604/610.html?sector=CC&raceid=16155 FIS Cross-Country Skiing World Cup D\u00fcsseldorf 5 December 2009 men's sprint freestyle results.] - accessed 5 December 2009.</ref>\n|-\n| align=center|5\n| align=center|5\n| align=right|12 December 2009 &nbsp;\n| {{flagicon|SUI}} [[Davos]]\n| align=right|15&nbsp;km F &nbsp;\n| {{flagathlete|[[Matti Heikkinen]]|FIN}}\n| {{flagathlete|[[Marcus Hellner]]|SWE}}\n| {{fl