\n| 6 || align=\"left\"| {{POL}} ||align=right|2155\n|-align=\"center\"\n| 7 || align=\"left\"| {{SLO}} ||align=right|1890\n|-align=\"center\"\n| 8 || align=\"left\"| {{GER}} ||align=right|1855\n|-align=\"center\"\n| 9 || align=\"left\"| {{FRA}} ||align=right|613\n|-align=\"center\"\n| 10 || align=\"left\"| {{KAZ}} ||align=right|531\n|}\n|}\n\n\n==Points distribution==\nThe table shows the number of points won in the 2009\u201310 Cross-Country Skiing World Cup for men and women.\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border:1px solid #C0C0C0; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:86%; margin-top:1em; text-align:center\" width=\"1000\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\"\n| width=150|'''Place'''\n| width=32|1 || width=32|2 || width=32|3 || width=32|4 || width=32|5 || width=32|6 || width=32|7 || width=32|8 || width=32|9 || width=32|10 || width=32|11 || width=32|12 || width=32|13 || width=32|14 || width=32|15 || width=32|16 || width=32|17 || width=32|18 || width=32|19 || width=32|20 || width=32|21 || width=32|22 || width=32|23 || width=32|24 || width=32|25 || width=32|26 || width=32|27 || width=32|28 || width=32|29 || width=32|30 \n|-\n| colspan=31|\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" align=left| '''Individual'''\n| rowspan=2|100 || rowspan=2|80 || rowspan=2|60 || rowspan=2|50 || rowspan=2|45 || rowspan=2|40 || rowspan=2|36 || rowspan=2|32 || rowspan=2|29 || rowspan=2|26 || rowspan=2|24 || rowspan=2|22 || rowspan=2|20 || rowspan=2|18 || rowspan=2|16 || rowspan=2|15 || rowspan=2|14 || rowspan=2|13 || rowspan=2|12 || rowspan=2|11 || rowspan=2|10 || rowspan=2|9 || rowspan=2|8 || rowspan=2|7 || rowspan=2|6 || rowspan=2|5 || rowspan=2|4 || rowspan=2|3 || rowspan=2|2 || rowspan=2|1 \n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" align=left| '''Team Sprint'''\n|-\n| colspan=31|\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" align=left| '''World Cup Final'''\n| rowspan=2|200 || rowspan=2|160 || rowspan=2|120 || rowspan=2|100 || rowspan=2|90 || rowspan=2|80 || rowspan=2|72 || rowspan=2|64 || rowspan=2|58 || rowspan=2|52 || rowspan=2|48 || rowspan=2|44 || rowspan=2|40 || rowspan=2|36 || rowspan=2|32 || rowspan=2|30 || rowspan=2|28 || rowspan=2|26 || rowspan=2|24 || rowspan=2|22 || rowspan=2|20 || rowspan=2|18 || rowspan=2|16 || rowspan=2|14 || rowspan=2|12 || rowspan=2|10 || rowspan=2|8 || rowspan=2|6 || rowspan=2|4 || rowspan=2|2 \n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" align=left| '''Relay'''\n|-\n| colspan=31|\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" align=left| '''Tour de Ski''' \n| 400 || 320 || 240 || 200 || 180 || 160 || 144 || 128 || 116 || 104 || 96 || 88 || 80 || 72 || 64 || 60 || 56 || 52 || 48 || 44 || 40 || 36 || 32 || 28 || 24 || 20 || 16 || 12 || 8 || 4 \n|-\n| colspan=31|\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" align=left| '''Stage Tour de Ski'''\n| rowspan=2|50 || rowspan=2|46 || rowspan=2|43 || rowspan=2|40 || rowspan=2|37 || rowspan=2|34 || rowspan=2|32 || rowspan=2|30 || rowspan=2|28 || rowspan=2|26 || rowspan=2|24 || rowspan=2|22 || rowspan=2|20 || rowspan=2|18 || rowspan=2|16 || rowspan=2|15 || rowspan=2|14 || rowspan=2|13 || rowspan=2|12 || rowspan=2|11 || rowspan=2|10 || rowspan=2|9 || rowspan=2|8 || rowspan=2|7 || rowspan=2|6 || rowspan=2|5 || rowspan=2|4 || rowspan=2|3 || rowspan=2|2 || rowspan=2|1 \n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" align=left| '''Stage World Cup Final'''\n|}\n\nA skier's best results in all distance races and sprint races counts towards the overall World Cup totals.\n\nAll distance races, included individual stages in Tour de Ski and in World Cup Final (which counts as 50% of a normal race), count towards the distance standings. All sprint races, including the sprint races during the Tour de Ski and the first race of the World Cup final (which counts as 50% of a normal race), count towards the sprint standings.\n\nThe Nations Cup ranking is calculated by adding each country's individual competitors' scores and scores from team events. Relay events count double (see World Cup final positions), with only one team counting towards the total, while in team sprint events two teams contribute towards the total, with the usual World Cup points (100 to winning team, etc.) awarded.\n\n==Achievements==\n\n;First World Cup career victory:\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Men\n*{{flagathlete|[[Ronny Hafs\u00e5s]]|NOR}}, 24, in his 2nd season \u2013 the WC 1 (15 km F) in Beitost\u00f8len; also first podium\n*{{flagathlete|[[John Kristian Dahl]]|NOR}}, 28, in his 10th season \u2013 the WC 6 (Sprint F) in Davos; first podium was 2003-04 WC 5 (Sprint C) in Val di Fiemme\n*{{flagathlete|[[Daniel Rickardsson]]|SWE}}, 27, in his 8th season \u2013 the WC 14 (10 km C) in Toblach; also first podium \n*{{flagathlete|[[Artem Zhmurko]]|RUS}}, 24, in his 4th season \u2013 the WC 20 (30 km Skiathlon) in Rybinsk; also first podium\n* {{flagathlete|[[Maurice Manificat]]|FRA}}, 23, in his 4th season \u2013 the WC 23 (30 km Skiathlon) in Lahti; first podium was 2009-10 WC 5 (15 km F) in Davos\n* {{flagathlete|[[Giorgio Di Centa]]|ITA}}, 37, in his 17th season \u2013 the WC 21 (15 km F) in Canmore; first podium was 1996-97 WC 8 (15 km F) in Hakuba\n* {{flagathlete|[[Nikita Kriukov]]|RUS}}, 24, in his 5th season \u2013 the WC 27 (Sprint C) in Stockholm; first podium was 2009-10 WC 2 (Sprint C) in Kuusamo\n{{col-2}}\n;Women\n*{{flagathlete|[[Hanna Falk]]|SWE}}, 20, in her 2nd season \u2013 the WC 4 (Sprint F) in D\u00fcsseldorf; also first podium \n*{{flagathlete|[[Irina Khazova]]|RUS}}, 25, in her 6th season \u2013 the WC 5 (10 km F) in Davos; first podium was 2009-10 WC 3 (10 km C) in Kuusamo\n*{{flagathlete|[[Vesna Fabjan]]|SLO}}, 24, in her 6th season \u2013 the WC 19 (Sprint F) in Rybinsk\n{{col-end}}\n\n\n;First World Cup podium:\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Men\n*{{flagathlete|[[Ronny Hafs\u00e5s]]|NOR}}, 24, in his 2nd season \u2013 no. 1 in the WC 1 (15 km F) in Beitost\u00f8len\n*{{flagathlete|[[Maxim Vylegzhanin]]|RUS}}, 27, in his 6th season \u2013 no. 2 in the WC 3 (15 km C) in Kuusamo\n*{{flagathlete|[[Daniel Rickardsson]]|SWE}}, 27, in his 8th season \u2013 no. 1 in