t places\n* {{flagathlete|[[Petra Majdi\u010d]]|SLO}}, 4 (20) first places\n* {{flagathlete|[[Charlotte Kalla]]|SWE}}, 2 (7) first places\n* {{flagathlete|[[Hanna Falk]]|SWE}}, 2 (2) first places\n* {{flagathlete|[[Arianna Follis]]|ITA}}, 1 (6) first place\n* {{flagathlete|[[Kristin St\u00f8rmer Steira]]|NOR}}, 1 (5) first place\n* {{flagathlete|[[Aino-Kaisa Saarinen]]|FIN}}, 1 (4) first place\n* {{flagathlete|[[Natalia Korosteleva]]|RUS}}, 1 (2) first place\n* {{flagathlete|[[Anna Olsson (skier)|Anna Olsson]]|SWE}}, 1 (2) first place\n* {{flagathlete|[[Irina Khazova]]|RUS}}, 1 (1) first place\n* {{flagathlete|[[Vesna Fabjan]]|SLO}}, 1 (1) first place\n{{col-end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091122205400/http://www.fis-ski.com/data/document/cal-cc09-10.pdf 2009-10 World Cup schedule, including Tour de Ski.] - accessed 10 November 2009\n*[http://www.fiscrosscountry.com/ FIS Cross-Country official website.] - accessed 19 November 2009.\n\n{{FIS Cross-Country World Cup seasons}}\n{{Wintersport season 2009\u201310}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2009-10 FIS Cross-Country World Cup}}\n[[Category:2009\u201310 FIS Cross-Country World Cup| ]]\n[[Category:2009 in cross-country skiing|World Cup 2009-10]]\n[[Category:2010 in cross-country skiing|World Cup 2009-10]]\n[[Category:FIS Cross-Country World Cup seasons]]\n", "name_user": "Reitimwinkl", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAchievements", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2009%E2%80%9310_FIS_Cross-Country_World_Cup"}
{"title_page": "Mariane Bargiel", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mariane Bargiel\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Mariane Tromlitz\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|df=y|1797|05|17}}\n| birth_place        = [[Greiz]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|1872|03|10|1797|05|17}}\n| death_place        = Berlin\n| other_names        = Mariane Wieck  \n| occupation         = {{plainlist|\n* Pianist\n* Soprano\n* Piano teacher\n}}\n| organization       = \n| spouses            = {{plainlist|\n* {{Marriage|[[Friedrich Wieck]]|1816|1825|reason=divorce}}\n* {{Marriage|Adolph Bargiel|1825|1836|reason=death}}\n}}\n| children           = [[Clara Schumann]]\n| relatives          = \n}}\n\n'''Mariane Bargiel''', n\u00e8e '''Tromlitz''', divorced '''Wieck''', also '''Marianne''' (17 May 1797 \u2013 10 March 1872) was a German pianist, [[soprano]] and piano teacher. She is known as the mother of [[Clara Schumann]].\n\n== Life ==\nBorn Mariane Tromlitz in [[Greiz]], she was the first child of Christian Gotthold Tromlitz (1765\u20131825), a church musician, music teacher and composer, and his wife Christiana Friederica n\u00e8e Carl (1766\u20131830). Her siblings were Georg Wilhelm (1799\u20131801) and Emilie (1802\u20131885). Her grandfather was the notable flutist and flute builder [[Johann George Tromlitz]]. She received first musical training from her father, and then studied with [[Friedrich Wieck]]. In her first public concert at age 15 at the Gesellschaftshaus (society hall) in [[Plauen]], she played the piano quartet by [[Anton Eberl]].<ref name=\"Bergmann\">Hanna Bergmann: [https://www.sophie-drinker-institut.de/bargiel-marianne Bargiel, Marianne, geb. Tromlitz, verh. Wieck, verh. Bargiel] in Online-Lexikon Europ\u00e4ische Instrumentalistinnen des 18. und 19. Jahrhunderts. Sophie-Drinker-Institut 2009, retrieved 25 November 2019.</ref>\n\nOn 23 June 1816, she married her teacher Friedrich Wieck in [[Plauen|Oberlosa]], [[Vogtland]]. The lived in [[Leipzig]]. During the first years, she appeared successfully as a pianist and singer, and worked as a piano teacher. The couple had five children, Adelheid (1817\u20131819), [[Clara Schumann|Clara Josephine]] (1819\u20131896), {{ill|Alwin Wieck|de|lt=Alwin}}, Gustav (1823\u20131884) and Victor (1824\u20131826).<ref name=\"Bergmann\" />\n\nShe left her husband on May 1824, and first returned to her parents, with Clara, then age 4 1/2, and Victor, a baby of three months. They were divorced on 22 January 1825. As the father customarily held custody of the children, Clara could stay with her mother only until age five, and lived from 17 September 1824 with her father in Leipzig.<ref name=\"Bergmann\" /><ref name=sp>Schumann-Portal: [https://www.schumann-portal.de/mariane-bargiel-mutter.html Mariane Wieck-Bargiel geb. Tromlitz (1797\u20131872), Mutter von Clara Schumann], retrieved 25 November 2019</ref>\n\nShe married {{ill|Adolph Bargiel|de}}, a piano and voice teacher, in August 1825, and they moved to Berlin in 1826. He became director of a musical academy there, founded by [[Johann Bernhard Logier]], where she also taught. The couple had four children, [[Woldemar Bargiel|Woldemar]], Eugen (1830\u20131907), C\u00e4cilie (1832\u20131910) and Clementine (1835\u20131869).<ref name=\"Bergmann\" />\nMariane Bargiel is listed as a soprano of the [[Sing-Akademie zu Berlin|Berliner Singakademie]] from 1827, as a soloist from 1829. The academy had to be closed in 1830.<!-- geschlossen werden, da aufgrund der [[Cholera]]-Epidemie in Berlin die Sch\u00fclerzahlen und somit die Einnahmen stark zur\u00fcckgegangen waren--><ref>Elisabeth Schmiedel, Joachim Draheim: ''Eine Musikerfamilie im 19. Jahrhundert: Marianne Bargiel, Clara Schumann, Woldemar Bargiel in Briefen und Dokumenten'', vol. 1, Munich 2007, {{ISBN|978-3-87397-343-5}}, p. 24.</ref> In 1836, Adolph Bargiel suffered a stroke and died after long illness in 1841.<!-- In dieser Zeit pflegte Mariane Bargiel ihren kranken Mann und verdiente den Familienunterhalt fortan durch ihre T\u00e4tigkeit als Klavierlehrerin.--><ref name=\"Bergmann\" />\n\nMariane Bargiel joined Stern'scher Gesangverein as a choir member and soloist, and worked as a piano teacher. She died at age 74 in Berlin on 10 March 1872.<ref>''Schumann-Briefedition'', series I, vol. 3 (family correspondence, Robert and Clara Schumanns with the Bargiel family), ed. Eberhard M\u00f6ller. Cologne 2011, p. 31.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* \n{{DNB portal|116056894}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bargiel, Mariane}}\n[[Category:German pianists]]\n[[Category:German music educators]]\n[[Category:German sopranos]]\n[[Category:1797 births]]\n[[Category:1872 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mariane Bargiel\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Mariane Tromlitz\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|df=y|1797|05|17}}\n| birth_place        = [[Greiz]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|1872|03|10|1797|05|17}}\n| death_place        = Berlin\n| other_names        = Mariane Wieck  \n| occupation         = {{plainlist|\n* Pianist\n* Soprano\n* Piano teacher\n}}\n| organization       = \n| spouses            = {{plainlist|\n* {{Marriage|[[Friedrich Wieck]]|1816|1825|reason=divorce}}\n* {{Marriage|Adolph Bargiel|1825|1836|reason=death}}\n}}\n| children           = [[Clara Schumann]]\n| relatives          = \n}}\n\n'''Mariane Bargiel''', n\u00e8e '''Tromlitz''', divorced '''Wieck''', also '''Marianne''' (17 May 1797 \u2013 10 March 1872) was a German pianist, [[soprano]] and piano teacher. She is known as the mother of [[Clara Schumann]].\n\n== Life ==\nBorn Mariane Tromlitz in [[Greiz]], she was the first child of Christian Gotthold Tromlitz (1765\u20131825), a church musician, music teacher and composer, and his wife Christiana Friederica n\u00e8e Carl (1766\u20131830). Her siblings were Georg Wilhelm (1799\u20131801) and Emilie (1802\u20131885). Her grandfather was the notable flutist and flute builder [[Johann George Tromlitz]]. She received first musical training from her father, and then studied with [[Friedrich Wieck]]. She played her first public concert at age 15 at the Gesellschaftshaus (society hall) in [[Plauen]], playing the piano quartet by [[Anton Eberl]].<ref name=\"Bergmann\">Hanna Bergmann: [https://www.sophie-drinker-institut.de/bargiel-marianne Bargiel, Marianne, geb. Tromlitz, verh. Wieck, verh. Bargiel] in Online-Lexikon Europ\u00e4ische Instrumentalistinnen des 18. und 19. Jahrhunderts. Sophie-Drinker-Institut 2009, retrieved 25 November 2019.</ref>\n\nOn 23 June 1816, she married her teacher Friedrich Wieck in [[Plauen|Oberlosa]], [[Vogtland]]. The lived in [[Leipzig]]. During the first years, she appeared successfully as a pianist and singer, and worked as a piano teacher. The couple had five children, Adelheid (1817\u20131819), [[Clara Schumann|Clara Josephine]] (1819\u20131896), {{ill|Alwin Wieck|de|lt=Alwin}}, Gustav (1823\u20131884) and Victor (1824\u20131826).<ref name=\"Bergmann\" />\n\nShe left her husband on May 1824, and first returned to her parents, with Clara, then age 4 1/2, and Victor, a baby of three months. They were divorced on 22 January 1825. As the father customarily held custody of the children, Clara could stay with her mother only until age five, and lived from 17 September 1824 with her father in Leipzig.<ref name=\"Bergmann\" /><ref name=sp>Schumann-Portal: [https://www.schumann-portal.de/mariane-bargiel-mutter.html Mariane Wieck-Bargiel geb. Tromlitz (1797\u20131872), Mutter von Clara Schumann], retrieved 25 November 2019</ref>\n\nShe married {{ill|Adolph Bargiel|de}}, a piano and voice teacher, in August 1825, and they moved to Berlin in 1826. He became director of a musical academy there, founded by [[Johann Bernhard Logier]], where she also taught. The couple had four children, [[Woldemar Bargiel|Woldemar]], Eugen (1830\u20131907), C\u00e4cilie (1832\u20131910) and Clementine (1835\u20131869).<ref name=\"Bergmann\" />\nMariane Bargiel is listed as a soprano of the [[Sing-Akademie zu Berlin|Berliner Singakademie]] from 1827, as a soloist from 1829. The academy had to be closed in 1830.<!-- geschlossen werden, da aufgrund der [[Cholera]]-Epidemie in Berlin die Sch\u00fclerzahlen und somit die Einnahmen stark zur\u00fcckgegangen waren--><ref>Elisabeth Schmiedel, Joachim Draheim: ''Eine Musikerfamilie im 19. Jahrhundert: Marianne Bargiel, Clara Schumann, Woldemar Bargiel in Briefen und Dokumenten'', vol. 1, Munich 2007, {{ISBN|978-3-87397-343-5}}, p. 24.</ref> In 1836, Adolph Bargiel suffered a stroke and died after long illness in 1841.<!-- In dieser Zeit pflegte Mariane Bargiel ihren kranken Mann und verdiente den Familienunterhalt fortan durch ihre T\u00e4tigkeit als Klavierlehrerin.--><ref name=\"Bergmann\" />\n\nMariane Bargiel joined Stern'scher Gesangverein as a choir member and soloist, and worked as a piano teacher. She died at age 74 in Berlin on 10 March 1872.<ref>''Schumann-Briefedition'', series I, vol. 3 (family correspondence, Robert and Clara Schumanns with the Bargiel family), ed. Eberhard M\u00f6ller. Cologne 2011, p. 31.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* \n{{DNB portal|116056894}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bargiel, Mariane}}\n[[Category:German pianists]]\n[[Category:German music educators]]\n[[Category:German sopranos]]\n[[Category:1797 births]]\n[[Category:1872 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Gerda Arendt", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mariane_Bargiel"}
{"title_page": "West Midlands (region)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|West Midlands (county)|West Midlands conurbation}}\n{{Short description|A region of England}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n| type                   = [[Regions of England|region of England]]\n| name                   = West Midlands\n| image_skyline          = West Midlands in England.svg\n| image_alt              = West Midlands, highlighted in red on a beige political map of England\n| image_caption          = \n| imagesize              = 200\n| coordinates            = \n| subdivision_type       = [[Sovereign state]]\n| subdivision_name       = [[United Kingdom]]\n| subdivision_type1      = {{nowrap|[[Countries of the United Kingdom|Constituent country]]}}\n| subdivision_name1      = [[England]]\n| seat_type              = Largest city\n| seat                   = [[Birmingham]]\n| seat1_type             = Largest urban area\n| seat1                  = [[West Midlands conurbation]]\n| seat2_type             = Largest town\n| seat2                  = \n| leader_title           = [[Local authority leaders' board|Leaders' board]]\n| leader_name            = [[West Midlands Councils]]\n| leader_title1          = [[European Parliament constituency|EP&nbsp;constituency]]\n| leader_name1           = [[West Midlands (European Parliament constituency)|West Midlands]]\n| unit_pref              = Metric\n| area_total_km2         = 13,000\n| area_rank              = 7th\n| population_as_of       = 2014 est.\n| population_footnotes   = \n| population_total       = 5,713,000\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| population_rank        = 5th\n| demographics_type1     = [[Gross value added|GVA]] \n| demographics1_title1   = Total\n| demographics1_info1    = \u00a3110&nbsp;billion\n| demographics1_title2   = Per capita\n| demographics1_info2    = \u00a317,161 ([[Countries of the United Kingdom by GVA per capita|7th]])\n| blank_name_sec1        = [[NUTS statistical regions of the United Kingdom|NUTS code]]\n| blank_info_sec1        = UKG\n| blank1_name_sec1       = [[ONS coding system|ONS code]]\n| blank1_info_sec1       = \n| website                = \n}}\n{{Politics of England}}\nThe '''West Midlands''' is one of nine official [[regions of England]] at the [[First level NUTS of the European Union|first level]] of [[NUTS statistical regions of the United Kingdom|NUTS]] for [[Eurostat|statistical]] purposes. It covers the western half of the area traditionally known as the [[Midlands (England)|Midlands]]. It contains [[Birmingham]] and the larger [[West Midlands conurbation]], which is the [[List of urban areas in the United Kingdom|third most populous]] in the [[United Kingdom]]. The City of [[Coventry]] is also located within the [[West Midlands county]], but is separated from the [[conurbation]] to the west by several miles of [[green belt]]. The region also contains 6 shire counties which stretch from the Welsh Border to the East Midlands.\n\nThe region is geographically diverse, from the urban central areas of the conurbation to the rural western counties of [[Shropshire]] and [[Herefordshire]] which border [[Wales]]. The longest river in the UK, the [[River Severn]], traverses the region southeastwards, flowing through the [[county town]]s of [[Shrewsbury]] and [[Worcester]], and the [[Ironbridge Gorge]], a [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]]. [[Staffordshire]] is home to the industrialised [[Staffordshire Potteries|Potteries]] conurbation, including the city of [[Stoke-on-Trent]], and the [[Staffordshire Moorlands]] area, which borders the southeastern [[Peak District National Park]] near [[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]]. The region also encompasses five [[Areas of Outstanding Natural Beauty]], the [[Wye Valley]], [[Shropshire Hills]], [[Cannock Chase]], [[Malvern Hills]], and parts of the [[Cotswolds]]. [[Warwickshire]] is home to the towns of [[Stratford upon Avon]], birthplace of writer [[William Shakespeare]], [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]], the birthplace of [[Rugby football]] and [[Nuneaton]], birthplace to author [[George Eliot]].\n\n==Geography==\n\nThe official region contains the [[Ceremonial counties of England|ceremonial counties]] of [[Herefordshire]], Shropshire, [[Staffordshire]], Warwickshire, [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] and [[Worcestershire]].\n[[File:Lyth Hill 01.jpg|thumb|Rural [[Shropshire]], [[Bayston Hill|Lyth Hill]].]]\n\nThere is some confusion in the use of the term \"West Midlands\", as the name is also used for the much smaller [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands county]] and conurbation which is in the central belt of the Midlands and on the eastern side of the West Midlands Region. It is also still used by various organisations within that area, such as [[West Midlands Police]] and [[West Midlands Fire Service]].\n\nThe highest point in the region is [[Black Mountain (hill)|Black Mountain]], at 703&nbsp;metres (2,307&nbsp;ft) in west Herefordshire on the border with [[Powys]], Wales.\n\nThe region contains five [[Areas of Outstanding Natural Beauty]] (AONBs), including the [[Shropshire Hills]], [[Malvern Hills]] and [[Cannock Chase]], and parts of the [[Wye Valley]] and [[Cotswolds]]. The [[Peak District]] national park also stretches into the northern corner of [[Staffordshire]].\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Railways===\n[[File:Birmingham & West Mids Passenger Railway_Map.JPG|thumb|Map of the West Midlands passenger railway network]]\nServed by many lines in the urban areas such as the [[West Coast Main Line]] and branches.  The [[Welsh Marches Line]] and the [[Cotswold Line]] transect the region as well as the [[Cross Country Route]] and [[Chiltern Line]].  There are plans to reopen the [[Honeybourne Line]].\n\n===Road===\n[[File:M6 Toll plaza, Great Wyrley.jpg|thumb|The [[M6 Toll]] plaza.]]\nNumerous notable roads pass through the region, with most converging around the central conurbation. The [[M5 motorway|M5]], which connects [[South West England]] to the region, passes through Worcestershire, near to [[Worcester]], and through the [[West Midlands county]], past [[West Bromwich]], with its northern terminus at its junction with the [[M6 motorway|M6]] just south of [[Walsall]]. The M6, which has its southern terminus just outside the southeast of the region at its junction with the [[M1 motorway|M1]], and which connects the region to [[North West England]], passes [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]] and [[Nuneaton]] in Warwickshire, [[Coventry]] and [[Birmingham]], and [[Stafford]] and [[Stoke-on-Trent]] in Staffordshire. The [[M6 toll]] provides an alternative route to the M6 between [[Coleshill, Warwickshire|Coleshill]] and [[Cannock]], passing north of [[Sutton Coldfield]] and just south of [[Lichfield]].  The [[M40 motorway|M40]] connects the region through [[South East England]] to London, with its northern terminus at its junction with the [[M42 motorway|M42]]; it passes close to [[Warwick]] and [[Banbury]]. The M42 connects the M5 at [[Bromsgrove]], passing around the south and east of Birmingham, joining the M40 and M6, passing [[Solihull]] and [[Castle Bromwich]], to [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]], northeast of Birmingham.  The [[M50 motorway (Great Britain)|M50]] connects the M5 from near [[Tewkesbury]] to [[Ross-on-Wye]] in the southwest. The [[M54 motorway|M54]] connects [[Wellington, Shropshire|Wellington]] in the west, passing [[Telford]], to the M6 near [[Cannock]]. The [[A5 road (Great Britain)|A5 road]] traverses the region northwest-southeast, passing through [[Shrewsbury]], [[Telford]], [[Cannock]], [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]] and [[Nuneaton]].\n\nThe longest elevated road viaduct in the UK is the {{convert|4779|m|mi|0|order=flip}} section from Gravelly Hill to Castle Bromwich on the M6, opened on 24 May 1972; the {{convert|5.6|km|mi|order=flip}} [[Bromford Viaduct]] is the longest viaduct in the UK. The section of the A45 in Coventry from [[Willenhall, Coventry|Willenhall]] to Allesley in 1939 was one of the UK's first ever large planned road schemes; road schemes on that scale had not been previously built, with few large road schemes outside of London, or were piecemeal.\n\nPrinces Square in Wolverhampton had Britain's first automatic traffic lights on 5 November 1927.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=Princes_Square|title=Princes Square - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|author=|date=|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk|access-date=15 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171115221840/https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=Princes_Square|archive-date=15 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On 13 January 2012, 34-year-old Ben Westwood of Wednesfield, was caught by the police, when speeding at 180&nbsp;mph, in an [[Audi A5|Audi RS5]] with a [[Lamborghini]] engine, from Wolverhampton up to Stafford on the M6, and back again. He was travelling so fast that he was outpacing the [[Central Counties Air Operations Unit]] [[Eurocopter EC135|Eurocopter]] helicopter. He and the vehicle had been in fifteen [[smash and grab]] raids and he was jailed for nine years at Wolverhampton Crown Court in August 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-19347144|title=Jail for 180mph M6 chase driver|author=|date=23 August 2012|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=7 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181007075234/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-19347144|archive-date=7 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Transport policy===\n[[File:M45 Motorway near Barby - geograph.org.uk - 31743.jpg|thumb|right|The [[M45 motorway]], originally called the [[Dunchurch]] Link, was one of the first motorways built in the UK, and is now one of the quietest]]\nAs part of the transport planning system, the Regional Assembly is under statutory requirement to produce a [[regional transport strategy (UK)|regional transport strategy]] (RTS) to provide long term planning for transport in the region. This involves region wide transport schemes such as those carried out by [[Highways England]] and [[Network Rail]].<ref name=\"GoWM1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gos.gov.uk/gowm/Transport/TransportRegTransStrat/?a=42496 |title=Regional Transport Strategy: the National Picture |publisher=[[Government Office]] for the West Midlands |accessdate=28 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630083736/http://www.gos.gov.uk/gowm/Transport/TransportRegTransStrat/?a=42496 |archivedate=30 June 2009 }}</ref>\n\nWithin the region, the local transport authorities carry out transport planning through the use of a [[local transport plan]] (LTP) which outlines their strategies, policies and implementation programme.<ref name=\"DfT1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/regional/ltp/theltpprocess |title=The LTP Process |publisher=[[Department for Transport]] |accessdate=28 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009193023/http://www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/regional/ltp/theltpprocess |archivedate=9 October 2007 }}</ref> The most recent LTP is that for the period 2006\u201311. In the West Midlands region, the following transport authorities have published their LTP online: [[Herefordshire]],<ref name=\"HLTP\">\n{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.herefordshire.gov.uk/transport/3197.asp\n |title       = Herefordshire 2006\u201311 Local Transport Plan\n |publisher   = [[Herefordshire Council]]\n |accessdate  = 5 May 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20081228235559/http://www.herefordshire.gov.uk/transport/3197.asp\n |archivedate = 28 December 2008\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> [[Shropshire]] U.A.,<ref name=\"ShLTP\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.shropshire.gov.uk/traveltransport.nsf/open/ADE3AAF9F3AAD7C48025709E003D2144\n|title=Shropshire2006-11 Local Transport Plan\n|publisher=[[Shropshire Council]]\n|accessdate=5 May 2009\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201150513/http://www.shropshire.gov.uk/traveltransport.nsf/open/ADE3AAF9F3AAD7C48025709E003D2144\n|archive-date=1 December 2008\n|url-status=live\n}}</ref> [[Staffordshire]],<ref name=\"StLTP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/transport/transportplanning/localtransportplan/LocalTransportPlan2.htm |title=Staffordshire2006-11 Local Transport Plan |publisher=[[Staffordshire]] County Council |accessdate=5 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121194044/http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/transport/transportplanning/localtransportplan/LocalTransportPlan2.htm |archivedate=21 November 2008 }}</ref> [[Telford and Wrekin]] U.A.,<ref name=T&WLTP>{{cite web|url=http://www.telford.gov.uk/Transport+streets+and+parking/Transport+planning/Local+Transport+Plan+2006-2011+with+mid-term+Delivery+Report.htm |title=Telford and Wrekin 2006\u201311 Local Transport Plan |publisher=[[Telford and Wrekin Council]] |accessdate=5 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630095014/http://www.telford.gov.uk/Transport+streets+and+parking/Transport+planning/Local+Transport+Plan+2006-2011+with+mid-term+Delivery+Report.htm |archivedate=30 June 2009 }}</ref> [[Warwickshire]],<ref name=\"WrLTP\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.warwickshire.gov.uk/ltp\n|title=Warwickshire 2006\u201311 Local Transport Plan\n|publisher=[[Warwickshire County Council]]\n|accessdate=5 May 2009\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430121313/http://www.warwickshire.gov.uk/ltp\n|archive-date=30 April 2009\n|url-status=live\n}}</ref> [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]<ref name=\"WMLTP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.westmidlandsltp.gov.uk/ |title=West Midlands 2006\u201311 Local Transport Plan |publisher=West Midlands LTP |accessdate=5 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090518075425/http://www.westmidlandsltp.gov.uk/ |archivedate=18 May 2009 }}</ref> and [[Worcestershire]].<ref name=\"WcLTP\">{{cite web|url=http://worcestershire.whub.org.uk/home/wccindex/wcc-ht/wcc-ht-ltp-v2.htm |title=Worcestershire 2006\u201311 Local Transport Plan |publisher=[[Worcestershire County Council]] |accessdate=5 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090311084239/http://worcestershire.whub.org.uk/home/wccindex/wcc-ht/wcc-ht-ltp-v2.htm |archivedate=11 March 2009 }}</ref> The transport authority of [[Stoke-on-Trent]] U.A. publishes a joint local transport plan in partnership with Staffordshire County Council to cover the North Staffordshire Major Urban Area, which includes Stoke-on-Trent and the more urban parts of [[Newcastle-under-Lyme]] and [[Staffordshire Moorlands]].<ref name=\"SoTLTP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stoke.gov.uk/ccm/content/rc/LTP/provisional-north-staffordshire-ltp.en |title=Stoke-on-Trent 2006\u201311 Local Transport Plan |publisher=[[Stoke-on-Trent City Council]] |accessdate=5 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630152508/http://www.stoke.gov.uk/ccm/content/rc/LTP/provisional-north-staffordshire-ltp.en |archivedate=30 June 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Towns and cities==\n{{clear}}\nMajor towns and cities in the West Midlands region include:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/StatBase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=8271&Pos=2&ColRank=1&Rank=224|title=Home - Office for National Statistics|author=|date=|website=www.statistics.gov.uk|access-date=19 March 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070421211031/http://www.statistics.gov.uk/StatBase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=8271&Pos=2&ColRank=1&Rank=224|archive-date=21 April 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n:<small>''Bold indicates [[City status in the United Kingdom|city status]].''</small>\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n;Population > 1,000,000\n* '''[[Birmingham]]''', [[West Midlands (county)|WMS]]\n;Population > 200,000\n* '''[[Coventry]]''', WMS\n* '''[[Stoke-on-Trent]]''', [[Staffordshire|STS]]\n* '''[[Wolverhampton]]''', WMS\n;Population > 100,000\n* [[Solihull]], WMS\n* [[Telford]], [[Shropshire|SHR]]\n* '''[[Worcester]]''', [[Worcestershire|WOR]]\n;Population > 50,000\n* [[Burton-upon-Trent]], STS\n* [[Dudley]], WMS\n* [[Halesowen]], WMS\n* '''[[Hereford]]''', [[Herefordshire|HER]]\n* [[Kidderminster]], WOR\n* [[Leamington Spa]], [[Warwickshire|WAR]]\n* [[Newcastle-under-Lyme]], STS\n* [[Nuneaton]], WAR\n* [[Redditch]], WOR\n* [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]], WAR\n* [[Shrewsbury]], SHR\n* [[Stafford]], STS\n* [[Stourbridge]], WMS\n* [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]], STS\n* [[Walsall]], WMS\n* [[West Bromwich]], WMS\n{{col-3}}\n;Population > 25,000\n* [[Cannock]], STS\n* [[Bedworth]], WAR\n* [[Bromsgrove]], WOR \n* '''[[Lichfield]]''', STS\n* [[Malvern, Worcestershire|Malvern]], WOR\n* [[Rowley Regis]], WMS\n* [[Smethwick]], WMS\n* [[Stratford-upon-Avon]], WAR\n* [[Tipton]], WMS\n* [[Warwick]], WAR\n* [[Wednesbury]], WMS\n;Other notable:\n* [[Atherstone]], WAR\n* [[Bridgnorth]], SHR\n* [[Droitwich Spa]], WOR\n* [[Evesham]], WOR\n* [[Kenilworth]], WAR\n* [[Kidsgrove]], STS\n* [[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]], STS\n* [[Oswestry]], SHR\n* [[Rugeley]], STS\n* [[Uttoxeter]], STS\n{{col-3}}\n[[File:WestMidlandsRegion.jpg|290px|left|thumb|A map of the West Midlands region, showing Towns/Cities in <span style=\"color:#f00;\">Red</span>, Motorways in <span style=\"color:#72a0fe;\">Blue</span>, [[AONB]]s in <span style=\"color:#78ff00;\"> Light Green</span> and [[National parks of the United Kingdom|National Parks]] in <span style=\"color:#4c8910;\"> Dark Green</span>.]]\n{{col-end}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Modern history==\n\n{{Further| Mercia}}\n\n===World War II===\nThe [[RAF Fauld explosion]] on 27 November 1944 in east Staffordshire produced a 100-foot deep crater, and is the UK's largest explosion, being caused by around 4,000 tonnes of [[Explosive material|high explosive]], and may be the [[Largest artificial non-nuclear explosions|world's largest non-nuclear explosion]].\n\nBirmingham was the third [[Birmingham Blitz|most bombed]] city in the UK after London and [[Liverpool]]; Spitfires were built in Castle Bromwich, [[Avro Lancaster|Lancaster]]s at Austin's works in [[Longbridge plant|Longbridge]] at [[Cofton Hackett]], and the [[Birmingham Small Arms Company]] at [[Small Heath, Birmingham|Small Heath]] produced the [[M1919 Browning machine gun]]. [[Boulton Paul Aircraft]] had their main aircraft factory in the north of Wolverhampton. [[RAF Defford]], in the south of Worcestershire between Pershore and [[Croome Court|Croome Park]], was where many important [[Airborne early warning and control|airborne radars]] were developed, such as [[H2S (radar)]] and anti-submarine radars.\n\n===Scientific heritage===\n[[Thomas Wedgwood (photographer)|Thomas Wedgwood]], son of Josiah Wedgwood, discovered the first [[Photographic paper|photo-sensitive]] (light-sensitive) chemicals \u2013 [[silver nitrate]] and [[silver chloride]] in the 1790s.\n\nSir [[Norman Lockyer]] of [[Kenilworth]] discovered [[helium]] in 1868, for which he used electromagnetic [[spectroscopy]].\n\n[[Edward Weston (chemist)|Edward Weston]] of Oswestry, who emigrated to the US, built the first accurate [[voltmeter]] in the late 1880s, and the [[Weston cell]] in 1893.\n\n[[Francis William Aston|Francis W. Aston]] of Harborne, educated at the University of Birmingham, developed [[mass spectrometry]] in 1919, which helped him to identify the first [[isotope]]s, receiving the [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize for Chemistry]] in 1922.\n\n[[Dennis Gabor]] invented holography at [[British Thomson-Houston]] in Rugby in 1947, receiving the [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel Prize for Physics]] in 1971.\n\n[[James Glaisher]] in 1862 took a record balloon flight with [[Henry Tracey Coxwell]] for the [[British Science Association|BAAS]] near Wolverhampton. They reached {{convert|29000|ft}} the composition of the Earth's atmosphere until then was not understood; the altitude records for the UK have not been exceeded since; [[Project Excelsior]] in the US in 1960 would later reach {{convert|20|mi|ft}}.\n\n[[Philip Lawley]] of Burton upon Trent was first person to realise that [[Health effects of tobacco|chemical damage to DNA]] caused cancer (at the Chester Beatty Research Institute in London) in the early 1960s.\n\n[[Francis Galton]] (d. 1911) of the [[Darwin\u2013Wedgwood family]]'s Birmingham branch was an early [[Eugenics|eugenicist]] rooted in improving animal breeding stock and examining heredity. He invented terms eugenics and ''[[nature versus nurture]]''. His limited calls for human eugenics were widened by the [[German Society for Racial Hygiene]] in 1905 founded by [[Alfred Ploetz]], which coupled with the racial superiority fallacies of [[Aryan race|Aryanism]] reached its nadir in [[Holocaust|genocidal]] [[anti-semitism]]. Moral teachings and [[deontological ethics|inherent replusions]] towards human eugenics were overcome by a minority of those in power espousing [[racial equality]]; European media and leaders lamented [[European imperialism|loss of Empire]], advocated [[ultranationalism]] and prized military physical advantage; Galton saw human eugenics as part of all means to ''do better''.\n\n===Industrial heritage===\n{{See also|Science and invention in Birmingham|Architecture of Birmingham}}\n[[File:The Iron Bridge - geograph.org.uk - 224230.jpg|thumb|The [[cast iron]] Iron Bridge at [[Coalbrookdale]], opened in January 1781 and was the first large-scale object made out of cast iron; but cast iron is not reliably strong due to impurities. [[Wrought iron]], where the carbon is hammered to remove to carbon and impurities is much stronger; the first large-scale wrought iron bridge was the [[Britannia Bridge]] over the [[Menai Strait]], only possible due to its innovative [[box girder]] design by [[Robert Stephenson]] ]]\nMuch of the [[Industrial revolution]] in the United Kingdom began in [[Birmingham]] and the [[Black Country]] area of West Midlands. The Industrial Revolution is thought to have begun when [[Abraham Darby I|Abraham Darby]] substituted [[coke (fuel)|coke]] in the place of charcoal to smelt iron, at his Old Furnace. The Black Country may be regarded as the world's first industrial landscape,<ref>{{cite web|title=Black Country Living Museum|url=http://www.bclm.co.uk/|publisher=Black Country Living Museum|accessdate=3 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130403022514/http://www.bclm.co.uk/|archive-date=3 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> while nearby [[Ironbridge Gorge]] claims to be the Birthplace of Industry.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Iron Bridge|url=http://www.ironbridge.org.uk/our-attractions/the-iron-bridge-and-tollhouse/|publisher=Ironbridge Gorge Museum Trust|accessdate=3 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130321095559/http://www.ironbridge.org.uk/our-attractions/the-iron-bridge-and-tollhouse|archive-date=21 March 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> [[The Iron Bridge|The world's first cast iron bridge in 1779]] spans the Gorge. The first self-propelled locomotive to run on rails in 1803 at Coalbrookdale, was built by [[Richard Trevithick]]. The [[Permanent way (history)|first iron rails]] for horse-drawn transport, were made at Coalbrookdale in 1768 by [[Richard Reynolds (ironmaster)|Richard Reynolds]] at [[Ketley Ironworks]]. Iron rails only became widely successful in 1820 when made out of [[wrought iron]] at [[Bedlington Ironworks]] in north-east England.\n\n[[File:Philipp Jakob Loutherbourg d. J. 002.jpg|thumb|''Coalbrookdale by Night'', of the [[Madeley Wood Company]], painted by [[Philip James de Loutherbourg]] in 1801]] \nBirmingham's industrial development was triggered by discussions at the [[Lunar Society of Birmingham]] at [[Soho House]], Boulton's house, and products were carried along the [[BCN Main Line]] canal. [[Soho Manufactory]] was the first man-made-powered factory in world. [[Chance Brothers]] of Smethwick built the glass for [[The Crystal Palace]] in 1851. [[Smethwick Engine]], now at [[Thinktank, Birmingham Science Museum]], is the oldest working steam engine, made in 1779, and is the oldest working engine in the world. Smethwick was a main centre for making [[lighthouse]] [[lantern]]s.\n\n[[Yale & Valor|Valor Fires]] in Erdington developed the first [[Radiant heating|radiant]] [[Gas heater|gas fire]] in 1967, a balanced [[flue]] fire in 1973, and a natural flame gas fire in 1978. The Erdington site, owned by Iceland's [[BDR Thermea]], closed in May 2012. The company also built [[Gas stove|gas cooker]]s; since 2011 the company has been part of [[Glen Dimplex]], who have a site at [[Cooper's Bank]], south of [[Gornal, West Midlands|Gornalwood]].\n\n[[File:Boulton, Watt and Murdoch - geograph.org.uk - 1754695.jpg|thumb|right|Boulton, Watt and Murdoch, a 1956 statue on Broad Street in Birmingham; the [[International System of Units|SI]] unit of power is the watt, most commonly found as the kW, a replacement for the imperial measurement of [[horsepower]] ]]\n[[Ditherington Flax Mill]] in Shrewsbury was the first [[Steel frame|iron-framed building]] in the world in 1797. [[Thomas Bolton & Sons]] of [[Froghall]], Staffordshire, made the world's first [[transatlantic telegraph cable]] in 1857, having supplied a [[Submarine communications cable|submarine cable]] across the English Channel in 1850. [[GEC Telecommunications]] was headquartered at the [[GEC Telephone and Radio Works]] in Coventry, it has now become the New Century Park, off the [[A428 road|A428]] north of [[Stoke Aldermoor]] in eastern Coventry. On 10 July 1890, a trunk circuit telephone line was opened between London and Birmingham by the [[National Telephone Company]]; for the first time this allowed phone calls between the London and the north.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.btplc.com/Thegroup/BTsHistory/1881to1911/1890.htm|title=1881to1911|author=|date=|website=www.btplc.com|access-date=10 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714194552/http://www.btplc.com/Thegroup/BTsHistory/1881to1911/1890.htm|archive-date=14 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The world's first [[coaxial cable]] was laid between London and Birmingham in 1936 to give 40 channels for telephone traffic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.btplc.com/Thegroup/BTsHistory/1912to1968/1936.htm|title=1912to1968|author=|date=|website=www.btplc.com|access-date=10 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714162420/http://www.btplc.com/Thegroup/BTsHistory/1912to1968/1936.htm|archive-date=14 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and brought into use in 1938, later extended to Manchester in 1940.\n\n[[File:BaskervilleSpec.svg|thumb|left|The [[Baskerville]] font named after the inventor of typefaces]]\n[[Alexander Parkes]] invented the first man-made plastic ([[thermoplastic]]) in Birmingham in 1856. [[Arthur Leslie Large]] of Birmingham is credited with inventing the [[kettle]] in 1922. Princess Square, Wolverhampton, was the site of Britain's first traffic lights in 1927. Infra-red cameras were developed at the Royal Radar Establishment in Malvern (with EMI Electronics) in 1967. The world's first [[Maglev]] train operated at [[AirRail Link|Birmingham Airport]] in 1983. The tallest freestanding structure in the region is the chimney of [[Ironbridge power stations|Ironbridge power station]] at 673&nbsp;ft. [[John Baskerville]] of Birmingham, a former stone carver, largely invented fonts, or [[typeface]]s, for printing.\n\n{{See also|Automotive industry in the United Kingdom}}\n\nMuch of the UK's car industry would be centred in Coventry and Birmingham; most of this has now gone. [[Midland Motor Cylinder]] (part of [[Birmid Industries]]) of Smethwick was the largest producer of automobile [[cylinder block]]s in Europe. [[Fort Dunlop]] was Europe's largest tyre plant. [[Metro-Cammell]] in Birmingham made most of the 1970s and 1980s [[London Underground]] trains. [[MG Rover Group|MG Rover]] (a company of Rover) closed in 2005 (from 1885), The [[Ryton plant]], which made the [[Peugeot 206]], closed at the end of 2006, with production moving to [[Trnava]] in Slovakia, and some to a plant at [[Kol\u00edn]] in the [[Czech Republic]]. [[Alfred Herbert (company)|Alfred Herbert]] of Coventry was the largest [[tool builder|machine-tool manufacturer]] in the UK for many decades; it was brought down in the 1970s by advancing technology overseas, and complacent strategic decisions of the management (caught like a rabbit in the headlights), finally closing in 1982; many Midlands manufacturing companies followed similar fates in the 1970s and 1980s. Tube Investments was based at [[Tube Investments House]], [[Five Ways, Birmingham|Five Ways]], Edgbaston (now a [[Marriott International|Marriott]] hotel).\n\n[[File:Grazebrook Beam Engine.jpg|thumb|right|1817 Boulton & Watt beam blowing engine re-erected on the Dartmouth Circus roundabout, on the [[A4540 road|A4540]] and the A38(M)]]\n[[Henry Wiggin & Co]] of Hereford developed the metal [[alloy]]s necessary for other Midlands' (and beyond) automotive and aerospace companies \u2013 [[Inconel]], [[Incoloy]] and [[Nimonic]]. It was the lack of [[vanadium]] for [[High-temperature corrosion|high-melting point alloys]], caused by Royal Navy action, that prevented German [[Messerschmitt Me 262|Me 262]] engines being serviceable; had German World War 2 engineers had a greater supply of vanadium and [[molybdenum]], the engine life (around 12 hours maximum, from entering service in April 1944 to the end of the war) of their [[Junkers Jumo 004|jet engine]] would have increased much more, which would have been significant to the war's outcome. [[Bristol Siddeley]] developed the rocket engines for [[Black Arrow]] at Ansty; in fact all of R-R's rocket engines were developed and built there at R-R's Industrial and Marine Gas Turbine Division; Britain's smaller rocket engines for missiles were built by [[Bristol Aerojet]] in what is now [[North Somerset]]. High Duty Alloys at Redditch constructed (forged) the compressor and turbine blades for Whittle's first engines, and many of the early jet engines; it made [[Concorde]]'s airframe from the [[Hiduminium]] R.R.58 [[aluminium alloy]].\n\n[[Maxaret]], the world's first [[Anti-lock braking system|ABS]] [[Brake|braking]] system, was invented in Coventry by Dunlop in the early 1950s for aircraft; [[John Boyd Dunlop]] was a Scottish vet who had first produced the first pneumatic [[Tire|tyres]] in 1889. [[Matthew Piers Watt Boulton]], grandson of Matthew Boulton, and born in the area, invented the [[aileron]], an important [[Flight control surfaces|flight control surface]] in 1868, decades before the first actual flight. [[Triumph Engineering]] was a famous motorbike firm in Meriden. About a quarter of all British WWI planes were built in Coventry. The [[Jensen Interceptor]] FF was the first production four-wheel-drive car in the world, designed by Major [[Tony Rolt]], and built at their factory in West Bromwich.\n\nCadbury launched ''[[Cadbury Dairy Milk|Dairy Milk]]'' in 1905, ''[[Bournville (chocolate bar)|Bournville]]'' in 1906, ''[[Cadbury Dairy Milk Fruit & Nut|Fruit & Nut]]'' in 1928, ''Whole Nut'' in 1930, ''[[Cadbury Roses]]'' in 1938, and the ''[[Cadbury Creme Egg]]'' in 1971. [[George Cadbury|George]] and [[Richard Cadbury]] built their factory in 1879 and [[Bournville]] in 1893, named after the [[Bournbrook|Bourn brook]]. [[Iceland (supermarket)]] opened its first store in Oswestry in 1970 \u2013 heralding the onset of frozen food in the UK. [[Alfred Bird]] invented egg-free custard in 1837 in Birmingham \u2013 accidentally given to guests at his home, being created as his wife had an allergy to eggs; he then invented [[baking powder]] in 1843 as his wife also had an allergy to [[yeast]].\n\n===Culture===\n[[J. R. R. Tolkien]] grew up in Birmingham, Kings Heath, then part of Worcestershire, and was inspired by [[Moseley Bog]] and [[Sarehole]], and perhaps by the [[Perrott's Folly]]. [[Philip Larkin]] came from Coventry. [[Rowland Hill]] (stamps) was from Kidderminster. The writer [[George Eliot]] came from [[Nuneaton]]. [[Anthony E. Pratt]] from Birmingham invented [[Cluedo]].\n\n[[Frederick Gibberd]] of Coventry designed [[Liverpool Metropolitan Cathedral]]. [[Edward Cave]] from Rugby made Britain's first magazine in 1731 \u2013 [[The Gentleman's Magazine]]. [[Philip Astley]] from Newcastle under Lyme invented the modern day circus in 1768 \u2013 [[Astley's Amphitheatre]].\n\nThe [[Castlemorton Common Festival]] in May 1992 near Malvern, led to the [[Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994]].\n\nThe highest numbered building in the UK is 2679 Stratford Road, [[A3400 road|Stratford Road]], [[Hockley Heath]].\n\nThe [[Nowka Bais]] is a [[Bengali culture|Bengali]] [[boat racing]] festival which takes place annually in [[Birmingham]]. It is a leading cultural event in the [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]], [[United Kingdom]] attracting not only the [[Bangladeshi diaspora]] but a variety of cultures.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.berkeleygroup.co.uk/news-and-insights/news/2019/st-joseph-makes-a-splash|title=St Joseph makes a splash at the 2019 Nowka Bais|website=Berkeley Group|access-date=5 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905132411/https://www.berkeleygroup.co.uk/news-and-insights/news/2019/st-joseph-makes-a-splash|archive-date=5 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It is also the largest kind of [[boat race]] in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/free-festival-street-food-dragon-14826783|publisher=[[Birmingham Mail]]|last=Bentley|first=David|date=29 July 2018|title=Free festival with street food and dragon boat racing returns to Birmingham|access-date=5 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905155927/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/free-festival-street-food-dragon-14826783|archive-date=5 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Regional assembly==\n\n{{Update|section|date=October 2014}}\n\nThe official representative body of the region is the [[West Midlands Leaders Board]] which has limited administrative functions such as regional planning and economic development. The board is not an elected body, but is made up of members appointed from local councils across the region and is known as a [[quango]]. It is based on ''Edward Street'' in Birmingham, near the [[National Indoor Arena]]. From March 2010, the funding decisions at regional level were taken over by [[Advantage West Midlands]], the [[Regional Development Agency]].\n\n==Demographics==\n\n===Ethnicity===\n[[File:United Kingdom European Union referendum 2016 voting area results (West Midlands).svg|thumb|450px|right|How the West Midlands region voted in the June 2016 [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|European Union referendum]]; only the (university) district of Warwick voted (58.8%) to stay in the EU; the region had the highest overall vote (59.3%) to leave, with large proportions in Stoke-on-Trent (69.4%) and [[Cannock Chase District|Cannock Chase]] (68.9%)]]\nThe West Midlands is the second most ethnically diverse region of the UK (London being the most diverse). This is in large part due to the [[West Midlands conurbation]], which is highly diverse. The ethnic makeup of the West Midlands as a whole as measured by the 2011 census was as follows:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|-\n!Ethnic group || 2011<br>population || 2011<br>%\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | White: [[White British|British]] || 4,434,333 || 79.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | White: [[Irish Briton|Irish]] || 55,216 || 1.0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | White: [[Irish Traveller]]/[[Romani people|Gypsy]]<ref group=\"note\">In 2001 part of the White Other category. New category created for the 2011 census</ref> || 4,734 || 0.1\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | White: [[White Other (United Kingdom Census)|Other]] ||139,386 || 2.5\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | '''[[White people|White]]: Total''' || '''4,633,669''' ||  \n'''82.7'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Asian or Asian British: [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|Indian]] || 218 439 || 3.9\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Asian or Asian British: [[British Pakistani|Pakistani]] || 227,248 || 4.1\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Asian or Asian British: [[British Bangladeshi|Bangladeshi]] || 52,477 || 0.9\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Asian or Asian British: [[British Chinese|Chinese]]|| 31,274 ||0.6\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Asian or Asian British: [[British Asian|Asian Other]] || 74,997 || 1.3\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | '''[[Asian people|Asian]] or [[British Asian|Asian British]]: Total''' || '''604,435''' || \n'''10.8'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Black or Black British: [[British African-Caribbean community|Caribbean]] || 86,794 || 1.6\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Black or Black British: [[Black British|African]] || 64,253 || 1.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Black or Black British: [[Other Black|Other]] || 31,078 || 0.6\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | '''[[Black people|Black]] or [[Black British]]: Total''' || '''182,125''' || \n'''3.3'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Mixed: [[White people|White]] and [[British African-Caribbean community|Caribbean]] || 68,533 || 1.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Mixed: [[White people|White]] and [[Black British|African]] || 9,232 || 0.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Mixed: [[White people|White]] and [[British Asian|Asian Other]] || 32,561 || 0.6\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Mixed: [[Multiracial|Other Mixed]] || 21,388 || 0.4\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | '''[[British Mixed]]: Total''' || '''131,714''' || \n'''2.4'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Other: [[Arab people|Arab]]<ref group=\"note\">In 2001 part of the 'Other' category. New category created for the 2011 census</ref> || 18,079 || 0.3\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Other: Any other ethnic group || 31,825 || 0.6\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | '''Other: Total''' || '''49,904''' || \n'''0.9'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | '''Total''' || '''5,601,847''' || \n'''100'''\n|}\n\n===Teenage pregnancy===\nFor top-tier authorities in the West Midlands, Stoke-on-Trent has the highest [[Teenage pregnancy and sexual health in the United Kingdom|teenage pregnancy]] rate. For council districts, [[Nuneaton and Bedworth]] in Warwickshire has the highest rate closely followed by [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]]. For top-tier authorities, Shropshire has the lowest rate, and for council districts [[Malvern Hills (district)|Malvern Hills]] has the lowest rate.\n\n===Social deprivation===\nThe region, from studies of multiple deprivation, shows similarities with [[Yorkshire and the Humber]], and is more deprived than the neighbouring East Midlands. From the [[Indices of deprivation 2007]], it can be seen that, in common with [[Northern England]], the region has more [[Super Output Areas|Lower Area Super Output Areas]] in the 20% most deprived districts than in the 20% least deprived districts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.communities.gov.uk/documents/communities/pdf/576659.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120609171001/http://www.communities.gov.uk/documents/communities/pdf/576659.pdf|url-status=dead|title=LSOA data|archivedate=9 June 2012}}</ref> The region's most deprived council districts, in descending order, are Birmingham (10th highest in England), Sandwell (14th), Stoke-on-Trent (16th), Wolverhampton (28th), Walsall (45th), Coventry (61st), and Dudley (100th). These have Labour MPs except for a Conservative MP in Walsall, one in Sandwell, one in Dudley, and one in Wolverhampton ([[Wolverhampton South West (UK Parliament constituency)|Wolverhampton South West]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.communities.gov.uk/communities/neighbourhoodrenewal/deprivation/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413213602/http://www.communities.gov.uk/communities/neighbourhoodrenewal/deprivation/|url-status=dead|title=Communities and Local Government 2007|archivedate=13 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe least deprived districts in 2007 (before Shropshire became a unitary authority in 2009) were Bromsgrove, South Staffordshire, Warwick, Wychavon, and Lichfield. These areas, like all rural areas of the West Midlands, have Conservative MPs. At county level, the least deprived areas, in descending order, were Warwickshire, Worcestershire, Solihull, Staffordshire, and Shropshire.\n\nIn March 2011 the region had the second highest overall [[Jobseeker's Allowance|unemployment claimant]] count in England at 4.7%, second to [[North East England]]. The highest in the region was Wolverhampton at 7.7%, the joint second highest (with Manchester) unemployment rate in England. Next is Sandwell with 7.1%, Birmingham with 7.0%, and Walsall with 6.4%. The lowest rate in the region is the district of [[Stratford-on-Avon (district)|Stratford-on-Avon]], with 1.6% \u2013 one of the lowest unemployment rates in England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/elmr/downloads/Table6-18.xls|title=Claimant count}}</ref>\n\n===Elections===\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2015}}\nThe [[Green Party of England and Wales]] was formed at the Bridge Inn in [[Napton-on-the-Hill]], Warwickshire, in February 1973,\nand originated from an article by [[Paul R. Ehrlich]] about population growth in ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine; it became the Ecology Party in 1975 and the Green Party in 1985; the first conference was in June 1973 at ''The Allesley Hotel'' at the [[A4114 road|A4114]]/A45 junction south of the main Jaguar works in [[Allesley]], in west Coventry.\n\n[[File:United Kingdom General Election 2017 Results Map (West Midlands).svg|thumb|right|General Election results in 2017]]\nIn the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]], [[Nuneaton (UK Parliament constituency)|Nuneaton]] was taken by Labour with a 7% swing, which was one of the largest swings of the night; in the 2015 election, the Nuneaton result would largely seal the eventual outcome of the election. In the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], [[North Warwickshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Warwickshire]] ([[Dan Byles]]) had the smallest Conservative majority, with 54; [[Stoke-on-Trent Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent Central]] had the smallest number of winning votes, with 12,220.\n\nIn the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], the Conservatives gained the largest share of the region by popular vote and took control of the number of seats, with 42% of the region's electorate voting Conservative, 33% Labour, 16% UKIP, 6% Liberal Democrat and 3% Green. The Conservatives gained 2 seats with virtually no swing from Labour to Conservative.\n\nIn the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]], [[South Staffordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Staffordshire]] ([[Gavin Williamson]]) had the second-highest Conservative vote proportion in the UK \u2013 69.8%. [[David Firth (statistician)|David Firth]], at the [[University of Warwick]], invented the BBC election [[exit poll]]. 6&nbsp;ft 9 [[Daniel Kawczynski]], a Shropshire MP, is the tallest MP ever.\n\nAlthough having a slightly smaller percentage of the vote than the neighbouring [[East Midlands]], the geographic area of the West Midlands is more Conservative, due to Labour's vote now consigned to the urban areas of Birmingham, Coventry and Stoke-on-Trent. The number of seats is more favoured towards Labour than the geographic spread, with 35 Conservative seats and 24 Labour. All of Warwickshire, Staffordshire, Herefordshire, Worcestershire and Shropshire is now Conservative.\n\n{{Constituencies in the West Midlands}}\n\n===Eurostat NUTS===\nIn the [[Eurostat]] [[Nomenclature of Territorial Units for Statistics]] (NUTS), the West Midlands form a level-1 NUTS region, coded \"UKG\", which is subdivided as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:gold; text-align:left;\"\n! NUTS 1\n! Code\n! NUTS 2\n! Code\n! NUTS 3\n! Code\n|-\n| West Midlands\n| UKG\n| rowspan=3 | [[Herefordshire]], Worcestershire and [[Warwickshire]]\n| rowspan=3 | UKG1\n| [[Herefordshire]]\n| UKG11\n|-\n| rowspan=\"13\" colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:NUTS 3 regions of the West Midlands 2010 map.svg|240px]]\n| [[Worcestershire]] CC\n| UKG12\n|-\n| [[Warwickshire]] CC\n| UKG13\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | [[Shropshire]] and [[Staffordshire]]\n| rowspan=4 | UKG2\n| [[Telford and Wrekin]]\n| UKG21\n|-\n| [[Shropshire]]\n| UKG22\n|-\n| [[Stoke-on-Trent]]\n| UKG23\n|-\n| [[Staffordshire]] CC\n| UKG24\n|-\n| rowspan=7 | [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]\n| rowspan=7 | UKG3\n| [[Birmingham]]\n| UKG31\n|-\n| [[Metropolitan Borough of Solihull|Solihull]]\n| UKG32\n|-\n| [[Coventry]]\n| UKG33\n|-\n| [[Metropolitan Borough of Dudley|Dudley]] \n| UKG36\n|-\n| [[Sandwell]]\n| UKG37\n|-\n| [[Metropolitan Borough of Walsall|Walsall]]\n| UKG38\n|-\n| [[Wolverhampton]]\n| UKG39\n|}\n\n==Local government==\nThe [[Regions of England|region]] consists of the following administrative subdivisions:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Map || Ceremonial county || Shire county / unitary || Districts\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\" | [[File:West Midlands counties 2009 map.svg|250px]] || colspan=\"3\" | 1.&nbsp;[[Herefordshire]] U.A.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Shropshire]] || colspan=\"2\" | 2.&nbsp;[[Shropshire Council|Shropshire]] U.A.\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | 3.&nbsp;[[Telford and Wrekin]] U.A.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Staffordshire]] || 4.&nbsp;Staffordshire&nbsp;\u2020 || ''a'')&nbsp;[[Cannock Chase (district)|Cannock Chase]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[East Staffordshire]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Lichfield (district)|Lichfield]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[Newcastle-under-Lyme (borough)|Newcastle-under-Lyme]], ''e'')&nbsp;[[South Staffordshire]],  ''f'')&nbsp;[[Stafford (borough)|Stafford]], ''g'')&nbsp;[[Staffordshire Moorlands]], ''h'')&nbsp;[[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | 5.&nbsp;[[Stoke-on-Trent]] U.A.\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | 6.&nbsp;[[Warwickshire]]&nbsp;\u2020 || ''a'')&nbsp;[[North Warwickshire]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[Nuneaton and Bedworth]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Rugby (borough)|Rugby]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[Stratford-on-Avon (district)|Stratford-on-Avon]], ''e'')&nbsp;[[Warwick (district)|Warwick]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | 7.&nbsp;[[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]&nbsp;* || ''a'')&nbsp;[[Birmingham]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[Coventry]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Dudley (borough)|Dudley]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[Sandwell (borough)|Sandwell]], ''e'')&nbsp;[[Solihull (borough)|Solihull]], ''f'')&nbsp;[[Walsall (borough)|Walsall]], ''g'')&nbsp;[[Wolverhampton]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | 8.&nbsp;[[Worcestershire]]&nbsp;\u2020 || ''a'')&nbsp;[[Bromsgrove (district)|Bromsgrove]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[Malvern Hills (district)|Malvern Hills]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Redditch]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[Worcester]], ''e'')&nbsp;[[Wychavon]], ''f'')&nbsp;[[Wyre Forest (district)|Wyre Forest]]\n|}\n\nKey: \u2020two-tier [[non-metropolitan county]]  |  *[[metropolitan county]] including the [[West Midlands Combined Authority]] and [[Mayor of the West Midlands|mayor]]\n\n===Demography===\n[[File:Statue of St Michael and Satan -Coventry Cathedral-5July2008.jpg|thumb|right|Statue of St Michael and Satan at [[Coventry Cathedral]] ]]\n[[File:BirminghamUK skyline Centenary Square 700.jpg|right|thumb|Urban [[Birmingham]], [[Centenary Square]].]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Ceremonial County\n! Population\n! Population density\n! Largest local authority\n! Largest settlement\n|-\n| '''West Midlands (region)'''\n| '''5,267,337'''\n| '''405/km\u00b2'''\n| '''[[Birmingham]] (1,006,500)'''\n| '''Birmingham (1,006,500)'''\n|-\n| [[West Midlands (county)]]\n| 2,600,100\n| 2,884/km\u00b2\n| Birmingham (1,006,500)\n| Birmingham (1,006,500)\n|-\n| [[Staffordshire]]\n| 1,062,500\n| 391/km\u00b2\n| [[Stoke-on-Trent]] (240,636)\n| Stoke-on-Trent (259,252)\n|-\n| [[Worcestershire]]\n| 552,900\n| 318/km\u00b2\n| [[Wychavon]] (116,300)\n| [[Worcester]] (93,400)\n|-\n| [[Warwickshire]]\n| 522,200\n| 264/km\u00b2\n| [[Warwick (district)|Warwick]] (132,900)\n| [[Nuneaton]] (70,721)\n|-\n| [[Shropshire]]\n| 451,100\n| 129/km\u00b2\n| [[Shropshire Council|Shropshire]] (290,900)\n| [[Telford]] (138,241)\n|-\n| [[Herefordshire]]\n| 177,800\n| 82/km\u00b2\n| N/A<ref>County of [[Hereford]] forms single local government unit ([[Unitary Authority]])</ref>\n| [[Hereford]] (50,400)\n|}\n\nThe West Midlands' population accounts for almost 11% of England's overall population. 49.36% of the region's population resides in the West Midlands county, 20.17% in Staffordshire, 10.49% in Worcestershire, 9.91% in Warwickshire, 8.56% in Shropshire, and 3.37% in Herefordshire.\n\n==Economy==\n{{More citations needed section|date=January 2017}}\n{{overly detailed|section|date=December 2018}}\n[[File:JCB Chairman - Sir Anthony Bamford.JPG|thumb|upright|left|Lord Bamford, the wealthiest British-nationality businessman]]\n[[Business Link]] West Midlands<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businesslink.gov.uk/west_midlands.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005055307/http://www.businesslink.gov.uk/west_midlands.html|url-status=dead|title=Business Link|archivedate=5 October 2012}}</ref> was based on the Quinton Business Park in [[Quinton, Birmingham|Quinton]], next to [[Highways England]] and the M5 at the [[A456 road|A456]] Quinton Interchange. NHS West Midlands, the [[NHS strategic health authority|strategic health authority]] was on Hagley Road (A456) in Edgbaston. The [[West Midlands Ambulance Service]] is on the Waterfront Business Park in [[Brierley Hill]], off the [[A461 road|A461]], near the headquarters of [[West Midlands Police]], where the [[Child Support Agency]] (CSA) was headquartered. The region's [[Manufacturing Advisory Service]] was on [[Wolverhampton Science Park]] off the [[A449 road|A449]] north of the city centre; this function is now represented by [[Made in the Midlands]], off M4 junction 2 at Pendeford north of Wolverhampton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mas-wm.org/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122225314/http://www.mas-wm.org/|url-status=dead|title=MAS \u2013 Manufacturing Advisory Service|archivedate=22 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Department for International Trade|DIT]] West Midlands (previously [[UK Trade & Investment|UKTI]]) for the region<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ukti-teams-in-the-english-regions/ukti-west-midlands-helping-companies-export-and-grow-overseas|title=DIT West Midlands: helping companies export and grow overseas|first1=DIT West|last1=Midl|first2=find out how DIT can|last2=help|date=|website=GOV.UK|access-date=23 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170823204623/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ukti-teams-in-the-english-regions/ukti-west-midlands-helping-companies-export-and-grow-overseas|archive-date=23 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> is based at the [[West Midlands Chambers of Commerce]] on ''Harborne Road'' (B4284), south of NHS West Midlands west of Five Ways; this was previously at the B4100/B4114 junction south of Aston University near the Matthew Boulton Campus of [[Birmingham Metropolitan College]]. Most of the region is covered by the [[Midlands Air Ambulance]], except Warwickshire is covered by the [[Warwickshire & Northamptonshire Air Ambulance]], based at [[Coventry Airport]]; both are charity-funded. Sir [[Anthony Bamford]] of Staffordshire is the richest British industrialist, at around \u00a33.15bn in 2014; Sir [[James Dyson]] is second (\u00a33bn).\n\n===Herefordshire===\n[[File:Cider orchards east of Hereford 2 - geograph.org.uk - 899483.jpg|thumb|right|Bulmers cider orchard east of Hereford, near the [[River Wye]] ]]\n[[H. P. Bulmer|Bulmers Cider]] is in Hereford within walking distance of [[Hereford railway station|Hereford station]]; it is the world's largest [[cider]] factory, and has the world's largest vat (for [[Strongbow (cider)|Strongbow]]), built in 1975.  [[Painter Brothers]] (part of [[Balfour Beatty]]) on the Aydon Ind Est off the A49 near [[Hereford Racecourse]] in the north of Hereford, is the UK's largest manufacturer of electricity pylons ([[transmission tower]]s), [[Radio masts and towers|broadcasting mast]]s, the [[Callender-Hamilton bridge]], and [[Railway electrification in Great Britain|rail electrification]] structures. [[Henry Wiggin|Special Metals Wiggin]], part of [[Special Metals Corporation]], based at Hereford was the main producer of [[List of alloys|nickel alloys]] in Europe, with a large site directly north of Painter Brothers at the A49/A4103 junction; further north on the A49 at Moreton Business Park at [[Moreton-on-Lugg]] is GEA Denco (part of [[GEA Group]]) who make [[dehumidifier]]s.  The [[Special Reconnaissance Regiment]] was formed in 2005. At Hereford, [[Cargill Meat Solutions|Cargill Meats Europe]] (formerly Sun Valley) have a large poultry meat processing facility, processing chickens from around [[Herefordshire]].\n\n[[Cadbury]] (Mondel\u0113z International) make milk chocolate crumb near [[Marlbrook, Herefordshire|Marlbrook]] (near [[Leominster]]).  [[Weston's Cider]] is in [[Much Marcle]], south-west of [[Ledbury]] at the [[A449 road|A449]]/B4024 junction, who also make Stowford Press.  Wye Fruit Ltd is in the north of Ledbury on the B4214; in the west of the town, off the [[A417 road|A417]] bypass is a large site of [[Amcor]], and further west is Universal Beverages (UBL), owned by Heineken since 2007 where it cans cider; the site of Ledbury Preserves of RHM made [[Robertson's]] jam, mincemeat and marmalade and closed in 2008 when production moved to [[Histon and Impington|Histon]] in Cambridgeshire. [[Atora]] suet has been made in Ledbury since around 2003, when production was moved from Teesside by RHM to a former factory of [[Just Juice]], which was bought by [[Del Monte Foods|Del Monte]] in 1999.  Holden Aluminium Technologies are a sports car chassis manufacturer at [[Linton, Bringsty|Linton]] on the [[A44 road|A44]], east of [[Bromyard]].  [[Kingspan Group|Kingspan Insulation]] is based at [[Pembridge]], next to [[Shobdon Aerodrome]], west of [[Leominster]] off the A44.  BT's [[Madley Communications Centre]], claims to be the world's largest [[Ground station|earth station]].  [[Tyrrells (crisps)|Tyrrells Potato Crisps]] are off the B4457 at [[Dilwyn]] west of Leominster, near the A44.\n\n===Shropshire===\n[[Rayburn Range]] and [[Aga Rangemaster Group]] are based in [[Telford]]; the [[People's Dispensary for Sick Animals|PDSA]] is in [[St George's and Priorslee]], Telford next to the M54 near the B5061/A5 Priorslee Roundabout; opposite the [[M54]] on Stafford Park is [[Virgin Balloon Flights]].  [[Hymix]] who make mountable [[concrete mixer]]s are on the east of Stafford Park near the A464. The [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|MoD]] have a significant depot at [[Lilleshall and Donnington]].  There are also high-technology industries such as [[Unimation]], [[Nikon]], [[Hitachi Maxell]], [[Ricoh]], [[Capgemini]], [[Fujitsu]] and [[Electronic Data Systems]].  In [[Hadley Castle]] off the A442, [[Denso]] Manufacturing UK Ltd make [[Car air conditioning|car air-conditioning systems]] and [[GKN]] Wheels make car wheels.  Nearby is [[Ogihara Corporation|Ogihara]] Europe, a tool making ([[Die (manufacturing)|die]]s and [[Machine press|press]]) and metal-pressing company.  [[Makita]] Manufacturing Europe off the [[A518 road|A518]] at Hortonwood,  Telford is the only plant in the UK that makes [[power tool]]s.  [[Chequer Foods]] (owned by the Chiswick-based [[Autobar Group]]), off the A442 near the A4169 junction in [[Halesfield]] to the south, make food sachets for the foodservice industry and [[Operational Ration Pack|UK's military ration pack]]s.\n\n[[M\u00fcller (company)|M\u00fcller Dairy Ltd]] is based in [[Market Drayton]], and [[Palethorpes]], part of [[Pork Farms]] which makes own-label sausages, is on the same site on [[A53 road|A53]].  At [[Crudgington]], [[Dairy Crest]] made ''Country Life'' butter and [[Clover (spread)|Clover]] until February 2015, and have their Technical Centre.  Anglo Beef Processors ([[ABP Food Group]]) are at [[Harlescott]] in the north of Shrewsbury.  Nearby [[Stadco]], a metal pressings company, are based off the A5124 and next to the railway, on the [[Battlefield, Shropshire|Battlefield]] Ind Estate and have a site at [[Hadley Castle]], Telford off the [[A442 road|A442]]. [[Uniq plc]] have a plant on the [[A488 road|A488]] at [[Minsterley]] making chilled desserts for Tesco.\n\nBT have their [[National Network Management Centre]] (Whittington House) off the A495 near the A5 roundabout on the Oswestry bypass in [[Whittington, Shropshire]]. Military helicopter training in the UK takes place at [[RAF Shawbury]], alongside training for the RAF's [[air traffic controller]]s (ATC).\n\n===Staffordshire===\n[[File:JCB Diesel Max Heritage Motor Centre, Gaydon.jpg|thumb|left|[[JCB Dieselmax]], holder of the [[land speed record]] for diesel-engined vehicles]]\nThe brewing companies such as [[Molson Coors Brewing Company|Coors Brewers]] are in [[Burton on Trent]], as well as [[Marmite]], [[Marston's Brewery]], [[General Nutrition Centers|GNC UK]] ([[Dietary supplement|health supplements]]), and [[Doncasters]] (aerospace components and steel [[forging]], founded by [[Daniel Doncaster]] of Sheffield). [[Conder Structures]] is a structural steel company next to Marmite on the A5121, and further south [[Johnson Controls]] make seats for Toyota in [[Branston, Staffordshire|Branston]]. [[Spirit Pub Company]] (which demerged from Punch Taverns in August 2011, and owns [[Chef & Brewer]], [[Flaming Grill]] and [[Fayre & Square]]) is near the A5121/A38 junction, with [[Punch Taverns]] slightly further north. [[Marley Eternit]] (part of the Belgium [[Etex Group]]), who make [[Eternit]] [[fibre cement]] roofing (often seen on industrial buildings) are based on the west side of the A38 in the south of Branston, (with another large plant at the [[A525 road|A525]]/[[A531 road|A531]] junction in [[Madeley, Staffordshire|Madeley]] near the M6 at [[Keele]]); next door in [[Dunstall]], [[Lanxess]] UK (former W. Hawley) make pigments.\n\n[[File:Roundabout by Michelin Factory - geograph.org.uk - 336395.jpg|thumb|right|The Michelin Man ([[Bibendum]]) at Sideway in Stoke, with his name originating from the Latin phrase ''Nunc est bibendum'']]\n[[Newell Rubbermaid]] UK (owner of [[Parker Pen Company|Parker Pen]], [[Berol]], [[Paper Mate]] and [[DYMO Corporation|DYMO]]), [[Graco (baby products)|Graco]] ([[Baby transport|buggies]]), a large [[Distribution center|RDC]] of Tesco, and [[Zytek]] (motorsport) are at [[Fradley]] Park, next to the A38, on an [[RAF Lichfield|old airfield]]. [[Norgren (company)|Norgren]] (part of IMI) is an international [[pneumatics|pneumatic]] technology company on the A5192 in Lichfield.\n\nOff the A522 north of Cheadle is JCB Earthmovers ([[Loader (equipment)|wheel loader]]s) and JCB Compact Products (mini excavators and [[skid-steer loader]]s). [[JCB (company)|JCB]] is based in Staffordshire, near the [[Alton Towers]] colossal leisure park; JCB Heavy Products (excavators), and their World Parts Centre are off the A50 in [[Uttoxeter Rural]] ([[Beamhurst]]). Lafarge Cement UK (former [[Blue Circle Industries|Blue Circle]]) have a large plant at [[Cauldon]] in [[Waterhouses, Staffordshire|Waterhouses]], between the A523 and A52.\n\n[[Michelin]] Tyres are made in [[Sideway]] in Stoke-on-Trent, next to Stoke's only [[St Joseph's College, Stoke-on-Trent|grammar school]] in the south of [[Trent Vale]]. [[Royal Doulton]] and [[Wedgwood]] are based in [[Barlaston]]. [[Emma Bridgewater]] make pottery on the A50 in Hanley. [[Tile Giant]] (owned by Travis Perkins since 2007) is based on the B5039 in Longton, and [[Walkers' Nonsuch]] make toffee on the A5007. [[Portmeirion Pottery]], who own the [[Royal Worcester]] brand, are on the B5041 in Stoke. [[Steelite International]] (pottery) are based at [[Middleport, Staffordshire|Middleport]], in west Burslem, next to the [[Trent and Mersey Canal]]. [[Dudson]] (pottery) is on the A50 in the north end of Burslem, towards Tunstall. [[Johnson Tiles]] and [[Norcros Adhesives]] (owned by [[Norcros]]) is in the west of Tunstall. [[Wade Ceramics]] is in [[Etruria, Staffordshire|Etruria]] to the east of Wolstanton, near the A53/A500 junction off the A53, near the HQ of the Sentinel newspaper ([[DMG Media|Harmsworth Printing]]). [[Swan Products]] ([[teasmade]]s and small appliances, owned by Littlewoods) are based in [[Fenton, Staffordshire|Fenton]]. [[Premier Foods]] make [[Mr Kipling]] slices and [[Bakewell tart|Cherry Bakewells]] in Trent Vale in the south of Stoke-on-Trent.\n\n[[Bet365]] is on [[Stoke-on-Trent Garden Festival|Festival Park]] in [[Etruria, Staffordshire|Etruria]], off the [[A53 road|A53]], and is Stoke-on-Trent's largest private sector employer. [[Goodwin Steel Castings]] make steel [[Casting (metalworking)|casting]]s in the east of Stoke on the A52. [[The Co-operative Pharmacy]] National Distribution Centre is on the A50 at [[Meir, Staffordshire|Meir]], on the former site of [[Cookson Ceramics]] (later [[Johnson Matthey]] until its closure in 2003). [[Dechra Pharmaceuticals]] make [[Veterinary pharmacist|veterinary pharmaceutical]]s at [[Talke]], off the A34. [[Churchill China]] are at Sandyford near [[Tunstall, Staffordshire|Tunstall]] at the A50/[[A527 road|A527]] junction. [[Sumitomo Corporation|Sumitomo Electrical Wiring Systems (Europe)]], who supply wiring for the automotive industry, are in [[Silverdale, Staffordshire|Silverdale]], not far from [[Keele University]]. At [[Kidsgrove]] off the A34, [[Converteam]] (former GEC) make [[Adjustable-speed drive|variable speed drive]]s (VSDs); AAH Pharmaceuticals have their Enterprise and Trident divisions in [[Talke]], in the west of Kidsgrove, off the [[A5011 road|A5011]]. [[AWS Electronics]] have a factory, off the A34 north of Newcastle. [[Phones 4u]] was at [[Knutton]] in the north of [[Borough of Newcastle-under-Lyme|Newcastle-under-Lyme]] until it went bankrupt in 2014. Off the B5500 in [[Chesterton, Staffordshire|Chesterton]] in the north-west of Newcastle, [[Broxap]] are a leading supplier of [[cast iron]] [[street furniture]]. [[Andritz AG|Andritz]] UK (engineering) are at Wolstanton, off the A34 in the north of Newcastle.\n\n[[File:Marmite-Guinness edition.JPG|thumb|right|Marmite is made from the [[Yeast extract|yeast left over]] from the [[Beer in England|brewing industry]] ]]\n[[RoadChef]] are at [[Norton Canes]], near [[Cannock]]. Tallent Automotive (previously [[ThyssenKrupp]], now owned by [[Gestamp Automoci\u00f3n|Gestamp]] since 2011) make [[Suspension (vehicle)|car suspension]]s and [[crossmember]]s at Cannock. [[Electrium]] ([[Wylex]] [[Residual-current device|RCD]]s, and Crabtree and Volex electrical wiring) is on the A460 next to the M6 toll at [[Bridgtown]]. [[Mann+Hummel]] UK, on the A460 south of M54 junction 1 at [[Featherstone, Staffordshire|Featherstone]], make [[Air filter|air]] and [[oil filter]]s. [[Motivair]], who make [[air compressor]]s, is based off the A5190 in [[Burntwood]]; [[Mizkan]] Europe (who now own [[Branston (brand)|Branston Pickle]] in Suffolk) make vinegar. Armitage Shanks (owned by [[Ideal Standard]] International) are in the east of Rugeley off the A513 in [[Armitage with Handsacre]], near the WCML; JCB Cab Systems are next to the A51 on the Riverside Ind Est.\n\nThe UK headquarters of [[Alstom]] Grid (former [[Areva]] T&D UK, and [[General Electric Company plc|GEC]]) is based in [[Stafford]] as well as a factory and the UK headquarters of [[Bostik]] (a subsidiary of [[Total S.A.|TOTAL]]). Alstom Power repair electrical generators. [[Altecnic]], who work with [[Caleffi]] of Italy, is in the north of Stafford in [[Creswell, Staffordshire|Creswell]], off M6 junction 14, and supply [[Piping and plumbing fitting|plumbing fitting]]s. MICROMINIATURES on the B5026 in Stone claim to be Europe's leading supplier of [[ice cream van]] chime equipment.\n\n[[Invotec Group]], a [[Printed circuit board|PCB]] manufacturer, is based off the A51 in [[Dosthill]], south of Tamworth. [[Numark (pharmacy)|Numark Pharmacy]] is in [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]] (former base of [[Reliant]]). JVM Castings make [[crankcase]]s off the A51 at The Leys in Tamworth, and have a site in Worcester. [[Bristan]] (owned by [[Masco]]) based in [[Dordon]] and [[Baddesley Ensor]] on the Birch Coppice Business Park south-west of Tamworth, next to a new [[Ocado]] distribution centre, is the UK's largest supplier of kitchen and bathroom taps; Volkswagen Group (VAG UK) have their main UK distribution facility there, the site of [[Birch Coppice Colliery]] before 1987; nearby [[Maersk]] have their [[Birmingham Intermodal Freight Terminal]] (rail). [[Ansell]] UK ([[medical glove]]s, from Australia) is on Tamworth Enterprise Park, off the A51 next to the West Coast Main Line; they also produce [[Mates condoms]]. [[Lyalvale Express]] make [[Shotgun shell|shotgun cartridge]]s north of Tamworth next to the WCML at [[Fisherwick]]. [[Whittington Barracks]] (DMS Whittington) near to the west is the home of the [[Defence Medical Services]] and [[Defence Dental Service]], and soon the [[Defence Medical Services Training Centre]].\n\n[[Premier Foods]] make [[Bird's Custard]], [[Angel Delight]] and [[Marvel (food)|Marvel]] [[powdered milk]] in [[Knighton, Stafford, Staffordshire|Knighton]], west of [[Eccleshall]] near the Shropshire boundary. [[Static Systems Group]] (SSG) in Wombourne, south Staffordshire, make most of the [[Nurse call button|nurse call]] systems for the NHS. Kerrygold have a large cheese production site on the [[A53 road|A53]] in [[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]] on the [[Barnfields]] Industrial Estate.\n\nOn the Balliol Business Park, in [[Bilbrook, Staffordshire|Bilbrook]] and directly west of Fordhouses in Wolverhampton north of [[Pendeford]], Cargill process poultry (with another site at Hereford), and next door is [[Moog Inc.|Moog Aircraft]] ([[GE Aviation]] Systems before September 2009, which had bought [[Smiths Aerospace]] in May 2007) which makes [[Aircraft flight control system|flight control]] actuation systems (for the hydraulics on Boeing and Airbus), to move to the [[I54]] Business Park in Bilbrook; the Balliol Business Park was formerly the site of [[Boulton Paul Aircraft]], that made the [[Boulton Paul Defiant|Defiant]].\n\n===Warwickshire===\n[[File:Dennis Eagle works entrance, Heathcote Industrial Estate, Warwick-Leamington - geograph.org.uk - 1414920.jpg|thumb|left|Dennis Eagle bin wagon works at Warwick]]\n[[Bridgestone]] UK, [[Telent]] (near the A46 bypass), [[Calor Gas|Calor]] (on Tachbrook Park off the [[A452 road|A452]]), next to [[Co-operative Energy]] and near [[Magna Powertrain]] UK, [[Baxi]] (now owned by [[BDR Thermea]], and on the A429 near [[Warwick railway station]]) with [[Potterton (company)|Potterton]], [[Volvo Trucks]] UK (next to the A46 bypass) and a large data centre of [[IBM]] are in [[Warwick]]. [[Dennis Eagle]], who make bin wagons, are headquartered off the A452 on the [[Heathcote, Warwickshire|Heathcote]] Ind Estate, south of Calor Gas, in east Warwick towards Leamington. [[Godiva Fire Pumps|Godiva]] (former Hale Products Europe, part of the [[IDEX Corporation]]) are the UK's leading manufacturer of [[fire pump]]s off the [[A445 road|A445]] in [[Emscote]], east Warwick.\n\n[[File:IBM Warwick - geograph.org.uk - 1588694.jpg|thumb|right|IBM at Warwick]]\n[[Aga Rangemaster Group]] is on the north of Leamington Spa Business Park, and directly south is [[Wolseley UK]]; [[Gruppo Raicam|Raicam Clutches]] ([[Automotive Products]]) is south of Wolseley; to the west [[Grupo Antolin]] UK make vehicle interiors; on the same estate is Caparo AP Braking, and [[Delphi Automotive]] have an electronics centre. On the [[Warwick Technology Park]], south of Warwick on the [[A425 road|A425]], are [[Phillips 66]] UK (former ConocoPhillips) who own [[Jet (brand)|JET UK]] (petrol); to the east is [[McKesson Corporation|McKesson]]'s European HQ (who produce the software for the NHS's 1.4&nbsp;million employees' payroll \u2013 the largest payroll in the UK),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electronicstaffrecord.nhs.uk/|title=Electronic Staff Record|author=|date=|website=www.electronicstaffrecord.nhs.uk|access-date=19 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150629110106/http://www.electronicstaffrecord.nhs.uk/|archive-date=29 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and to the west is Tulip (who produce [[Spam (food)|SPAM]], with Plumrose and Danepak) in the UK and are owned by [[Danish Crown AmbA|Danish Crown Group]] \u2013 Europe's largest pork producer, near [[Midcounties Co-operative]] which is next to the wireless division of [[Arqiva]]; [[National Grid plc]] is in the centre of the park, and [[Allinea]] Software is at the Innovation Centre.\n\n[[File:NFU Mutual Headquarters, Tiddington - geograph.org.uk - 1727835.jpg|thumb|left|NFU Mutual headquarters at Tiddington, east of Stratford-upon-Avon]]\n[[NFU Mutual]] is in [[Tiddington, Warwickshire|Tiddington]] near Stratford and the [[National Farmers Union (England and Wales)|NFU]] is in [[Stoneleigh, Warwickshire|Stoneleigh]]; [[The Pony Club]] and other parts of the [[British Equestrian Federation]] are in Stoneleigh. [[AGCO]] Limited UK and its European Operations Centre is nearby at [[Stareton]], who own [[Massey Ferguson]] with [[Valtra]] UK; the large factory at Coventry closed in 2002. The [[British Horse Society]] is in [[Kenilworth]]. At [[Cubbington]] is the UK headquarters of [[Joma]], and has the Thwaites [[dumper]] manufacturer. [[Caparo Vehicle Technologies]] is off the [[B4087 road]] towards Leamington Spa. [[Codemasters]] is off the A425 in [[Long Itchington]], east of Leamington, opposite the 600-acre [[RLS Polo Club]]; directly east of Leamington on the A425 is Ricardo's [[Midlands Technical Centre]]. [[Recaro]] UK (car seats) is off the [[A4177 road|A4177]] next to a [[RAF Honiley|former airfield]] (now a proving ground), west of Kenilworth. Further north, the University of Warwick, on the Coventry/Warwickshire boundary, is home to the [[WMG (formerly Warwick Manufacturing Group)|Warwick Manufacturing Group]] technology consultancy and the [[Tata Motors]] European Technical Centre.\n\n[[SRS Frigadon]], off the [[A3400 road|A3400]] (former A34) at [[Atherstone on Stour]], is an Anglo-Swedish refrigeration company that makes [[chiller]]s and heat exchangers.\n\n[[File:Entrance to Daw Mill Colliery - geograph.org.uk - 210862.jpg|thumb|right|In 2008, the former [[Daw Mill]] colliery produced 3.2&nbsp;million tonnes of coal, a UK record]]\n[[BMW]] have their main European [[Straight-4|four-cylinder engine]] plant at [[Hams Hall]] near the M42. [[Subaru]] UK and [[Isuzu]] UK (IM Group) are sandwiched between the M6 and the M42 (south of junction 8) at the Coleshill Manor Office Campus, west of [[Coleshill, Warwickshire|Coleshill]]. Off the B4117 in the north of Coleshill is [[Thomas & Betts]] UK (former [[Adaptaflex]]), which makes [[Electrical conduit|flexible conduit]]s. [[TNT N.V.|TNT]] UK is off the B4116 in the west of [[Atherstone]], and [[Aldi]] UK is on the other side of the road; Aldi opened its first UK store on 17 July 1990 in Stechford, Birmingham, and now has around 700 UK stores. [[3M]] have an [[abrasive]] products ([[sandpaper]]) factory in the east of the town. [[Daw Mill]], next to the [[Birmingham to Peterborough Line|railway]], was Britain's biggest coal producer near the B4098/B4114 junction at [[Arley, Warwickshire|Arley]] and [[Over Whitacre]]. [[Holland & Barrett]] are Europe's largest health food chain, with 1,400 stores.  [[Triton Showers]] (the UK's largest shower company) are based in [[Nuneaton]]; [[Adams Childrenswear]], formerly on the A4254 on the [[Attleborough, Warwickshire|Attleborough]] Fields Ind Est, closed most of its stores in 2010.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nSouth of Nuneaton, at the [[A444 road|A444]]/B4113 roundabout is the national distribution centre of [[Dairy Crest]], where it also packages [[Cathedral City Cheddar|Cathedral City]] cheese. North of Coventry, [[Oleo International]] (its name is from the [[Oleo strut]]) is a world leader in [[Buffer (rail transport)|railway buffer]]s based on the B4113 in [[Exhall]], next to the M6. The [[London congestion charge]] is operated by Capita, based at Prologis Park (Bedworth) in the west of Exhall. [[Rolls-Royce plc|Rolls-Royce]] have a large engine overhaul plant (former [[Armstrong Siddeley]]), near [[Ansty, Warwickshire|Ansty]] and the M6/M69 junction in [[Coombe Fields]], which also makes their engine casings, built on a [[RAF Ansty|former airfield]]; [[Ansty Park]] is a new development on the same former airfield.\n\n[[Aston Martin]] and [[Jaguar Land Rover Gaydon Centre|Land Rover]] have their headquarters in [[Gaydon]]. Nearby to the south in the same area as the [[Battle of Edgehill]] (1642) west of the M40 is [[MoD Kineton]] (former [[Defence Storage and Distribution Agency]] or DSDA Kineton, now part of [[Defence Equipment and Support]] or DE&S), home of the Army School of Ammunition and [[Defence Explosive Ordnance Disposal, Munitions and Search Training Regiment]] which teaches [[bomb disposal]] (Improvised Explosive Device Disposal); on the opposite site of the B4086 is [[Marlborough Barracks]] and [[Defence Munitions Centre]] Kineton.\n\n[[File:Rugby-Millbuck House - geograph.org.uk - 1012751.jpg|thumb|right|Morgan Sindall Construction HQ on Corporation Street (B4632) in Rugby]]\n[[GE Power Conversion]] UK (former Alstom, then Converteam) and [[Morgan Sindall]] Construction & Infrastructure (former [[Morgan Est]]) are in [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]]. [[Alstom]] have their Power and Transport division in the north of Rugby on the [[A426 road|A426]], where they service [[steam turbine]]s; on the Swift Valley Ind Estate [[Premier Foods]] have their national distribution centre; on the same estate [[Ball Corporation|Ball Packaging Europe]] UK have a main plant ([[tin can]]s), and nearby are [[Mors\u00f8 (company)|Mors\u00f8]] UK ([[wood-burning stove]]s). The European HQ of [[Gap (clothing retailer)|Gap]] is in the north of Rugby, alongside the M6 in [[Churchover]]; Gap is the world's third-biggest fashion retailer, with 118 stores in the UK. [[CEMEX]] have the country's largest cement works, west of Rugby at the junction of the A428 and the [[A4071 road|A4071]] western bypass towards [[Long Lawford]] (former [[Rugby Cement]]).\n\n===West Midlands county===\n{{more footnotes|date=December 2018}}\n;In Central Birmingham\n*[[Mitchells and Butlers]] in [[pub chain|pubs, inns and restaurants]].\n*The [[Insolvency Service]]'s Intelligence and Enforcement Directorate.<ref>Intelligence and Enforcement Directorate, The Insolvency Service, 18 The Priory Queensway, Birmingham</ref>\n*[[Stamp duty in the United Kingdom|Stamp Duty Land Tax and stamp duty on shares]]<ref>HMRC Stamp Duty Taxes, [[City Centre House]], Birmingham</ref>\n*[[Ofwat]] in water;<ref>Ofwat, [[Centre City Tower (Birmingham)|Centre City Tower]], Birmingham</ref> relatedly in subject: the [[Consumer Council for Water]].<ref>The Consumer Council for Water, [[Victoria Square, Birmingham|Victoria Square]], Birmingham</ref>\n*National Debtline<ref>Tricorn House, 51\u201353 Hagley Rd, Birmingham \u2013 specifically near [[Five Ways, Birmingham|Five Ways]].</ref>\n*The [[Solicitors Regulation Authority]]<ref>SRA, [[The Cube (building)|The Cube]], Birmingham part of the Mailbox.</ref>\n*[[H. Samuel]], jewellers.<ref>H. Samuel, Hunters Road, [[Hockley, Birmingham|Hockley]] within the [[Jewellery Quarter]], Birmingham since 1912 http://www.hsamuel.co.uk/about_us {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180114183930/http://www.hsamuel.co.uk/about_us/ |date=14 January 2018 }}</ref>\n*[[J Hudson & Co]] the world's largest producer of [[whistle]]s make [[Acme Whistles]].<ref>J Hudson & Co 244 Barr Street, Boulton Middleway, Birmingham, namely in the Jewellery Quarter where the A41 and A4540 meet.</ref>\n*Deakin & Francis make [[cufflink]]s.<ref>Founded 1786, headquarters: Deakin & Francis, 15\u201317 Regent Pl, Birmingham</ref>\n*[[National Express]] and [[CrossCountry]] in transport.<ref>The latter at [[Cannon House, Birmingham|Cannon House]]</ref>\n\n;Car Manufacturers\n[[File:Jaguar sign 19o06.jpg|thumb|right|The leaping jaguar mascot outside the car company's head office south of Coventry]]\n*[[Land Rover]] [[Solihull plant|main factory]]<ref name=sh>[[Solihull]]</ref>\n*[[Jaguar Cars]], [[Peugeot]] UK (inc. [[Peugeot Technical Centre]]) and Citroen UK & Ireland<ref>Head office, B4110 at [[Stoke Aldermoor]]</ref> [[Whitley plant|Jaguar Land Rover Engineering Centre]]; [[Jaguar Land Rover]] have a large manufacturing plant at [[Castle Bromwich Assembly]] making the [[Jaguar XJ|XJ]], [[Jaguar XF|XF]] and [[Jaguar XK|XK]]. The Jaguar Veneer Manufacturing Centre.<ref>Jaguar Land Rover, [[Whitley, Coventry]]</ref>\n\n;Nearest Birmingham\n[[File:Cadbury Factory, Bournville - geograph.org.uk - 1266844.jpg|thumb|right|Cadbury in Birmingham]]\n*[[Cadbury]]'s main plant and [[Cadbury World]] remains in [[Bournville]], Birmingham; since 2012 owned by [[Mondel\u0113z International]]; today many executive functions are in [[Zurich]]; some milk chocolate is output from Fabryka w Jankowicach, Poland; [[Bournville (chocolate bar)|most dark]] for more than 10 years from France. \n*[[Dollond & Aitchison]] opticians and optical products [[Aston]]<ref>D&A, Aston Cross Business Park, 50 Rocky Lane, Aston, Birmingham, B6 5RQ</ref>\n*[[ATS Euromaster]] automotive repairs are in<ref>ATS Euromaster, [[Aston]], Birmingham</ref>\n*B Mason & Sons produce rolled copper and [[cupronickel]] alloy precision strips; applications include [[submarine communication cable]]s, coaxial cables and associated waveguides, contacts and heatsinks.<ref>Wharf Street, Aston, Birmingham</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bmason.co.uk/internet/media/training/quality/data_sheets/C103_Datasheet.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=12 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113035550/http://www.bmason.co.uk/internet/media/training/quality/data_sheets/C103_Datasheet.pdf |archive-date=13 January 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[Kiepe Electric]] UK (former Vossloh-Kiepe)<ref>Kiepe Electric, Aston Science Park, Birmingham</ref>\n*[[Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company|Goodyear Tyres]]<ref>Goodyear, 2920 Trident Court, Solihull Parkway, Birmingham Business Park, Birmingham</ref>\n*[[Dunlop Aircraft Tyres]] manufacture and retread<ref>40 Fort Pkwy, Birmingham</ref> \n*[[Claire's]] (accessories) European head office is off the A4040 at Erdington. \n*[[Royal Society for the Prevention of Accidents]] in training, surveying and policy advice.<ref>RoSPA, 28 Calthorpe Rd, Birmingham \u2013 specifically in [[Calthorpe Fields]] in north Edgbaston, next to [[St George's School, Birmingham|St George's School]]</ref>\n;Outskirts of County\n*[[GKN Driveline]] produce [[constant-velocity joint]]s<ref>Headquartered in Redditch, GKN Driveline its UK plant at the A38/[[A452 road|A452]] roundabout in [[Tyburn, West Midlands|Tyburn]], north of the JLR plant.</ref>\n*Stadco UK, metal pressing<ref>at [[Bromford]] off the A47.</ref>\n*Concentric UK produce [[Oil pump (internal combustion engine)|oil]] and water pumps for small diesel engines, off the A38 in [[Gravelly Hill]].\n*[[HiQ (tyres)|HiQ]], tyre merchants.\n*[[VDO (company)|VDO]] make fuel systems.\n*[[UK Mail]]<ref>Office/depot at the A47/A4040 junction next to the River Tame at [[Ward End]] near M6, and next to the former [[LDV Group|LDV]] factory.</ref>\n*[[Genting Group]] UK casinos<ref>Genting Group, [[Star City (entertainment complex)|Star City]] near Washwood Heath.</ref>\n*[[Dana Holding Corporation|Dana Traction Technologies]] make axles (including that of the [[Ford Transit]] and [[Range Rover]]) and [[limited slip differential]]s<ref>Dana Traction Technologies, [[Witton, West Midlands|Witton]]</ref>\n*[[Titanium Metals|TIMET]] UK. \n*[[SCC (Specialist Computer Centres)]] (computing)<ref>A41 at the [[River Cole, West Midlands|River Cole]] bridge</ref>\n*[[Goodrich Corporation|Goodrich Engine Controls]] make [[Engine control unit|engine control systems]] for jet engines<ref>Goodrich Engine Controls, [[Hall Green]], Birmingham</ref>\n*[[Pilkington]] Automotive make [[Triplex Safety Glass]]<ref>in [[Kings Norton]]</ref>\n*[[Alcoa]] plant<ref>[[Kitts Green]] (towards Solihull), next to the [[River Cole, West Midlands|River Cole]].</ref>\n*Small-scale production of [[MG (car)|MG]] by [[Nanjing Automobile (Group) Corporation|Nanjing Automobile Group]] on part of the former [[MG Rover Group]] site<ref>at [[Longbridge]].</ref>\n*Webasto Roof Systems<ref>is on the A4097 in Minworth</ref>\n*[[Hozelock]] make [[hose coupling]]s, sprayguns, sprinklers and rain/grey water pumps<ref>Hozelock, Midpoint Park Birmingham</ref>\n*[[Schaeffler Group]] UK (inc. [[INA (company)|INA]]) make [[timing belt (camshaft)|timing belt]]s and [[Automobile wheel bearing|wheel bearing]]s)for wind turbines, passenger cars and aircraft<ref>Maypoint Business Park, next to the railway on the opposite side of the A38</ref>\n*[[The Works (retailer)]] distribution centre, books, puzzles, toys and games<ref>Midpoint Park, south of A38</ref> \n*The [[Defence Infrastructure Organisation]] (former Defence Estates)<ref>[[Sutton Coldfield]]</ref>\n*[[Legrand (company)|Legrand]] UK make electrical switches)<ref>Legrand based at the A41/A4540 junction at [[Newtown, Birmingham|Newtown]] south of Aston.</ref> \n*[[Delcam]] ([[Computer-aided technologies|CAD/CAM]] software)<ref>at [[Small Heath, Birmingham|Small Heath]] Trading Est off the A45.</ref> \n*[[Eaton Corporation|Eaton Electric]] make [[residual-current device]]s<ref>Birmingham</ref> \n*[[Cutler-Hammer]] and [[Switchgear]]<ref>[[Tyseley]]</ref>\n*TRW Automotive Electronics<ref>TRW Automotive Electronics, A453 north of the M6 at [[Perry Barr]].</ref> \n*[[Highways England]] [[National Traffic Control Centre]]<ref>Highways England, [[Quinton, Birmingham|]], Birmingham.</ref> \n*[[Ishida (company)|Ishida]] Europe makes industrial [[multihead weigher]]s and food processing equipment<ref>Ishida, [[Woodgate, Birmingham|Woodgate]] Business Park</ref>\n*[[Lander Automotive]] make pipes for automotive cooling systems;\n*[[Aisin Seiki Co.|Aisin Europe Manufacturing]]\n*[[Keiper]] UK automotive seating\n\n;Near other main towns\n*[[Severn Trent]] (water)<ref>Severn Trent, 2 St John Street, Coventry</ref>\n*[[Saint-Gobain]] UK is based at Binley Business Park, in the same building as [[Jewson]] (owned by Saint-Gobain, who also own [[Graham Group]]). \n*[[Coventry Building Society]] nearby [[Jewson]], off the B4428, is in the east of the city at [[Binley, Coventry|Binley]]. \n*[[E.ON UK]] (former Powergen)\n*[[Molins (company)|Molins]] [[Innovative Technology for Custom Machinery|ITCM]] research centre\n*[[Chartered Institute of Housing]]\n*[[PCMS]] (retail software)\n*[[Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors|RICS]] UK<ref>Westwood Business Park in [[Westwood Heath]]</ref>\n*[[Bladon Jets]] develop micro [[gas turbine]]s and were the first to develop an [[Axial compressor|axial flow]] micro example in 1994.<ref>Bladon Jets, Pinley</ref>\n*[[Halfords Autocentre]]<ref name=sh/>\n*[[Motaquip Limited]] UYT [[body in white]] automotive components.\n*[[Axeon]] UK distributes [[lithium-ion battery|litium-ion batteries]]<ref>Axeon UK, Coventry</ref>\n\n[[Speciality Fibres and Materials]] developed [[Lyocell]] (Tencel) in the 1980s.<ref>SFM, [[Foleshill]]</ref>\n*[[Morgan Advanced Materials Composites and Defence Systems]], make the [[British Army]]'s helmet \u2013 the [[Mk 7 helmet]] and electronics for the [[Cougar (vehicle)]], as well as body armour for the police.<ref>[[Edgwick]] and [[Great Heath]]</ref>\n*[[Bystronic]] UK makes [[laser cutting]] equipment<ref>Wayside Business Park, [[Longford, Coventry]]</ref>\n*Magnetto-Topy make car wheels<ref name=wp>[[Whitmore Park]], Coventry</ref>\n*[[Stadco]] UK design division<ref name=wp/>\n*Pailton Engineering make [[steering column]]s and [[steering linkage]]s<ref name=wp/>\n*[[Meggitt Aircraft Braking Systems]] (MABS) see [[List of aircraft braking systems|Braking Systems]]; related [[Meggitt Thermal Systems]] produce aircraft [[ice protection system]]s.<ref name=wp/> \n*[[Brose (company)|Brose]] UK makes [[Mechatronics|mechatronic]] [[Power window|window regulator]]s and seat adjustors<ref>Bayton Road</ref>\n*The [[Education and Skills Funding Agency]], and [[National Apprenticeship Service]]. \n*[[AAH Pharmaceuticals]] and [[Lloyds Pharmacy]], owned by [[Celesio]].<ref name=wt>At [[Walsgrave]] Triangle</ref>\n*[[Sainsbury's]]: ''TU'' clothing distribution.<ref name=wt/>\n*[[Georg Fischer (Swiss company)|+GF+ AgieCharmilles]] (machine tools).<ref name=wt/> \n*[[Rohm and Haas]] UK makes materials for [[printed circuit board]]s<ref>[[Binley, Coventry|Binley]]</ref>\n*[[British Chambers of Commerce]], a representative and awards-giving corporate membership organisation. \n*[[Walkers (snack foods)]] within their corn and wheat products ranges<ref>Middlemarch Business Park, [[Baginton]] next to Coventry Airport</ref>\n*[[Gefco]] UK (owned by Peugeot); \n*[[Webasto]]-Edscha Cabrio UK make [[convertible]] car roofs. \n*[[Terex]] Construction makes [[backhoe loader]]s, [[Telescopic handler|telehandler]]s, site dumpers and other construction equipment.<ref name=pp>Prologis Park, Coventry</ref> \n*Co-op National Distribution Centre for the bulk of England<ref name=pp/>\n\n[[File:MuedaGas 0126.jpg|thumb|left|A [[Land Rover Defender]] in eastern Africa, made in Solihull]]\nThe [[Forensic Science Service]], [[Linpac]], [[Lafarge (company)|Lafarge Cement UK]] and [[IMI plc]] (former [[ICI Metals Division]]) are on the Birmingham Business Park in [[Bickenhill]], near the airport; the [[National Exhibition Centre]] (NEC) is just north, between the airport and the M42. [[Lafarge Tarmac]] is in Marston Green, [[Bickenhill]]; [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF Lemf\u00f6rder UK]]'s site at Bickenhill makes axle modules for Land Rover off the B4438 north of the NEC, near the new site of [[Tarmac (company)|Tarmac]] (after the Lafarge merger). [[Newey and Eyre]], Britain's largest electrical wholesaler and part of [[Rexel]] UK, is at Sheldon on the [[A45 road|A45]] near the airport. [[Neopost]] UK is off the A452. [[Goodrich Corporation|Goodrich UK]] is in [[Shirley, West Midlands|Shirley]]. [[Prologis]] UK, [[Intersport]] UK (on the Cranmore Ind Est), and [[Enterprise Inns]] are on the A34 in [[Monkspath]]; next door is [[Trelleborg Sealing Solutions]] UK; [[TRW Automotive|TRW Conekt]] have a main automotive engineering research centre (with Girling Brakes, at the former Lucas Research Centre) at the A34/B4102 roundabout at The Green Business Park in Shirley Heath, further north on the A34 from Enterprise Inns, on other side of the road. The Mormons (Latter Day Saints) have their European HQ in Solihull near the [[Heart of England NHS Foundation Trust|hospital]], on the B4025 opposite Morrisons. [[Amtico]] (flooring) is based in the south of Solihull, with a main factory in [[Foleshill]], Coventry. [[Compin]] UK, with [[Fainsa]], are in Solihull, and make train and bus seats.\n\n[[File:Former Staffordshire Building Society Offices.jpg|thumb|right|Carillion head office in Wolverhampton]]\n[[Carillion]] in construction<ref>Wolverhampton [[Wolverhampton Ring Road|ring-road]] (A4150)</ref>\n[[Tarmac Group]] was on the A4039 south-east of the city centre in [[Ettingshall]] until 2012 when it merged with Lafarge. [[Marston's Brewery|Marston's]] is headquartered west of the ring road, on the A41, and have the [[Park Brewery]] on the A4124, east of the city centre. The UK's [[VAT Registration Service]], for [[Value Added Tax (United Kingdom)|Value Added Tax]] is at HMRC in Wolverhampton on the opposite side of the [[Wolverhampton Ring Road]] (A4150) to the HQ of Marstons, on the west side of the town centre. [[Flint Group|Flint Ink]] UK in the east of the town centre, former [[Mander Brothers]], was the largest ink supplier in the [[British Empire]], before being bought in 1998. [[BAE Systems Land & Armaments]] (former [[Alvis plc|Alvis]] Bridging and Vickers Armstrong) formerly on the A4126 in [[Ettingshall]], near the former Tarmac site, closed at the end of 2011. In [[Fordhouses]], along the [[A449 road|A449]] to the north, are [[HS Marston]] (part of the former [[Hamilton Sundstrand]], now [[UTC Aerospace Systems]]) makes [[heat exchanger]]s, [[Goodrich Corporation|Goodrich Actuation Systems]] (the former Actuation Division of Lucas Aerospace and [[H. M. Hobson]]), and a new engine plant for JLR. Goodrich in the UK, is what became of Lucas before a takeover by Goodrich; Lucas Aerospace was a world leader in flight control actuation for civil aircraft.\n\n[[File:Steel Distribution Depot - geograph.org.uk - 236054.jpg|thumb|left|Wednesfield Steelpark in September 2006]]\nOn the Staffordshire boundary, to the west on the Pendeford Business Park, are [[ADAS (company)|ADAS]] (previously on the A41 in [[Wergs]]), [[Gunnebo Security Group|Gunnebo]] UK ([[Automated cash handling|cash handling]]) and [[Birmingham Midshires]]. [[Turner Powertrain Systems]] is the world market leader for transmissions for [[backhoe loader]]s, mini [[excavator]]s [[telescopic handler]]s, and site dumpers is further south, to the west of the A449 near [[Dunstall Hill]]. [[Hampson Industries]] is in [[Brierley Hill]]. Wednesbury Tube (part of [[Mueller Industries]]) make [[Copper tubing|copper pipe]] on the A41 in Bilston at the Key Ind Est near the [[Loxdale tram stop]], and its sister company [[Primaflow]] makes brass fittings in Nechells. On the A4124, Tata Steel (former site of British Steel Seamless Tubes until 1995) have their [[Wednesfield Steelpark]] (the UK's biggest steelyard, built by Corus in 1999) on the Walsall boundary.\n\n[[Boss Design]] is a furniture manufacturer in Blowers Green, Dudley at the [[A461 road|A461]]/A459 roundabout. [[KUKA]] Robotics UK, a maker of industrial robots, and [[Joseph Ash]] (galvinizers) are off the A459 at [[Mucklow Hill]] in Halesowen, with [[Floors-2-Go]] based off the [[A458 road|A458]]; [[Sandvik]] Coromant UK (Swedish machine cutting tools, who provide Birmingham's [[Christmas tree]]) are off junction 3 of the M5 on the A456. Hingley Trailers (former M+G Trailers before 2009) makes [[Semi-trailer|trailer]]s on the [[A458 road|A458]] in [[Lye, West Midlands|Lye]]. [[Marcegaglia]] UK make electrical-resistance welded steel tubes off the [[A461 road|A461]] in Dudley. [[Essar Group|Essar Steel]] UK (former [[Servosteel]]) on the A4101 Pensnett Road in west Dudley, is the largest independent steel toll processor in the UK. [[Rentokil Initial|Initial Cleaning Services]] (Facilities) is based on the Ashmore Ind Estate, at the [[A461 road|A461]]/A459 Castle Gate Island roundabout, opposite the [[Showcase Cinemas|Showcase]] cinema on the Castle Gate Leisure Park. The [[Merry Hill Shopping Centre]], similar to [[Meadowhall (shopping centre)|Meadowhall]] in [[Sheffield]], is built on a large former steelworks, the [[Round Oak Steelworks]].\n\n[[Avery Weigh-Tronix]] is on the site of James Watt's [[Soho Foundry]] in [[Smethwick]]; [[Interlink Express]] (and its parent [[GeoPost]] UK) is on Summit Crescent Ind Estate off the [[A4252 road|A4252]], north of [[Smethwick Galton Bridge railway station]], next to the M5. [[Hadley Group]] near the Soho Foundry is the largest [[Rolling (metalworking)|cold roll forming]] manufacturer in the UK. J. B. & S. Lees makes [[Strip steel|steel strip]] at the Trident Steel Works in Albion, West Bromwich off the B4166 and also by [[Firth Cleveland]] at the B4517/B4163 junction in Tipton further up the Birmingham Canal. Caparo Precision Tubes between the M5 and A4182 in Oldbury, is the UK's largest producer of [[Electric resistance welding|electric resistance welded]] (ERW) steel tubes, and [[Wellman Group]] make boilers off the A457 to the west. [[Metsec]], east of Oldbury (owned by [[Voestalpine]]), is one of the UK's largest [[Rolling (metalworking)|cold roll-forming]] companies. [[Conex B\u00e4nninger]] (former IBP Conex), on the B4166 in New Town, west of West Bromwich on Birmingham Canal, make pipe and [[compression fitting]]s. [[Rhodia (company)|Rhodia]]'s Oldbury site on the B4170 in [[Langley Green, West Midlands|Langley Green]], south of Oldbury and east of the M5 is a world-leading site (former [[Albright and Wilson]]) in phosphorus-based chemistry. The AA have a main office on the A4123 at the A4034 roundabout in [[Rounds Green]], west of Oldbury. [[BIP Chemicals]] (former British Cyanides) at Oldbury are the oldest polymer manufacturer in the UK. STILL UK ([[KION Group]]) is in [[Harvills Hawthorn]], [[Golds Hill]] at the A461/A41 roundabout, north-west of West Bromwich; further along the A41 is [[2 Sisters Food Group]], Britain's largest processor of chicken. Nesbit Evans in the east of Wednesbury, off the A41, are a main manufacturer of hospital beds, owned by [[ArjoHuntleigh]].\n\n[[File:Chubb building.jpg|thumb|left|Willenhall is the lockmaking capital of the UK, and the home of Chubb]]\nThe national headquarters of [[One Stop]] is on the A4124 in [[Brownhills]], at [[Clayhanger, West Midlands|Clayhanger]]. [[Homeserve]] is in the north of Walsall on the [[A34 road|A34]], opposite Walsall Retail Park; next door to the north, on the other side of the [[Wyrley and Essington Canal]] on the B4210, on the edge of [[Blakenall Heath]], is [[Eagle Envelopes]], part of [[Mayer-Kuvert]], Europe's leading envelope manufacturer. [[Imperial Bathroom Company]], on the Empire Ind Est off the B4152 in [[Leighswood]], is in the north of Walsall borough; next door is [[RMD Kwikform]] (scaffolding) on the opposite side of [[Rushall Canal]]; to the south was GKN Driveline Walsall from 1953 until 2010, which was the largest independent manufacturer of [[Constant-velocity joint|CV-jointed]] [[Drive shaft|propshaft]]s in Europe. [[Poundland]] is in [[Willenhall]], on the side of the [[Black Country Route]] ([[A454 road|A454]]) towards the M6 junction 11. [[Wedge Group]], based on the B4484 in Willenhall, is the largest [[Hot-dip galvanizing|hot dip galvanising]] company in the UK. [[Assa Abloy]] UK (and [[Yale (company)|Yale]] UK, former Yale & Towne), owned by a Swedish company, is off the A454 at the B4464 roundabout in Willenhall, as the town is known for manufacture of locks; close by is [[A.F. Blakemore]], which supplies most of the [[Spar (retailer)|SPAR]] shops in the UK. [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF Lemf\u00f6rder UK]] make chassis components (a main competitor to GKN), in the east of Darlaston, with [[Caparo]] Atlas Fastenings off the A4038.\n{{clear}}\n\n===Worcestershire===\n{{see also|Manufacturing in Worcester}}\n[[File:Worcester Bosch - geograph.org.uk - 57948.jpg|thumb|right|Worcester Bosch; Bosch Thermotechnology are in [[Warndon]] ]]\nIn Redditch are [[Halfords]], on the B4497 to the south in [[Washford, Worcestershire|Washford]], and [[GKN]] (it has the second largest turnover in the West Midlands) is on the [[A441 road|A441]] in [[Riverside, Worcestershire|Riverside]]. CompAir Hydrovane, who make [[Rotary vane pump|rotary vane]] compressors, are on the [[Districts of Redditch|Washford]] Ind Estate near the B4497/A453 junction in Redditch. [[Mettis Aerospace]] are on the B4184 in Enfield, north Redditch, and make light metal components (the former [[High Duty Alloys Ltd.|High Duty Alloys]], which made most of the [[Forging|forged]] pistons for Britain's aircraft engines in WWII). [[Hymatic]] (part of Honeywell Defense and Space) make world-leading [[cryocooler]]s, on Moon's Moat Ind Est, in the north-east of Redditch; on same site the [[KAC Alarm Company]], also part of Honeywell, make [[Manual fire alarm activation|break glass call points]] for [[Fire alarm system|fire alarm]]s; they innovated them in the 1970s, and are global leaders. [[Magna International|Magna Interior Systems]] make the cockpit module ([[dashboard]]) for the MINI. [[Henry Milward & Sons|Entaco]] make needles for hand sewing and medical purposes in the south of Redditch on the Washford Ind Est. Directly east of Redditch in [[Beoley]] is [[Lear Corporation]] UK, who make car seats. [[Phoenix Group (company)|Phoenix Group]] (non-public [[Life insurance|life assurance]] schemes) is off the A435 in the north-east of the county near the Warwickshire boundary, at [[Wythall]], and has a large turnover; nearby to west [[Metalrax]], headquartered in [[Alvechurch]] near the M42, make (via subsidiaries) most of the [[Cookware and bakeware|bakeware]] sold in the UK.\n\n[[File:Lea & Perrins worcestershire sauce 150ml.jpg|thumb|right|The factory opened in 1897; the recipe for [[Worcestershire sauce]] came from [[Marcus Sandys, 3rd Baron Sandys|Lord Sandys]], and was only discovered accidentally when initially discarded and left to mature for months]]\nRoger Dyson Group manufactures [[Vehicle recovery|auto-recovery]] vehicles off the A442 in north Droitwich, near [[Vax (vacuum)|Vax]] and [[Koito Industries|Koito Europe]] (car [[headlamp]]s). South of Bromsgrove, on the B4091 at [[Stoke Prior, Worcestershire|Stoke Prior]], [[L.G. Harris & Co]] make [[paintbrush]]es. [[Lea & Perrins]] is in [[Worcester]]. [[Joy Mining Machinery]] are on the A44 in the west of Worcester. [[Worcester, Bosch Group]] make 1,200 boilers a day. [[Yamazaki Mazak Corporation|Mazak]] UK have the parent company's European manufacturing facility (for [[Numerical control|CNC]] machine tools) on the B4639 in the north of Worcester, next to the [[Worcester and Birmingham Canal]]; nearby on the Blackpole Ind Est, [[Froude Hofmann]] have their world headquarters, who make [[dynamometer]]s, originated from [[William Froude]] (formerly [[Heenan & Froude]]).\n\n[[Sealine]] make boats at the [[A442 road|A442]]/A451 roundabout in Kidderminster, owned by [[Brunswick Boat Group]]. Also in Kidderminster off the A451, Stourport Road are [[Brintons]] Carpets and [[Beakbane]]. [[Roxel]] UK (equally owned by [[Safran]] and [[MBDA]]), develops [[solid-fuel rocket]]s for missiles at the A449/A442 junction south of Kidderminster and in [[Hartlebury]], on the former site of [[Royal Ordnance Rocket Motors]]. The [[West Midland Safari Park]] is off the [[A456 road|A456]] in [[Bewdley]], west of Kidderminster. [[Morgan Technical Ceramics]] is headquartered on the B4195 at [[Lickhill]] in [[Stourport-on-Severn]], south of Kidderminster; at the B4193/A4025 roundabout, [[XTA Electronics]] make [[audio amplifiers]]. [[Egbert H. Taylor]] off the A442 in [[Elmley Lovett]], near [[Hartlebury]] is the world's leading manufacturer of metal bins.  Leigh Sinton was the home of [[Biffa Waste Services]] Worcester depot until the closure in July 2013.\n\n[[File:Qinetiq, Malvern - geograph.org.uk - 728922.jpg|thumb|left|Qinetiq at the [[Malvern Hills Science Park]], or Malvern Technology Centre; the integrated circuit was invented here in 1952]]\n[[Liquid crystal display]]s were developed in 1972 in conjunction with the [[Royal Radar Establishment]], where [[Geoffrey Dummer]] invented the idea of the [[integrated circuit]] in 1952. It was based in [[Malvern, Worcestershire|Malvern]], and became the [[Royal Signals and Radar Establishment]], which developed [[Thermography|thermal imaging]] and [[Pyroelectricity|pyroelectric]] [[infrared detector]]s, and is now a large site owned by [[QinetiQ]]. [[Morgan Motor Company]] is in [[Malvern Link]]; nearby is [[Desire Petroleum]]. [[Commsoft RMS]] is in [[Evesham]]. [[Allen Gears]] supply industrial-sized gears off the A4104 in [[Pershore]]. For many years [[Group 4 (company)|Group 4 Security]], which was the largest security company in Europe, had its headquarters in [[Broadway, Worcestershire|Broadway]] off the A44, on the edge of the [[Cotswolds]]; [[G4S]] Integrated Services now has its HQ there.\n\n==Education==\n[[File:KEASTON Main.jpg|right|thumb|[[King Edward VI Aston School]]]]\n\n[[File:ShrewsburySixthFormCollege.JPG|right|thumb|[[Shrewsbury Sixth Form College]] ]]\n{{More citations needed section|date=January 2017}}\n\n===Secondary education===\nSelective schools are in low numbers as follows: Birmingham (8), Walsall (2), Wolverhampton (1), Warwickshire (6), Stoke-on-Trent (1), and Telford and Wrekin (2). The highest proportion per head therefore is Warwickshire (its population is between 550,000 and 600,000 people). The other counties and metropolitan boroughs have none, their public education systems are comprehensive in intake. The grammar and independent schools tend to produce pass-rate examination results among the top twenty ranked regionally. Many pupils compete for entrance examinations to attend such long-established [[Grammar schools in England|Grammar Schools]] and most have significant parent sponsorship. In 2016 two of the top ten such schools nationally were in Warwickshire, where in the [[CV postcode area|CV37 postal district]] prices were 34% higher than the county as a whole.<ref>https://www.lloydsbank.com/assets/media/pdfs/press-releases/2016/160907-house-prices-near-schools-press-release.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212074021/http://www.lloydsbank.com/assets/media/pdfs/press-releases/2016/160907-house-prices-near-schools-press-release.pdf |date=12 December 2017 }} Press Release \"Parents willing to pay \u00a353,000 more to live near a top school\n\", Lloyds Bank, 2016</ref> The top 20 schools at A-level rarely change from year to year; slightly lower in the table pass-rate boosts and top grades regularly occur among the schools receiving industrial funding, with similar frequency to London, the North East, and the North West, particularly in [[free school (England)|schools]] and [[Academy (English school)|academies]] which have some of the most advanced facilities.\n\nAround 275,000 secondary schools are in the region, the greatest number after the [[South East England|South East]], Greater London and [[North West England|North West]].\n\nAt [[GCSE]] based on % of entrants' pass rates, the best performing local government area in 2010 was [[Solihull]], closely followed by Warwickshire and Shropshire. Dudley, Herefordshire, Telford and Wrekin, Birmingham and Staffordshire (in descending order) are above the English average, at which rate, is approximately Worcestershire. The area consistently having fewest passes is [[Sandwell]], followed by Stoke-on-Trent.  Struggling pupils in Wolverhampton and Walsall also attain fewer passes than the English average in most GCSE years, sometimes by a very narrow margin.  For metropolitan boroughs, Solihull then Dudley perform best. Dudley is the best metropolitan borough at A-level passes and has a consistent post-2000 history of being better than Solihull.\n\nSchools have been [[off-rolling]] pupils.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Adams |first1=Richard |title='Off-rolling' hides true extent of disadvantage gap in schools \u2013 study |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2019/dec/05/off-rolling-hides-true-extent-of-disadvantage-gap-in-schools-study |accessdate=19 December 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=5 December 2019}}</ref>  Pupils likely to do badly in examinations are expelled before the examinations to improve the school performance in league tables.  Expelled pupils then disproportionately get involved in gangs and in crime.  [[Knife crime in the West Midlands]] is the highest outside London.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/dec/05/west-midlands-schools-fuelling-violent-by-excluding-pupils West Midlands schools 'fuelling violent crime by excluding pupils'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205204909/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/dec/05/west-midlands-schools-fuelling-violent-by-excluding-pupils |date=5 December 2018 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nAt A-level in 2010, the consistently best performing area was Herefordshire where most A-level candidates attend Hereford [[sixth form college]]. Dudley is also above the English average; the other metropolitan boroughs have low-to-average A-level pass or high mark proportions. Shropshire is at the English average.\n\nRegionally in persistent [[truancy]] at secondary school, Sandwell had the highest rate at 6.9%; [[Bromsgrove (district)|Bromsgrove]] had the lowest at 2.3%.<ref>2010 statistics (approx.)</ref>\n\n===Tertiary education===\nThere are thirty-seven FE colleges (FECs).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aoc.co.uk/en/aoc_regions/regions.cfm/region/WM/region/WM/page/1|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130817212236/http://www.aoc.co.uk/en/aoc_regions/regions.cfm/region/WM/region/WM/page/1|url-status=dead|title=Directory of AoC member Colleges|archivedate=17 August 2013}}</ref> There are six LSCs for the area (which fund FECs), and the [[Learning and Skills Council]] head office is based in [[Coventry]]. The five largest FE colleges in the region \u2013 [[Bournville College]], [[North Warwickshire and Hinckley College]], [[Solihull College]], [[South & City College Birmingham]] and [[Stoke-on-Trent College]] \u2013 each have more than 25,000 students.\n\nSchool children in Shropshire and Solihull are most likely to attend university, followed by Herefordshire, Worcestershire and Warwickshire.\n\n===School league tables===\nBelow is a list of the top thirty state schools in the West Midlands by 2010 A level results:\n* 1. [[King Edward VI Camp Hill]] School for Girls, Kings Heath (1212)\n* 2. [[Sutton Coldfield Grammar School for Girls]]\n* 3. [[King Edward VI Five Ways]], [[Bartley Green]]\n* 4. [[King Edward VI Camp Hill]] School for Boys, [[Kings Heath]]\n* 5. [[Stratford-upon-Avon Grammar School for Girls]]\n* 6. [[Queen Mary's Grammar School]], Walsall\n* 7. [[King Edward VI College, Stourbridge]]\n* 8. [[Newport Girls High School]]\n* 9. [[King Edward VI Handsworth]]\n* 10. [[King Edward VI School, Stratford-upon-Avon]]\n* 11. [[King Edward VI Aston]]\n* 12. [[Bishop Vesey's Grammar School]], [[Sutton Coldfield]]\n* 13. [[Wolverhampton Girls' High School]]\n* 14. [[Thomas Telford School]], [[Telford]]\n* 15. [[St. Joseph's College, Stoke-on-Trent]]\n* 16. [[Queen Mary's High School]], Walsall\n* 17. [[Rugby High School for Girls]]\n* 18. [[St Augustine's High School, Redditch]]\n* 19. [[Hereford Sixth Form College]]\n* 20. [[Moorlands Sixth Form College]], [[Cheadle, Staffordshire]]\n* 21. [[King Edward VI Sheldon Heath Academy]]\n* 22. [[Southam College]]\n* 23. [[Shrewsbury Sixth Form College]]\n* 24. [[King Edward VI School (Lichfield)]]\n* 25. [[Plantsbrook School]], Sutton Coldfield\n* 26. [[Colyton Grammar School]]\n* 27. [[Kings Norton Girls School]]\n* 28. [[Old Swinford Hospital]], [[Stourbridge]]\n* 29. [[St Francis of Assisi Catholic Technology College]], Aldridge\n* 30. [[William Brookes School]], [[Much Wenlock]] (880)\n\n===Universities===\n[[File:University of Birmingham - Aston Webb.jpg|thumb|right|University of Birmingham]]\n[[File:Medical teaching centre WU 4g07.JPG|thumb|right|University of Warwick \u2013 Medical Teaching Centre]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! University\n! Students\n! National Ranking (2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings|title=Top UK University League Tables and Rankings 2019|author=|date=|website=thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk|access-date=17 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013231901/https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings|archive-date=13 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[University of Birmingham]]\n| 34,835\n|15\n|-\n|[[Coventry University]]\n| 31,690\n|50\n|-\n|[[University of Warwick]]\n| 25,615\n| 8\n|-\n|[[Birmingham City University]]\n| 24,130\n|95\n|-\n|[[University of Wolverhampton]]\n| 19,560\n| \u2013\n|-\n|[[Staffordshire University]]\n| 14,910\n|101\n|-\n|[[Aston University]]\n| 14,162\n|30\n|-\n|[[University of Worcester]]\n| 10,745\n|97\n|-\n|[[Keele University]]\n| 10,600\n|46\n|-\n|[[Harper Adams University]]\n| 5,410\n|46\n|-\n|[[University College Birmingham]]\n| 4,935\n| \u2013\n|-\n|[[Newman University, Birmingham|Newman University]]\n| 2,830 \n| \u2013\n|}\n\nThe University of Birmingham is the main university in the region<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hefce.ac.uk/pubs/hefce/2007/07_18/outputWM.pdf|title=HEFCE|author=|date=|website=hefce.ac.uk|access-date=29 March 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091112183521/http://www.hefce.ac.uk/pubs/hefce/2007/07_18/outputWM.pdf|archive-date=12 November 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> and has the most funding. It has a large research grant, as does the University of Warwick, which is the next largest in terms of funding. Birmingham and Warwick are members of the [[Russell Group]] of public research universities. Keele and Aston have a moderate research grant, but none of the other universities do. Keele, although having the largest campus in the UK (by area), is one of the smallest universities in the region. There are medical schools at [[Warwick Medical School|Warwick]], [[Keele University Medical School|Keele]] and [[University of Birmingham Medical School|Birmingham]]. Birmingham and Warwick receive more than twice as much total income than any other university in the region \u2013 around \u00a3400&nbsp;million each.\n\nAround 45% of students are from the region, and 35% from other parts of the UK, while 20% are from overseas.  The region attracts students from [[South East England]] owing to good access via the [[M40 motorway|M40]] and the [[West Coast Main Line]], but there is a good mix from other regions too, except the North East (especially) and Yorkshire.  Students native to the West Midlands are most likely to study in the region (40%), then the [[East Midlands]] (12%), the [[North West England|North West]] (11%), and then Yorkshire (9%). Very few go to the [[East of England]] or the [[North East England|North East]]. The region has a net export of university students to other regions.\n\nAt time of graduation in 2010 almost 60% of graduates remained in the West Midlands, with 10% going to London, 7% to the South-East, and around 5% to the East Midlands. Very few go to Yorkshire, the North-East, or even (neighbouring) Wales.\n\n==Media==\n{{See also|Media in Birmingham}}\n\n=== Television ===\n[[File:ITV Central TV studios - geograph.org.uk - 1150068.jpg|thumb|right|ITV Central [[Gas Street Studios]] in Birmingham]]\nThe West Midlands region of the [[BBC]] is based at the [[Mailbox Birmingham|Mailbox]] in Birmingham. From there, the regional programme [[Midlands Today]] is produced. [[Central Independent Television|ITV Central]] broadcasts from Birmingham, off [[Broad Street, Birmingham|Broad Street]] on [[Gas Street Basin|Gas Street]] next to the [[Worcester and Birmingham Canal]], with its [[ITV News Central]] regional programme.\n\nSome northern parts of the region, including [[Biddulph]], receive [[BBC North West Tonight]] and [[Granada Reports]] both of which are based at [[Media City UK]] in [[City of Salford|Salford]] and are broadcast from the [[Winter Hill transmitting station|Winter Hill]] transmitter.\n\nThe BBC has its engineering training centre at [[Wood Norton, Worcestershire]], off the A44 north of Evesham in Norton and Lenchwick. [[BBC English Regions]] is based at Birmingham.\n\n=== Radio ===\n\n==== BBC Local Radio ====\nThe West Midlands is served by numerous [[BBC Local Radio]] stations, including [[BBC WM]], [[BBC Coventry & Warwickshire]], [[BBC Radio Stoke]], [[BBC Hereford & Worcester]] and [[BBC Radio Shropshire]].\n\n==== Commercial radio ====\nCommercial radio stations include [[Free Radio (network)|Free Radio]], [[Capital Midlands]], [[Capital Mid-Counties]], [[Heart West Midlands]], [[Smooth Radio West Midlands]], [[Absolute Radio]], [[Signal Radio]], [[Signal 107]], [[Sunshine 855]] and [[Sunshine Radio (FM)|Sunshine Radio Herefordshire & Monmouthshire]].\n\n==== Community Radio ====\n\n[[Community radio]] stations include:\n* The Bridge 102.5 ([[Stourbridge]])\n* [[Youthcomm Radio]] ([[Worcester]]) \n* [[Big City Radio]] ([[Birmingham]]) \n* Radio Plus and Hillz FM in ([[Coventry]]) \n* [[WCR FM]] and Gorgeous Radio ([[Wolverhampton]]) \n* [[Moorlands Radio]] ([[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]]) \n* [[6 Towns Radio]], Cre8 FM and [[Cross Rhythms City Radio]] ([[Stoke-on-Trent]]) \n* The Hitmix ([[Newcastle-under-Lyme]]) \n* [[Cannock Chase Radio]] and [[Stafford FM]] ([[Stafford]])\n\nStafford is also notable for [[Windmill Broadcasting]], the [[United Kingdom|UK's]] only radio station based in a [[Windmill]], in the [[Broad Eye Windmill]].\n\n=== Newspapers ===\nLocal newspapers include:\n* ''[[Berrow's Worcester Journal]]''\n* ''[[Birmingham Mail]]''\n* ''[[Birmingham Post]]''\n* ''[[Burton Mail]]''\n* ''[[Coventry Telegraph]]''\n* ''[[Express & Star]]'' (Wolverhampton)\n* ''[[Nuneaton News]]''\n* ''[[Shropshire Star]]''\n* ''[[The Sentinel (Staffordshire)|The Sentinel]]'' (Stoke-on-Trent)\n* ''[[The Shuttle (Kidderminster)|The Shuttle]]'' (Kidderminster based, reporting on Wyre Forest news, Worcestershire)\n* ''[[Worcester News]]''\n\n===Magazines===\nWilliam Gibbons of Wolverhampton prints ''[[New Scientist]]'', ''[[The Lady (magazine)|The Lady]]'', ''[[Farmers Weekly]]'', ''[[BBC Focus]]'', ''[[Psychologies]]'', ''[[History Revealed]]'', ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'', and ''[[Tractors & Machinery]]''.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nThe Polestar Varnicoat works on the A44 in [[Pinvin]], north of Pershore, for many years{{when|date=August 2016}} printed ''[[Woman's Own]]'', ''[[Heat (magazine)|Heat]]'', ''[[Pick Me Up (magazine)|Pick Me Up]]'', ''[[Chat (magazine)|Chat]]'', and ''That's Life''.\n\n=== Online ===\n[[Channel 4]]'s 4Talent network has a hub in the West Midlands dealing with rising media talent from the region.<ref>[http://4talent.channel4.com/<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{Cite web |url=http://4talent.channel4.com/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=15 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810190536/http://4talent.channel4.com/ |archive-date=10 August 2014 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n{{See also|Sport in Birmingham}}\n[[File:St Georges Park Aerial May 2012.jpg|thumb|right|St George's Park is the training ground of the [[England National Football Team]]]]\nThe [[National Sports Centre]] at [[Lilleshall Hall]] is in [[Sheriffhales]], Shropshire, north-east of Telford; it was largely established by the [[Sport and Recreation Alliance|Central Council of Physical Recreation]] in 1949 as a National Recreation Centre; the south of England had theirs at [[Bisham Abbey]] on the Thames. [[St George's Park National Football Centre]] is at [[Tatenhill]] near [[Byrkley Park]] in [[Needwood Forest]], near former the [[RAF Tatenhill]] off the [[A515 road|A515]], four miles west of Burton upon Trent.\n\nThe [[Tough Guy Competition]], now a widespread sport competition in the US, began in 1987 on a farm at [[Perton]] in Staffordshire. The main British athletics championships are held in Birmingham in late June. The [[International Olympic Committee|Olympic Movement]] started at [[Much Wenlock]], and also to the east of region, where [[Pierre de Coubertin|Baron de Coubertin]] formulated his ideas for sport and the Olympics at [[Rugby School]] in 1883, with the headmaster [[Thomas Arnold]], whose son would be the famous poet [[Matthew Arnold]] and whose great-grandson would be [[Aldous Huxley]].\n\n===Football===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Club\n! League\n! City/Town\n! Stadium\n! Capacity\n|-\n|[[Aston Villa FC]]\n| [[Premier League]]\n| [[Birmingham]]\n|[[Villa Park]]\n| 42,788\n|-\n|[[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.]]\n|Premier League\n| [[Wolverhampton]]\n|[[Molineux Stadium]]\n| 31,700\n|-\n|[[Birmingham City F.C.]]\n|[[EFL Championship]]\n| Birmingham\n|[[St Andrew's (stadium)|St Andrew's]]\n| 30,079\n|-\n|[[Stoke City FC]]\n| Championship\n| [[Stoke-on-Trent]]\n|[[Britannia Stadium]]\n| 28,384\n|-\n|[[West Bromwich Albion FC]]\n| Championship\n| [[West Bromwich]]\n|[[The Hawthorns]]\n| 26,500\n|-\n|[[Burton Albion F.C.]]\n| [[League One]]\n| [[Burton-upon-Trent]]\n|[[Pirelli Stadium]]\n| 6,912\n|-\n|[[Coventry City FC]]\n| League One\n| [[Coventry]]\n|[[Ricoh Arena]]\n| 32,609\n|-\n|[[Shrewsbury Town F.C.]]\n| League One\n| [[Shrewsbury]]\n|[[Prostar Stadium]]\n| 9,875\n|-\n|[[Walsall F.C.]]\n| League One\n| [[Walsall]]\n|[[Bescot Stadium]]\n| 11,300\n|-\n|[[Port Vale F.C.]]\n| [[League Two]]\n| Stoke-on-Trent\n|[[Vale Park]]\n| 19,052\n|-\n|[[Solihull Moors]]\n|[[National League (division)|National League]]\n| [[Solihull]]/Birmingham\n|Damson Park\n|3,050\n|-\n|[[A.F.C. Telford United]]\n|[[National League North]]\n| [[Telford]]\n|[[New Bucks Head]]\n| 6,300\n|-\n|[[Hereford F.C.]]\n|National League North\n| [[Hereford]]\n|[[Edgar Street]]\n| 4,913\n|-\n|[[Kidderminster Harriers F.C.]]\n|National League North\n| [[Kidderminster]]\n|[[Aggborough]]\n| 6,250\n|-\n| [[Nuneaton Town F.C.]]\n|National League North\n| [[Nuneaton]]\n| [[Liberty Way]]\n| 4,314\n|-\n|[[Leamington F.C.]]\n|National League North\n| [[Whitnash]]\n|New Windmill Ground\n| 5,000\n|}\n\n===Rugby===\nIn [[rugby union]], the region is home to professional [[English Premiership (rugby union)|Premiership]] teams [[Wasps RFC]] and [[Worcester Warriors]]. In [[rugby league]], [[Coventry Bears]] play in the third tier [[League 1 (rugby league)|League 1]].\n\n===Tennis===\n{{See also|History of tennis}}\n[[File:Tennis Match, Family Circle Cup 2008.JPG|thumb|right|Tennis was invented in Edgbaston, Birmingham]]\nBritain's first tennis club was founded in 1872 in [[Royal Leamington Spa|Leamington Spa]]. The modern rules of lawn tennis were developed in 1874 by Leamington Tennis Club. Tennis was pioneered in Edgbaston in 1859, and [[Edgbaston Archery and Lawn Tennis Society]] also claims to be the oldest tennis club in the world, where tennis was invented by Major [[Harry Gem]] and the Spaniard [[Augurio Perera]].\n\nA famous 1970s [[Tennis Girl]] picture was taken on 12 September 1976 by Oldbury's [[Martin Elliott]] at the tennis courts of Birmingham University, featuring 18-year-old Fiona Butler, now of [[Stourport-on-Severn]].{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n===Motor sport===\n[[Team Dynamics]] at [[Pershore]], has won the [[British Touring Car Championship]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons and category|West Midlands|West Midlands (region)}}\n{{Portal|England}}\n* [http://www.advantagewm.co.uk/ Advantage West Midlands \u2013 Regional Development Agency]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111026042255/http://www.go-wm.gov.uk/ Government Office for the West Midlands]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140222044235/http://www.wmra.gov.uk/ West Midlands Regional Assembly]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061130220616/http://www.direct.gov.uk/Dl1/Directories/LocalCouncils/LocalGovernmentByRegion/fs/en?CONTENT_ID=4003650&chk=J1Wt8n Government's list of councils in the West Midlands]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100318045124/http://www.mlawestmidlands.org.uk/ MLA West Midlands \u2013 Museums, Libraries and Archives Regional Agency]\n* [http://www.westmidlands.nhs.uk/ NHS West Midlands \u2013 The regional Strategic Health Authority for the West Midlands]\n* [http://www.bclm.co.uk/ Black Country Living Museum, which tells the history of the modern West Midlands areas of Dudley, Sandwell, Walsall and Wolverhampton]\n\n{{United Kingdom topics}}\n{{English regions}}\n{{West Midlands}}\n\n{{coord|52.47|N|2.29|W|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:West Midlands (Region)}}\n[[Category:West Midlands (region)| ]]\n[[Category:Regions of England]]\n[[Category:NUTS 1 statistical regions of England]]\n[[Category:NUTS 1 statistical regions of the European Union]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|West Midlands (county)|West Midlands conurbation}}\n{{Short description|A region of England}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n| type                   = [[Regions of England|region of England]]\n| name                   = West Midlands\n| image_skyline          = West Midlands in England.svg\n| image_alt              = West Midlands, highlighted in red on a beige political map of England\n| image_caption          = \n| imagesize              = 200\n| coordinates            = \n| subdivision_type       = [[Sovereign state]]\n| subdivision_name       = [[United Kingdom]]\n| subdivision_type1      = {{nowrap|[[Countries of the United Kingdom|Constituent country]]}}\n| subdivision_name1      = [[England]]\n| seat_type              = Largest city\n| seat                   = [[Birmingham]]\n| seat1_type             = Largest urban area\n| seat1                  = [[West Midlands conurbation]]\n| seat2_type             = Largest town\n| seat2                  = \n| leader_title           = [[Local authority leaders' board|Leaders' board]]\n| leader_name            = [[West Midlands Councils]]\n| leader_title1          = [[European Parliament constituency|EP&nbsp;constituency]]\n| leader_name1           = [[West Midlands (European Parliament constituency)|West Midlands]]\n| unit_pref              = Metric\n| area_total_km2         = 13,000\n| area_rank              = 7th\n| population_as_of       = 2014 est.\n| population_footnotes   = \n| population_total       = 5,713,000\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| population_rank        = 5th\n| demographics_type1     = [[Gross value added|GVA]] \n| demographics1_title1   = Total\n| demographics1_info1    = \u00a3110&nbsp;billion\n| demographics1_title2   = Per capita\n| demographics1_info2    = \u00a317,161 ([[Countries of the United Kingdom by GVA per capita|7th]])\n| blank_name_sec1        = [[NUTS statistical regions of the United Kingdom|NUTS code]]\n| blank_info_sec1        = UKG\n| blank1_name_sec1       = [[ONS coding system|ONS code]]\n| blank1_info_sec1       = \n| website                = \n}}\n{{Politics of England}}\nThe '''West Midlands''' is one of nine official [[regions of England]] at the [[First level NUTS of the European Union|first level]] of [[NUTS statistical regions of the United Kingdom|NUTS]] for [[Eurostat|statistical]] purposes. It covers the western half of the area traditionally known as the [[Midlands (England)|Midlands]]. It contains [[Birmingham]] and the larger [[West Midlands conurbation]], which is the [[List of urban areas in the United Kingdom|third most populous]] in the [[United Kingdom]]. The City of [[Coventry]] is also located within the [[West Midlands county]], but is separated from the [[conurbation]] to the west by several miles of [[green belt]]. The region also contains 6 shire counties which stretch from the Welsh Border to the East Midlands.\n\nThe region is geographically diverse, from the urban central areas of the conurbation to the rural western counties of [[Shropshire]] and [[Herefordshire]] which border [[Wales]]. The longest river in the UK, the [[River Severn]], traverses the region southeastwards, flowing through the [[county town]]s of [[Shrewsbury]] and [[Worcester]], and the [[Ironbridge Gorge]], a [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]]. [[Staffordshire]] is home to the industrialised [[Staffordshire Potteries|Potteries]] conurbation, including the city of [[Stoke-on-Trent]], and the [[Staffordshire Moorlands]] area, which borders the southeastern [[Peak District National Park]] near [[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]]. The region also encompasses five [[Areas of Outstanding Natural Beauty]], the [[Wye Valley]], [[Shropshire Hills]], [[Cannock Chase]], [[Malvern Hills]], and parts of the [[Cotswolds]]. [[Warwickshire]] is home to the towns of [[Stratford upon Avon]], birthplace of writer [[William Shakespeare]], [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]], the birthplace of [[Rugby football]] and [[Nuneaton]], birthplace to author [[George Eliot]].\n\n==Geography==\n\nThe official region contains the [[Ceremonial counties of England|ceremonial counties]] of [[Herefordshire]], Shropshire, [[Staffordshire]], Warwickshire, [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] and [[Worcestershire]].\n[[File:Lyth Hill 01.jpg|thumb|Rural [[Shropshire]], [[Bayston Hill|Lyth Hill]].]]\n\nThere is some confusion in the use of the term \"West Midlands\", as the name is also used for the much smaller [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands county]] and conurbation which is in the central belt of the Midlands and on the eastern side of the West Midlands Region. It is also still used by various organisations within that area, such as [[West Midlands Police]] and [[West Midlands Fire Service]].\n\nThe highest point in the region is [[Black Mountain (hill)|Black Mountain]], at 703&nbsp;metres (2,307&nbsp;ft) in west Herefordshire on the border with [[Powys]], Wales.\n\nThe region contains five [[Areas of Outstanding Natural Beauty]] (AONBs), including the [[Shropshire Hills]], [[Malvern Hills]] and [[Cannock Chase]], and parts of the [[Wye Valley]] and [[Cotswolds]]. The [[Peak District]] national park also stretches into the northern corner of [[Staffordshire]].\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Railways===\n[[File:Birmingham & West Mids Passenger Railway_Map.JPG|thumb|Map of the West Midlands passenger railway network]]\nServed by many lines in the urban areas such as the [[West Coast Main Line]] and branches.  The [[Welsh Marches Line]] and the [[Cotswold Line]] transect the region as well as the [[Cross Country Route]] and [[Chiltern Line]].  There are plans to reopen the [[Honeybourne Line]].\n\n===Road===\n[[File:M6 Toll plaza, Great Wyrley.jpg|thumb|The [[M6 Toll]] plaza.]]\nNumerous notable roads pass through the region, with most converging around the central conurbation. The [[M5 motorway|M5]], which connects [[South West England]] to the region, passes through Worcestershire, near to [[Worcester]], and through the [[West Midlands county]], past [[West Bromwich]], with its northern terminus at its junction with the [[M6 motorway|M6]] just south of [[Walsall]]. The M6, which has its southern terminus just outside the southeast of the region at its junction with the [[M1 motorway|M1]], and which connects the region to [[North West England]], passes [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]] and [[Nuneaton]] in Warwickshire, [[Coventry]] and [[Birmingham]], and [[Stafford]] and [[Stoke-on-Trent]] in Staffordshire. The [[M6 toll]] provides an alternative route to the M6 between [[Coleshill, Warwickshire|Coleshill]] and [[Cannock]], passing north of [[Sutton Coldfield]] and just south of [[Lichfield]].  The [[M40 motorway|M40]] connects the region through [[South East England]] to London, with its northern terminus at its junction with the [[M42 motorway|M42]]; it passes close to [[Warwick]] and [[Banbury]]. The M42 connects the M5 at [[Bromsgrove]], passing around the south and east of Birmingham, joining the M40 and M6, passing [[Solihull]] and [[Castle Bromwich]], to [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]], northeast of Birmingham.  The [[M50 motorway (Great Britain)|M50]] connects the M5 from near [[Tewkesbury]] to [[Ross-on-Wye]] in the southwest. The [[M54 motorway|M54]] connects [[Wellington, Shropshire|Wellington]] in the west, passing [[Telford]], to the M6 near [[Cannock]]. The [[A5 road (Great Britain)|A5 road]] traverses the region northwest-southeast, passing through [[Shrewsbury]], [[Telford]], [[Cannock]], [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]] and [[Nuneaton]].\n\nThe longest elevated road viaduct in the UK is the {{convert|4779|m|mi|0|order=flip}} section from Gravelly Hill to Castle Bromwich on the M6, opened on 24 May 1972; the {{convert|5.6|km|mi|order=flip}} [[Bromford Viaduct]] is the longest viaduct in the UK. The section of the A45 in Coventry from [[Willenhall, Coventry|Willenhall]] to Allesley in 1939 was one of the UK's first ever large planned road schemes; road schemes on that scale had not been previously built, with few large road schemes outside of London, or were piecemeal.\n\nPrinces Square in Wolverhampton had Britain's first automatic traffic lights on 5 November 1927.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=Princes_Square|title=Princes Square - Roader's Digest: The SABRE Wiki|author=|date=|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk|access-date=15 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171115221840/https://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=Princes_Square|archive-date=15 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On 13 January 2012, 34-year-old Ben Westwood of Wednesfield, was caught by the police, when speeding at 180&nbsp;mph, in an [[Audi A5|Audi RS5]] with a [[Lamborghini]] engine, from Wolverhampton up to Stafford on the M6, and back again. He was travelling so fast that he was outpacing the [[Central Counties Air Operations Unit]] [[Eurocopter EC135|Eurocopter]] helicopter. He and the vehicle had been in fifteen [[smash and grab]] raids and he was jailed for nine years at Wolverhampton Crown Court in August 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-19347144|title=Jail for 180mph M6 chase driver|author=|date=23 August 2012|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=7 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181007075234/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-19347144|archive-date=7 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Transport policy===\n[[File:M45 Motorway near Barby - geograph.org.uk - 31743.jpg|thumb|right|The [[M45 motorway]], originally called the [[Dunchurch]] Link, was one of the first motorways built in the UK, and is now one of the quietest]]\nAs part of the transport planning system, the Regional Assembly is under statutory requirement to produce a [[regional transport strategy (UK)|regional transport strategy]] (RTS) to provide long term planning for transport in the region. This involves region wide transport schemes such as those carried out by [[Highways England]] and [[Network Rail]].<ref name=\"GoWM1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gos.gov.uk/gowm/Transport/TransportRegTransStrat/?a=42496 |title=Regional Transport Strategy: the National Picture |publisher=[[Government Office]] for the West Midlands |accessdate=28 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630083736/http://www.gos.gov.uk/gowm/Transport/TransportRegTransStrat/?a=42496 |archivedate=30 June 2009 }}</ref>\n\nWithin the region, the local transport authorities carry out transport planning through the use of a [[local transport plan]] (LTP) which outlines their strategies, policies and implementation programme.<ref name=\"DfT1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/regional/ltp/theltpprocess |title=The LTP Process |publisher=[[Department for Transport]] |accessdate=28 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009193023/http://www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/regional/ltp/theltpprocess |archivedate=9 October 2007 }}</ref> The most recent LTP is that for the period 2006\u201311. In the West Midlands region, the following transport authorities have published their LTP online: [[Herefordshire]],<ref name=\"HLTP\">\n{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.herefordshire.gov.uk/transport/3197.asp\n |title       = Herefordshire 2006\u201311 Local Transport Plan\n |publisher   = [[Herefordshire Council]]\n |accessdate  = 5 May 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20081228235559/http://www.herefordshire.gov.uk/transport/3197.asp\n |archivedate = 28 December 2008\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> [[Shropshire]] U.A.,<ref name=\"ShLTP\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.shropshire.gov.uk/traveltransport.nsf/open/ADE3AAF9F3AAD7C48025709E003D2144\n|title=Shropshire2006-11 Local Transport Plan\n|publisher=[[Shropshire Council]]\n|accessdate=5 May 2009\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201150513/http://www.shropshire.gov.uk/traveltransport.nsf/open/ADE3AAF9F3AAD7C48025709E003D2144\n|archive-date=1 December 2008\n|url-status=live\n}}</ref> [[Staffordshire]],<ref name=\"StLTP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/transport/transportplanning/localtransportplan/LocalTransportPlan2.htm |title=Staffordshire2006-11 Local Transport Plan |publisher=[[Staffordshire]] County Council |accessdate=5 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121194044/http://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/transport/transportplanning/localtransportplan/LocalTransportPlan2.htm |archivedate=21 November 2008 }}</ref> [[Telford and Wrekin]] U.A.,<ref name=T&WLTP>{{cite web|url=http://www.telford.gov.uk/Transport+streets+and+parking/Transport+planning/Local+Transport+Plan+2006-2011+with+mid-term+Delivery+Report.htm |title=Telford and Wrekin 2006\u201311 Local Transport Plan |publisher=[[Telford and Wrekin Council]] |accessdate=5 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630095014/http://www.telford.gov.uk/Transport+streets+and+parking/Transport+planning/Local+Transport+Plan+2006-2011+with+mid-term+Delivery+Report.htm |archivedate=30 June 2009 }}</ref> [[Warwickshire]],<ref name=\"WrLTP\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.warwickshire.gov.uk/ltp\n|title=Warwickshire 2006\u201311 Local Transport Plan\n|publisher=[[Warwickshire County Council]]\n|accessdate=5 May 2009\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430121313/http://www.warwickshire.gov.uk/ltp\n|archive-date=30 April 2009\n|url-status=live\n}}</ref> [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]<ref name=\"WMLTP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.westmidlandsltp.gov.uk/ |title=West Midlands 2006\u201311 Local Transport Plan |publisher=West Midlands LTP |accessdate=5 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090518075425/http://www.westmidlandsltp.gov.uk/ |archivedate=18 May 2009 }}</ref> and [[Worcestershire]].<ref name=\"WcLTP\">{{cite web|url=http://worcestershire.whub.org.uk/home/wccindex/wcc-ht/wcc-ht-ltp-v2.htm |title=Worcestershire 2006\u201311 Local Transport Plan |publisher=[[Worcestershire County Council]] |accessdate=5 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090311084239/http://worcestershire.whub.org.uk/home/wccindex/wcc-ht/wcc-ht-ltp-v2.htm |archivedate=11 March 2009 }}</ref> The transport authority of [[Stoke-on-Trent]] U.A. publishes a joint local transport plan in partnership with Staffordshire County Council to cover the North Staffordshire Major Urban Area, which includes Stoke-on-Trent and the more urban parts of [[Newcastle-under-Lyme]] and [[Staffordshire Moorlands]].<ref name=\"SoTLTP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stoke.gov.uk/ccm/content/rc/LTP/provisional-north-staffordshire-ltp.en |title=Stoke-on-Trent 2006\u201311 Local Transport Plan |publisher=[[Stoke-on-Trent City Council]] |accessdate=5 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630152508/http://www.stoke.gov.uk/ccm/content/rc/LTP/provisional-north-staffordshire-ltp.en |archivedate=30 June 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Towns and cities==\n{{clear}}\nMajor towns and cities in the West Midlands region include:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/StatBase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=8271&Pos=2&ColRank=1&Rank=224|title=Home - Office for National Statistics|author=|date=|website=www.statistics.gov.uk|access-date=19 March 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070421211031/http://www.statistics.gov.uk/StatBase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=8271&Pos=2&ColRank=1&Rank=224|archive-date=21 April 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n:<small>''Bold indicates [[City status in the United Kingdom|city status]].''</small>\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n;Population > 1,000,000\n* '''[[Birmingham]]''', [[West Midlands (county)|WMS]]\n;Population > 200,000\n* '''[[Coventry]]''', WMS\n* '''[[Stoke-on-Trent]]''', [[Staffordshire|STS]]\n* '''[[Wolverhampton]]''', WMS\n;Population > 100,000\n* [[Solihull]], WMS\n* [[Telford]], [[Shropshire|SHR]]\n* '''[[Worcester]]''', [[Worcestershire|WOR]]\n;Population > 50,000\n* [[Burton-upon-Trent]], STS\n* [[Dudley]], WMS\n* [[Halesowen]], WMS\n* '''[[Hereford]]''', [[Herefordshire|HER]]\n* [[Kidderminster]], WOR\n* [[Leamington Spa]], [[Warwickshire|WAR]]\n* [[Newcastle-under-Lyme]], STS\n* [[Nuneaton]], WAR\n* [[Redditch]], WOR\n* [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]], WAR\n* [[Shrewsbury]], SHR\n* [[Stafford]], STS\n* [[Stourbridge]], WMS\n* [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]], STS\n* [[Walsall]], WMS\n* [[West Bromwich]], WMS\n{{col-3}}\n;Population > 25,000\n* [[Cannock]], STS\n* [[Bedworth]], WAR\n* [[Bromsgrove]], WOR \n* '''[[Lichfield]]''', STS\n* [[Malvern, Worcestershire|Malvern]], WOR\n* [[Rowley Regis]], WMS\n* [[Smethwick]], WMS\n* [[Stratford-upon-Avon]], WAR\n* [[Tipton]], WMS\n* [[Warwick]], WAR\n* [[Wednesbury]], WMS\n;Other notable:\n* [[Atherstone]], WAR\n* [[Bridgnorth]], SHR\n* [[Droitwich Spa]], WOR\n* [[Evesham]], WOR\n* [[Kenilworth]], WAR\n* [[Kidsgrove]], STS\n* [[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]], STS\n* [[Oswestry]], SHR\n* [[Rugeley]], STS\n* [[Uttoxeter]], STS\n{{col-3}}\n[[File:WestMidlandsRegion.jpg|290px|left|thumb|A map of the West Midlands region, showing Towns/Cities in <span style=\"color:#f00;\">Red</span>, Motorways in <span style=\"color:#72a0fe;\">Blue</span>, [[AONB]]s in <span style=\"color:#78ff00;\"> Light Green</span> and [[National parks of the United Kingdom|National Parks]] in <span style=\"color:#4c8910;\"> Dark Green</span>.]]\n{{col-end}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Modern history==\n\n{{Further| Mercia}}\n\n===World War II===\nThe [[RAF Fauld explosion]] on 27 November 1944 in east Staffordshire produced a 100-foot deep crater, and is the UK's largest explosion, being caused by around 4,000 tonnes of [[Explosive material|high explosive]], and may be the [[Largest artificial non-nuclear explosions|world's largest non-nuclear explosion]].\n\nBirmingham was the third [[Birmingham Blitz|most bombed]] city in the UK after London and [[Liverpool]]; Spitfires were built in Castle Bromwich, [[Avro Lancaster|Lancaster]]s at Austin's works in [[Longbridge plant|Longbridge]] at [[Cofton Hackett]], and the [[Birmingham Small Arms Company]] at [[Small Heath, Birmingham|Small Heath]] produced the [[M1919 Browning machine gun]]. [[Boulton Paul Aircraft]] had their main aircraft factory in the north of Wolverhampton. [[RAF Defford]], in the south of Worcestershire between Pershore and [[Croome Court|Croome Park]], was where many important [[Airborne early warning and control|airborne radars]] were developed, such as [[H2S (radar)]] and anti-submarine radars.\n\n===Scientific heritage===\n[[Thomas Wedgwood (photographer)|Thomas Wedgwood]], son of Josiah Wedgwood, discovered the first [[Photographic paper|photo-sensitive]] (light-sensitive) chemicals \u2013 [[silver nitrate]] and [[silver chloride]] in the 1790s.\n\nSir [[Norman Lockyer]] of [[Kenilworth]] discovered [[helium]] in 1868, for which he used electromagnetic [[spectroscopy]].\n\n[[Edward Weston (chemist)|Edward Weston]] of Oswestry, who emigrated to the US, built the first accurate [[voltmeter]] in the late 1880s, and the [[Weston cell]] in 1893.\n\n[[Francis William Aston|Francis W. Aston]] of Harborne, educated at the University of Birmingham, developed [[mass spectrometry]] in 1919, which helped him to identify the first [[isotope]]s, receiving the [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize for Chemistry]] in 1922.\n\n[[Dennis Gabor]] invented holography at [[British Thomson-Houston]] in Rugby in 1947, receiving the [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel Prize for Physics]] in 1971.\n\n[[James Glaisher]] in 1862 took a record balloon flight with [[Henry Tracey Coxwell]] for the [[British Science Association|BAAS]] near Wolverhampton. They reached {{convert|29000|ft}} the composition of the Earth's atmosphere until then was not understood; the altitude records for the UK have not been exceeded since; [[Project Excelsior]] in the US in 1960 would later reach {{convert|20|mi|ft}}.\n\n[[Philip Lawley]] of Burton upon Trent was first person to realise that [[Health effects of tobacco|chemical damage to DNA]] caused cancer (at the Chester Beatty Research Institute in London) in the early 1960s.\n\n[[Francis Galton]] (d. 1911) of the [[Darwin\u2013Wedgwood family]]'s Birmingham branch was an early [[Eugenics|eugenicist]] rooted in improving animal breeding stock and examining heredity. He invented terms eugenics and ''[[nature versus nurture]]''. His limited calls for human eugenics were widened by the [[German Society for Racial Hygiene]] in 1905 founded by [[Alfred Ploetz]], which coupled with the racial superiority fallacies of [[Aryan race|Aryanism]] reached its nadir in [[Holocaust|genocidal]] [[anti-semitism]]. Moral teachings and [[deontological ethics|inherent replusions]] towards human eugenics were overcome by a minority of those in power espousing [[racial equality]]; European media and leaders lamented [[European Imperialism|loss of Empire]], advocated [[ultranationalism]] and prized military physical advantage; Galton saw human eugenics as part of all means to ''do better''.\n\n===Industrial heritage===\n{{See also|Science and invention in Birmingham|Architecture of Birmingham}}\n[[File:The Iron Bridge - geograph.org.uk - 224230.jpg|thumb|The [[cast iron]] Iron Bridge at [[Coalbrookdale]], opened in January 1781 and was the first large-scale object made out of cast iron; but cast iron is not reliably strong due to impurities. [[Wrought iron]], where the carbon is hammered to remove to carbon and impurities is much stronger; the first large-scale wrought iron bridge was the [[Britannia Bridge]] over the [[Menai Strait]], only possible due to its innovative [[box girder]] design by [[Robert Stephenson]] ]]\nMuch of the [[Industrial revolution]] in the United Kingdom began in [[Birmingham]] and the [[Black Country]] area of West Midlands. The Industrial Revolution is thought to have begun when [[Abraham Darby I|Abraham Darby]] substituted [[coke (fuel)|coke]] in the place of charcoal to smelt iron, at his Old Furnace. The Black Country may be regarded as the world's first industrial landscape,<ref>{{cite web|title=Black Country Living Museum|url=http://www.bclm.co.uk/|publisher=Black Country Living Museum|accessdate=3 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130403022514/http://www.bclm.co.uk/|archive-date=3 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> while nearby [[Ironbridge Gorge]] claims to be the Birthplace of Industry.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Iron Bridge|url=http://www.ironbridge.org.uk/our-attractions/the-iron-bridge-and-tollhouse/|publisher=Ironbridge Gorge Museum Trust|accessdate=3 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130321095559/http://www.ironbridge.org.uk/our-attractions/the-iron-bridge-and-tollhouse|archive-date=21 March 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> [[The Iron Bridge|The world's first cast iron bridge in 1779]] spans the Gorge. The first self-propelled locomotive to run on rails in 1803 at Coalbrookdale, was built by [[Richard Trevithick]]. The [[Permanent way (history)|first iron rails]] for horse-drawn transport, were made at Coalbrookdale in 1768 by [[Richard Reynolds (ironmaster)|Richard Reynolds]] at [[Ketley Ironworks]]. Iron rails only became widely successful in 1820 when made out of [[wrought iron]] at [[Bedlington Ironworks]] in north-east England.\n\n[[File:Philipp Jakob Loutherbourg d. J. 002.jpg|thumb|''Coalbrookdale by Night'', of the [[Madeley Wood Company]], painted by [[Philip James de Loutherbourg]] in 1801]] \nBirmingham's industrial development was triggered by discussions at the [[Lunar Society of Birmingham]] at [[Soho House]], Boulton's house, and products were carried along the [[BCN Main Line]] canal. [[Soho Manufactory]] was the first man-made-powered factory in world. [[Chance Brothers]] of Smethwick built the glass for [[The Crystal Palace]] in 1851. [[Smethwick Engine]], now at [[Thinktank, Birmingham Science Museum]], is the oldest working steam engine, made in 1779, and is the oldest working engine in the world. Smethwick was a main centre for making [[lighthouse]] [[lantern]]s.\n\n[[Yale & Valor|Valor Fires]] in Erdington developed the first [[Radiant heating|radiant]] [[Gas heater|gas fire]] in 1967, a balanced [[flue]] fire in 1973, and a natural flame gas fire in 1978. The Erdington site, owned by Iceland's [[BDR Thermea]], closed in May 2012. The company also built [[Gas stove|gas cooker]]s; since 2011 the company has been part of [[Glen Dimplex]], who have a site at [[Cooper's Bank]], south of [[Gornal, West Midlands|Gornalwood]].\n\n[[File:Boulton, Watt and Murdoch - geograph.org.uk - 1754695.jpg|thumb|right|Boulton, Watt and Murdoch, a 1956 statue on Broad Street in Birmingham; the [[International System of Units|SI]] unit of power is the watt, most commonly found as the kW, a replacement for the imperial measurement of [[horsepower]] ]]\n[[Ditherington Flax Mill]] in Shrewsbury was the first [[Steel frame|iron-framed building]] in the world in 1797. [[Thomas Bolton & Sons]] of [[Froghall]], Staffordshire, made the world's first [[transatlantic telegraph cable]] in 1857, having supplied a [[Submarine communications cable|submarine cable]] across the English Channel in 1850. [[GEC Telecommunications]] was headquartered at the [[GEC Telephone and Radio Works]] in Coventry, it has now become the New Century Park, off the [[A428 road|A428]] north of [[Stoke Aldermoor]] in eastern Coventry. On 10 July 1890, a trunk circuit telephone line was opened between London and Birmingham by the [[National Telephone Company]]; for the first time this allowed phone calls between the London and the north.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.btplc.com/Thegroup/BTsHistory/1881to1911/1890.htm|title=1881to1911|author=|date=|website=www.btplc.com|access-date=10 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714194552/http://www.btplc.com/Thegroup/BTsHistory/1881to1911/1890.htm|archive-date=14 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The world's first [[coaxial cable]] was laid between London and Birmingham in 1936 to give 40 channels for telephone traffic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.btplc.com/Thegroup/BTsHistory/1912to1968/1936.htm|title=1912to1968|author=|date=|website=www.btplc.com|access-date=10 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714162420/http://www.btplc.com/Thegroup/BTsHistory/1912to1968/1936.htm|archive-date=14 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and brought into use in 1938, later extended to Manchester in 1940.\n\n[[File:BaskervilleSpec.svg|thumb|left|The [[Baskerville]] font named after the inventor of typefaces]]\n[[Alexander Parkes]] invented the first man-made plastic ([[thermoplastic]]) in Birmingham in 1856. [[Arthur Leslie Large]] of Birmingham is credited with inventing the [[kettle]] in 1922. Princess Square, Wolverhampton, was the site of Britain's first traffic lights in 1927. Infra-red cameras were developed at the Royal Radar Establishment in Malvern (with EMI Electronics) in 1967. The world's first [[Maglev]] train operated at [[AirRail Link|Birmingham Airport]] in 1983. The tallest freestanding structure in the region is the chimney of [[Ironbridge power stations|Ironbridge power station]] at 673&nbsp;ft. [[John Baskerville]] of Birmingham, a former stone carver, largely invented fonts, or [[typeface]]s, for printing.\n\n{{See also|Automotive industry in the United Kingdom}}\n\nMuch of the UK's car industry would be centred in Coventry and Birmingham; most of this has now gone. [[Midland Motor Cylinder]] (part of [[Birmid Industries]]) of Smethwick was the largest producer of automobile [[cylinder block]]s in Europe. [[Fort Dunlop]] was Europe's largest tyre plant. [[Metro-Cammell]] in Birmingham made most of the 1970s and 1980s [[London Underground]] trains. [[MG Rover Group|MG Rover]] (a company of Rover) closed in 2005 (from 1885), The [[Ryton plant]], which made the [[Peugeot 206]], closed at the end of 2006, with production moving to [[Trnava]] in Slovakia, and some to a plant at [[Kol\u00edn]] in the [[Czech Republic]]. [[Alfred Herbert (company)|Alfred Herbert]] of Coventry was the largest [[tool builder|machine-tool manufacturer]] in the UK for many decades; it was brought down in the 1970s by advancing technology overseas, and complacent strategic decisions of the management (caught like a rabbit in the headlights), finally closing in 1982; many Midlands manufacturing companies followed similar fates in the 1970s and 1980s. Tube Investments was based at [[Tube Investments House]], [[Five Ways, Birmingham|Five Ways]], Edgbaston (now a [[Marriott International|Marriott]] hotel).\n\n[[File:Grazebrook Beam Engine.jpg|thumb|right|1817 Boulton & Watt beam blowing engine re-erected on the Dartmouth Circus roundabout, on the [[A4540 road|A4540]] and the A38(M)]]\n[[Henry Wiggin & Co]] of Hereford developed the metal [[alloy]]s necessary for other Midlands' (and beyond) automotive and aerospace companies \u2013 [[Inconel]], [[Incoloy]] and [[Nimonic]]. It was the lack of [[vanadium]] for [[High-temperature corrosion|high-melting point alloys]], caused by Royal Navy action, that prevented German [[Messerschmitt Me 262|Me 262]] engines being serviceable; had German World War 2 engineers had a greater supply of vanadium and [[molybdenum]], the engine life (around 12 hours maximum, from entering service in April 1944 to the end of the war) of their [[Junkers Jumo 004|jet engine]] would have increased much more, which would have been significant to the war's outcome. [[Bristol Siddeley]] developed the rocket engines for [[Black Arrow]] at Ansty; in fact all of R-R's rocket engines were developed and built there at R-R's Industrial and Marine Gas Turbine Division; Britain's smaller rocket engines for missiles were built by [[Bristol Aerojet]] in what is now [[North Somerset]]. High Duty Alloys at Redditch constructed (forged) the compressor and turbine blades for Whittle's first engines, and many of the early jet engines; it made [[Concorde]]'s airframe from the [[Hiduminium]] R.R.58 [[aluminium alloy]].\n\n[[Maxaret]], the world's first [[Anti-lock braking system|ABS]] [[Brake|braking]] system, was invented in Coventry by Dunlop in the early 1950s for aircraft; [[John Boyd Dunlop]] was a Scottish vet who had first produced the first pneumatic [[Tire|tyres]] in 1889. [[Matthew Piers Watt Boulton]], grandson of Matthew Boulton, and born in the area, invented the [[aileron]], an important [[Flight control surfaces|flight control surface]] in 1868, decades before the first actual flight. [[Triumph Engineering]] was a famous motorbike firm in Meriden. About a quarter of all British WWI planes were built in Coventry. The [[Jensen Interceptor]] FF was the first production four-wheel-drive car in the world, designed by Major [[Tony Rolt]], and built at their factory in West Bromwich.\n\nCadbury launched ''[[Cadbury Dairy Milk|Dairy Milk]]'' in 1905, ''[[Bournville (chocolate bar)|Bournville]]'' in 1906, ''[[Cadbury Dairy Milk Fruit & Nut|Fruit & Nut]]'' in 1928, ''Whole Nut'' in 1930, ''[[Cadbury Roses]]'' in 1938, and the ''[[Cadbury Creme Egg]]'' in 1971. [[George Cadbury|George]] and [[Richard Cadbury]] built their factory in 1879 and [[Bournville]] in 1893, named after the [[Bournbrook|Bourn brook]]. [[Iceland (supermarket)]] opened its first store in Oswestry in 1970 \u2013 heralding the onset of frozen food in the UK. [[Alfred Bird]] invented egg-free custard in 1837 in Birmingham \u2013 accidentally given to guests at his home, being created as his wife had an allergy to eggs; he then invented [[baking powder]] in 1843 as his wife also had an allergy to [[yeast]].\n\n===Culture===\n[[J. R. R. Tolkien]] grew up in Birmingham, Kings Heath, then part of Worcestershire, and was inspired by [[Moseley Bog]] and [[Sarehole]], and perhaps by the [[Perrott's Folly]]. [[Philip Larkin]] came from Coventry. [[Rowland Hill]] (stamps) was from Kidderminster. The writer [[George Eliot]] came from [[Nuneaton]]. [[Anthony E. Pratt]] from Birmingham invented [[Cluedo]].\n\n[[Frederick Gibberd]] of Coventry designed [[Liverpool Metropolitan Cathedral]]. [[Edward Cave]] from Rugby made Britain's first magazine in 1731 \u2013 [[The Gentleman's Magazine]]. [[Philip Astley]] from Newcastle under Lyme invented the modern day circus in 1768 \u2013 [[Astley's Amphitheatre]].\n\nThe [[Castlemorton Common Festival]] in May 1992 near Malvern, led to the [[Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994]].\n\nThe highest numbered building in the UK is 2679 Stratford Road, [[A3400 road|Stratford Road]], [[Hockley Heath]].\n\nThe [[Nowka Bais]] is a [[Bengali culture|Bengali]] [[boat racing]] festival which takes place annually in [[Birmingham]]. It is a leading cultural event in the [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]], [[United Kingdom]] attracting not only the [[Bangladeshi diaspora]] but a variety of cultures.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.berkeleygroup.co.uk/news-and-insights/news/2019/st-joseph-makes-a-splash|title=St Joseph makes a splash at the 2019 Nowka Bais|website=Berkeley Group|access-date=5 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905132411/https://www.berkeleygroup.co.uk/news-and-insights/news/2019/st-joseph-makes-a-splash|archive-date=5 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It is also the largest kind of [[boat race]] in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/free-festival-street-food-dragon-14826783|publisher=[[Birmingham Mail]]|last=Bentley|first=David|date=29 July 2018|title=Free festival with street food and dragon boat racing returns to Birmingham|access-date=5 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905155927/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/free-festival-street-food-dragon-14826783|archive-date=5 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Regional assembly==\n\n{{Update|section|date=October 2014}}\n\nThe official representative body of the region is the [[West Midlands Leaders Board]] which has limited administrative functions such as regional planning and economic development. The board is not an elected body, but is made up of members appointed from local councils across the region and is known as a [[quango]]. It is based on ''Edward Street'' in Birmingham, near the [[National Indoor Arena]]. From March 2010, the funding decisions at regional level were taken over by [[Advantage West Midlands]], the [[Regional Development Agency]].\n\n==Demographics==\n\n===Ethnicity===\n[[File:United Kingdom European Union referendum 2016 voting area results (West Midlands).svg|thumb|450px|right|How the West Midlands region voted in the June 2016 [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|European Union referendum]]; only the (university) district of Warwick voted (58.8%) to stay in the EU; the region had the highest overall vote (59.3%) to leave, with large proportions in Stoke-on-Trent (69.4%) and [[Cannock Chase District|Cannock Chase]] (68.9%)]]\nThe West Midlands is the second most ethnically diverse region of the UK (London being the most diverse). This is in large part due to the [[West Midlands conurbation]], which is highly diverse. The ethnic makeup of the West Midlands as a whole as measured by the 2011 census was as follows:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|-\n!Ethnic group || 2011<br>population || 2011<br>%\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | White: [[White British|British]] || 4,434,333 || 79.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | White: [[Irish Briton|Irish]] || 55,216 || 1.0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | White: [[Irish Traveller]]/[[Romani people|Gypsy]]<ref group=\"note\">In 2001 part of the White Other category. New category created for the 2011 census</ref> || 4,734 || 0.1\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | White: [[White Other (United Kingdom Census)|Other]] ||139,386 || 2.5\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | '''[[White people|White]]: Total''' || '''4,633,669''' ||  \n'''82.7'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Asian or Asian British: [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|Indian]] || 218 439 || 3.9\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Asian or Asian British: [[British Pakistani|Pakistani]] || 227,248 || 4.1\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Asian or Asian British: [[British Bangladeshi|Bangladeshi]] || 52,477 || 0.9\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Asian or Asian British: [[British Chinese|Chinese]]|| 31,274 ||0.6\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Asian or Asian British: [[British Asian|Asian Other]] || 74,997 || 1.3\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | '''[[Asian people|Asian]] or [[British Asian|Asian British]]: Total''' || '''604,435''' || \n'''10.8'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Black or Black British: [[British African-Caribbean community|Caribbean]] || 86,794 || 1.6\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Black or Black British: [[Black British|African]] || 64,253 || 1.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Black or Black British: [[Other Black|Other]] || 31,078 || 0.6\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | '''[[Black people|Black]] or [[Black British]]: Total''' || '''182,125''' || \n'''3.3'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Mixed: [[White people|White]] and [[British African-Caribbean community|Caribbean]] || 68,533 || 1.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Mixed: [[White people|White]] and [[Black British|African]] || 9,232 || 0.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Mixed: [[White people|White]] and [[British Asian|Asian Other]] || 32,561 || 0.6\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Mixed: [[Multiracial|Other Mixed]] || 21,388 || 0.4\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | '''[[British Mixed]]: Total''' || '''131,714''' || \n'''2.4'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Other: [[Arab people|Arab]]<ref group=\"note\">In 2001 part of the 'Other' category. New category created for the 2011 census</ref> || 18,079 || 0.3\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | Other: Any other ethnic group || 31,825 || 0.6\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | '''Other: Total''' || '''49,904''' || \n'''0.9'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\" | '''Total''' || '''5,601,847''' || \n'''100'''\n|}\n\n===Teenage pregnancy===\nFor top-tier authorities in the West Midlands, Stoke-on-Trent has the highest [[Teenage pregnancy and sexual health in the United Kingdom|teenage pregnancy]] rate. For council districts, [[Nuneaton and Bedworth]] in Warwickshire has the highest rate closely followed by [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]]. For top-tier authorities, Shropshire has the lowest rate, and for council districts [[Malvern Hills (district)|Malvern Hills]] has the lowest rate.\n\n===Social deprivation===\nThe region, from studies of multiple deprivation, shows similarities with [[Yorkshire and the Humber]], and is more deprived than the neighbouring East Midlands. From the [[Indices of deprivation 2007]], it can be seen that, in common with [[Northern England]], the region has more [[Super Output Areas|Lower Area Super Output Areas]] in the 20% most deprived districts than in the 20% least deprived districts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.communities.gov.uk/documents/communities/pdf/576659.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120609171001/http://www.communities.gov.uk/documents/communities/pdf/576659.pdf|url-status=dead|title=LSOA data|archivedate=9 June 2012}}</ref> The region's most deprived council districts, in descending order, are Birmingham (10th highest in England), Sandwell (14th), Stoke-on-Trent (16th), Wolverhampton (28th), Walsall (45th), Coventry (61st), and Dudley (100th). These have Labour MPs except for a Conservative MP in Walsall, one in Sandwell, one in Dudley, and one in Wolverhampton ([[Wolverhampton South West (UK Parliament constituency)|Wolverhampton South West]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.communities.gov.uk/communities/neighbourhoodrenewal/deprivation/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413213602/http://www.communities.gov.uk/communities/neighbourhoodrenewal/deprivation/|url-status=dead|title=Communities and Local Government 2007|archivedate=13 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe least deprived districts in 2007 (before Shropshire became a unitary authority in 2009) were Bromsgrove, South Staffordshire, Warwick, Wychavon, and Lichfield. These areas, like all rural areas of the West Midlands, have Conservative MPs. At county level, the least deprived areas, in descending order, were Warwickshire, Worcestershire, Solihull, Staffordshire, and Shropshire.\n\nIn March 2011 the region had the second highest overall [[Jobseeker's Allowance|unemployment claimant]] count in England at 4.7%, second to [[North East England]]. The highest in the region was Wolverhampton at 7.7%, the joint second highest (with Manchester) unemployment rate in England. Next is Sandwell with 7.1%, Birmingham with 7.0%, and Walsall with 6.4%. The lowest rate in the region is the district of [[Stratford-on-Avon (district)|Stratford-on-Avon]], with 1.6% \u2013 one of the lowest unemployment rates in England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/elmr/downloads/Table6-18.xls|title=Claimant count}}</ref>\n\n===Elections===\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2015}}\nThe [[Green Party of England and Wales]] was formed at the Bridge Inn in [[Napton-on-the-Hill]], Warwickshire, in February 1973,\nand originated from an article by [[Paul R. Ehrlich]] about population growth in ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine; it became the Ecology Party in 1975 and the Green Party in 1985; the first conference was in June 1973 at ''The Allesley Hotel'' at the [[A4114 road|A4114]]/A45 junction south of the main Jaguar works in [[Allesley]], in west Coventry.\n\n[[File:United Kingdom General Election 2017 Results Map (West Midlands).svg|thumb|right|General Election results in 2017]]\nIn the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]], [[Nuneaton (UK Parliament constituency)|Nuneaton]] was taken by Labour with a 7% swing, which was one of the largest swings of the night; in the 2015 election, the Nuneaton result would largely seal the eventual outcome of the election. In the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], [[North Warwickshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Warwickshire]] ([[Dan Byles]]) had the smallest Conservative majority, with 54; [[Stoke-on-Trent Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent Central]] had the smallest number of winning votes, with 12,220.\n\nIn the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], the Conservatives gained the largest share of the region by popular vote and took control of the number of seats, with 42% of the region's electorate voting Conservative, 33% Labour, 16% UKIP, 6% Liberal Democrat and 3% Green. The Conservatives gained 2 seats with virtually no swing from Labour to Conservative.\n\nIn the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]], [[South Staffordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Staffordshire]] ([[Gavin Williamson]]) had the second-highest Conservative vote proportion in the UK \u2013 69.8%. [[David Firth (statistician)|David Firth]], at the [[University of Warwick]], invented the BBC election [[exit poll]]. 6&nbsp;ft 9 [[Daniel Kawczynski]], a Shropshire MP, is the tallest MP ever.\n\nAlthough having a slightly smaller percentage of the vote than the neighbouring [[East Midlands]], the geographic area of the West Midlands is more Conservative, due to Labour's vote now consigned to the urban areas of Birmingham, Coventry and Stoke-on-Trent. The number of seats is more favoured towards Labour than the geographic spread, with 35 Conservative seats and 24 Labour. All of Warwickshire, Staffordshire, Herefordshire, Worcestershire and Shropshire is now Conservative.\n\n{{Constituencies in the West Midlands}}\n\n===Eurostat NUTS===\nIn the [[Eurostat]] [[Nomenclature of Territorial Units for Statistics]] (NUTS), the West Midlands form a level-1 NUTS region, coded \"UKG\", which is subdivided as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:gold; text-align:left;\"\n! NUTS 1\n! Code\n! NUTS 2\n! Code\n! NUTS 3\n! Code\n|-\n| West Midlands\n| UKG\n| rowspan=3 | [[Herefordshire]], Worcestershire and [[Warwickshire]]\n| rowspan=3 | UKG1\n| [[Herefordshire]]\n| UKG11\n|-\n| rowspan=\"13\" colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:NUTS 3 regions of the West Midlands 2010 map.svg|240px]]\n| [[Worcestershire]] CC\n| UKG12\n|-\n| [[Warwickshire]] CC\n| UKG13\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | [[Shropshire]] and [[Staffordshire]]\n| rowspan=4 | UKG2\n| [[Telford and Wrekin]]\n| UKG21\n|-\n| [[Shropshire]]\n| UKG22\n|-\n| [[Stoke-on-Trent]]\n| UKG23\n|-\n| [[Staffordshire]] CC\n| UKG24\n|-\n| rowspan=7 | [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]\n| rowspan=7 | UKG3\n| [[Birmingham]]\n| UKG31\n|-\n| [[Metropolitan Borough of Solihull|Solihull]]\n| UKG32\n|-\n| [[Coventry]]\n| UKG33\n|-\n| [[Metropolitan Borough of Dudley|Dudley]] \n| UKG36\n|-\n| [[Sandwell]]\n| UKG37\n|-\n| [[Metropolitan Borough of Walsall|Walsall]]\n| UKG38\n|-\n| [[Wolverhampton]]\n| UKG39\n|}\n\n==Local government==\nThe [[Regions of England|region]] consists of the following administrative subdivisions:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Map || Ceremonial county || Shire county / unitary || Districts\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\" | [[File:West Midlands counties 2009 map.svg|250px]] || colspan=\"3\" | 1.&nbsp;[[Herefordshire]] U.A.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Shropshire]] || colspan=\"2\" | 2.&nbsp;[[Shropshire Council|Shropshire]] U.A.\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | 3.&nbsp;[[Telford and Wrekin]] U.A.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Staffordshire]] || 4.&nbsp;Staffordshire&nbsp;\u2020 || ''a'')&nbsp;[[Cannock Chase (district)|Cannock Chase]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[East Staffordshire]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Lichfield (district)|Lichfield]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[Newcastle-under-Lyme (borough)|Newcastle-under-Lyme]], ''e'')&nbsp;[[South Staffordshire]],  ''f'')&nbsp;[[Stafford (borough)|Stafford]], ''g'')&nbsp;[[Staffordshire Moorlands]], ''h'')&nbsp;[[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | 5.&nbsp;[[Stoke-on-Trent]] U.A.\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | 6.&nbsp;[[Warwickshire]]&nbsp;\u2020 || ''a'')&nbsp;[[North Warwickshire]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[Nuneaton and Bedworth]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Rugby (borough)|Rugby]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[Stratford-on-Avon (district)|Stratford-on-Avon]], ''e'')&nbsp;[[Warwick (district)|Warwick]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | 7.&nbsp;[[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]&nbsp;* || ''a'')&nbsp;[[Birmingham]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[Coventry]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Dudley (borough)|Dudley]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[Sandwell (borough)|Sandwell]], ''e'')&nbsp;[[Solihull (borough)|Solihull]], ''f'')&nbsp;[[Walsall (borough)|Walsall]], ''g'')&nbsp;[[Wolverhampton]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | 8.&nbsp;[[Worcestershire]]&nbsp;\u2020 || ''a'')&nbsp;[[Bromsgrove (district)|Bromsgrove]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[Malvern Hills (district)|Malvern Hills]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Redditch]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[Worcester]], ''e'')&nbsp;[[Wychavon]], ''f'')&nbsp;[[Wyre Forest (district)|Wyre Forest]]\n|}\n\nKey: \u2020two-tier [[non-metropolitan county]]  |  *[[metropolitan county]] including the [[West Midlands Combined Authority]] and [[Mayor of the West Midlands|mayor]]\n\n===Demography===\n[[File:Statue of St Michael and Satan -Coventry Cathedral-5July2008.jpg|thumb|right|Statue of St Michael and Satan at [[Coventry Cathedral]] ]]\n[[File:BirminghamUK skyline Centenary Square 700.jpg|right|thumb|Urban [[Birmingham]], [[Centenary Square]].]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Ceremonial County\n! Population\n! Population density\n! Largest local authority\n! Largest settlement\n|-\n| '''West Midlands (region)'''\n| '''5,267,337'''\n| '''405/km\u00b2'''\n| '''[[Birmingham]] (1,006,500)'''\n| '''Birmingham (1,006,500)'''\n|-\n| [[West Midlands (county)]]\n| 2,600,100\n| 2,884/km\u00b2\n| Birmingham (1,006,500)\n| Birmingham (1,006,500)\n|-\n| [[Staffordshire]]\n| 1,062,500\n| 391/km\u00b2\n| [[Stoke-on-Trent]] (240,636)\n| Stoke-on-Trent (259,252)\n|-\n| [[Worcestershire]]\n| 552,900\n| 318/km\u00b2\n| [[Wychavon]] (116,300)\n| [[Worcester]] (93,400)\n|-\n| [[Warwickshire]]\n| 522,200\n| 264/km\u00b2\n| [[Warwick (district)|Warwick]] (132,900)\n| [[Nuneaton]] (70,721)\n|-\n| [[Shropshire]]\n| 451,100\n| 129/km\u00b2\n| [[Shropshire Council|Shropshire]] (290,900)\n| [[Telford]] (138,241)\n|-\n| [[Herefordshire]]\n| 177,800\n| 82/km\u00b2\n| N/A<ref>County of [[Hereford]] forms single local government unit ([[Unitary Authority]])</ref>\n| [[Hereford]] (50,400)\n|}\n\nThe West Midlands' population accounts for almost 11% of England's overall population. 49.36% of the region's population resides in the West Midlands county, 20.17% in Staffordshire, 10.49% in Worcestershire, 9.91% in Warwickshire, 8.56% in Shropshire, and 3.37% in Herefordshire.\n\n==Economy==\n{{More citations needed section|date=January 2017}}\n{{overly detailed|section|date=December 2018}}\n[[File:JCB Chairman - Sir Anthony Bamford.JPG|thumb|upright|left|Lord Bamford, the wealthiest British-nationality businessman]]\n[[Business Link]] West Midlands<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businesslink.gov.uk/west_midlands.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005055307/http://www.businesslink.gov.uk/west_midlands.html|url-status=dead|title=Business Link|archivedate=5 October 2012}}</ref> was based on the Quinton Business Park in [[Quinton, Birmingham|Quinton]], next to [[Highways England]] and the M5 at the [[A456 road|A456]] Quinton Interchange. NHS West Midlands, the [[NHS strategic health authority|strategic health authority]] was on Hagley Road (A456) in Edgbaston. The [[West Midlands Ambulance Service]] is on the Waterfront Business Park in [[Brierley Hill]], off the [[A461 road|A461]], near the headquarters of [[West Midlands Police]], where the [[Child Support Agency]] (CSA) was headquartered. The region's [[Manufacturing Advisory Service]] was on [[Wolverhampton Science Park]] off the [[A449 road|A449]] north of the city centre; this function is now represented by [[Made in the Midlands]], off M4 junction 2 at Pendeford north of Wolverhampton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mas-wm.org/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122225314/http://www.mas-wm.org/|url-status=dead|title=MAS \u2013 Manufacturing Advisory Service|archivedate=22 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Department for International Trade|DIT]] West Midlands (previously [[UK Trade & Investment|UKTI]]) for the region<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ukti-teams-in-the-english-regions/ukti-west-midlands-helping-companies-export-and-grow-overseas|title=DIT West Midlands: helping companies export and grow overseas|first1=DIT West|last1=Midl|first2=find out how DIT can|last2=help|date=|website=GOV.UK|access-date=23 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170823204623/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ukti-teams-in-the-english-regions/ukti-west-midlands-helping-companies-export-and-grow-overseas|archive-date=23 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> is based at the [[West Midlands Chambers of Commerce]] on ''Harborne Road'' (B4284), south of NHS West Midlands west of Five Ways; this was previously at the B4100/B4114 junction south of Aston University near the Matthew Boulton Campus of [[Birmingham Metropolitan College]]. Most of the region is covered by the [[Midlands Air Ambulance]], except Warwickshire is covered by the [[Warwickshire & Northamptonshire Air Ambulance]], based at [[Coventry Airport]]; both are charity-funded. Sir [[Anthony Bamford]] of Staffordshire is the richest British industrialist, at around \u00a33.15bn in 2014; Sir [[James Dyson]] is second (\u00a33bn).\n\n===Herefordshire===\n[[File:Cider orchards east of Hereford 2 - geograph.org.uk - 899483.jpg|thumb|right|Bulmers cider orchard east of Hereford, near the [[River Wye]] ]]\n[[H. P. Bulmer|Bulmers Cider]] is in Hereford within walking distance of [[Hereford railway station|Hereford station]]; it is the world's largest [[cider]] factory, and has the world's largest vat (for [[Strongbow (cider)|Strongbow]]), built in 1975.  [[Painter Brothers]] (part of [[Balfour Beatty]]) on the Aydon Ind Est off the A49 near [[Hereford Racecourse]] in the north of Hereford, is the UK's largest manufacturer of electricity pylons ([[transmission tower]]s), [[Radio masts and towers|broadcasting mast]]s, the [[Callender-Hamilton bridge]], and [[Railway electrification in Great Britain|rail electrification]] structures. [[Henry Wiggin|Special Metals Wiggin]], part of [[Special Metals Corporation]], based at Hereford was the main producer of [[List of alloys|nickel alloys]] in Europe, with a large site directly north of Painter Brothers at the A49/A4103 junction; further north on the A49 at Moreton Business Park at [[Moreton-on-Lugg]] is GEA Denco (part of [[GEA Group]]) who make [[dehumidifier]]s.  The [[Special Reconnaissance Regiment]] was formed in 2005. At Hereford, [[Cargill Meat Solutions|Cargill Meats Europe]] (formerly Sun Valley) have a large poultry meat processing facility, processing chickens from around [[Herefordshire]].\n\n[[Cadbury]] (Mondel\u0113z International) make milk chocolate crumb near [[Marlbrook, Herefordshire|Marlbrook]] (near [[Leominster]]).  [[Weston's Cider]] is in [[Much Marcle]], south-west of [[Ledbury]] at the [[A449 road|A449]]/B4024 junction, who also make Stowford Press.  Wye Fruit Ltd is in the north of Ledbury on the B4214; in the west of the town, off the [[A417 road|A417]] bypass is a large site of [[Amcor]], and further west is Universal Beverages (UBL), owned by Heineken since 2007 where it cans cider; the site of Ledbury Preserves of RHM made [[Robertson's]] jam, mincemeat and marmalade and closed in 2008 when production moved to [[Histon and Impington|Histon]] in Cambridgeshire. [[Atora]] suet has been made in Ledbury since around 2003, when production was moved from Teesside by RHM to a former factory of [[Just Juice]], which was bought by [[Del Monte Foods|Del Monte]] in 1999.  Holden Aluminium Technologies are a sports car chassis manufacturer at [[Linton, Bringsty|Linton]] on the [[A44 road|A44]], east of [[Bromyard]].  [[Kingspan Group|Kingspan Insulation]] is based at [[Pembridge]], next to [[Shobdon Aerodrome]], west of [[Leominster]] off the A44.  BT's [[Madley Communications Centre]], claims to be the world's largest [[Ground station|earth station]].  [[Tyrrells (crisps)|Tyrrells Potato Crisps]] are off the B4457 at [[Dilwyn]] west of Leominster, near the A44.\n\n===Shropshire===\n[[Rayburn Range]] and [[Aga Rangemaster Group]] are based in [[Telford]]; the [[People's Dispensary for Sick Animals|PDSA]] is in [[St George's and Priorslee]], Telford next to the M54 near the B5061/A5 Priorslee Roundabout; opposite the [[M54]] on Stafford Park is [[Virgin Balloon Flights]].  [[Hymix]] who make mountable [[concrete mixer]]s are on the east of Stafford Park near the A464. The [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|MoD]] have a significant depot at [[Lilleshall and Donnington]].  There are also high-technology industries such as [[Unimation]], [[Nikon]], [[Hitachi Maxell]], [[Ricoh]], [[Capgemini]], [[Fujitsu]] and [[Electronic Data Systems]].  In [[Hadley Castle]] off the A442, [[Denso]] Manufacturing UK Ltd make [[Car air conditioning|car air-conditioning systems]] and [[GKN]] Wheels make car wheels.  Nearby is [[Ogihara Corporation|Ogihara]] Europe, a tool making ([[Die (manufacturing)|die]]s and [[Machine press|press]]) and metal-pressing company.  [[Makita]] Manufacturing Europe off the [[A518 road|A518]] at Hortonwood,  Telford is the only plant in the UK that makes [[power tool]]s.  [[Chequer Foods]] (owned by the Chiswick-based [[Autobar Group]]), off the A442 near the A4169 junction in [[Halesfield]] to the south, make food sachets for the foodservice industry and [[Operational Ration Pack|UK's military ration pack]]s.\n\n[[M\u00fcller (company)|M\u00fcller Dairy Ltd]] is based in [[Market Drayton]], and [[Palethorpes]], part of [[Pork Farms]] which makes own-label sausages, is on the same site on [[A53 road|A53]].  At [[Crudgington]], [[Dairy Crest]] made ''Country Life'' butter and [[Clover (spread)|Clover]] until February 2015, and have their Technical Centre.  Anglo Beef Processors ([[ABP Food Group]]) are at [[Harlescott]] in the north of Shrewsbury.  Nearby [[Stadco]], a metal pressings company, are based off the A5124 and next to the railway, on the [[Battlefield, Shropshire|Battlefield]] Ind Estate and have a site at [[Hadley Castle]], Telford off the [[A442 road|A442]]. [[Uniq plc]] have a plant on the [[A488 road|A488]] at [[Minsterley]] making chilled desserts for Tesco.\n\nBT have their [[National Network Management Centre]] (Whittington House) off the A495 near the A5 roundabout on the Oswestry bypass in [[Whittington, Shropshire]]. Military helicopter training in the UK takes place at [[RAF Shawbury]], alongside training for the RAF's [[air traffic controller]]s (ATC).\n\n===Staffordshire===\n[[File:JCB Diesel Max Heritage Motor Centre, Gaydon.jpg|thumb|left|[[JCB Dieselmax]], holder of the [[land speed record]] for diesel-engined vehicles]]\nThe brewing companies such as [[Molson Coors Brewing Company|Coors Brewers]] are in [[Burton on Trent]], as well as [[Marmite]], [[Marston's Brewery]], [[General Nutrition Centers|GNC UK]] ([[Dietary supplement|health supplements]]), and [[Doncasters]] (aerospace components and steel [[forging]], founded by [[Daniel Doncaster]] of Sheffield). [[Conder Structures]] is a structural steel company next to Marmite on the A5121, and further south [[Johnson Controls]] make seats for Toyota in [[Branston, Staffordshire|Branston]]. [[Spirit Pub Company]] (which demerged from Punch Taverns in August 2011, and owns [[Chef & Brewer]], [[Flaming Grill]] and [[Fayre & Square]]) is near the A5121/A38 junction, with [[Punch Taverns]] slightly further north. [[Marley Eternit]] (part of the Belgium [[Etex Group]]), who make [[Eternit]] [[fibre cement]] roofing (often seen on industrial buildings) are based on the west side of the A38 in the south of Branston, (with another large plant at the [[A525 road|A525]]/[[A531 road|A531]] junction in [[Madeley, Staffordshire|Madeley]] near the M6 at [[Keele]]); next door in [[Dunstall]], [[Lanxess]] UK (former W. Hawley) make pigments.\n\n[[File:Roundabout by Michelin Factory - geograph.org.uk - 336395.jpg|thumb|right|The Michelin Man ([[Bibendum]]) at Sideway in Stoke, with his name originating from the Latin phrase ''Nunc est bibendum'']]\n[[Newell Rubbermaid]] UK (owner of [[Parker Pen Company|Parker Pen]], [[Berol]], [[Paper Mate]] and [[DYMO Corporation|DYMO]]), [[Graco (baby products)|Graco]] ([[Baby transport|buggies]]), a large [[Distribution center|RDC]] of Tesco, and [[Zytek]] (motorsport) are at [[Fradley]] Park, next to the A38, on an [[RAF Lichfield|old airfield]]. [[Norgren (company)|Norgren]] (part of IMI) is an international [[pneumatics|pneumatic]] technology company on the A5192 in Lichfield.\n\nOff the A522 north of Cheadle is JCB Earthmovers ([[Loader (equipment)|wheel loader]]s) and JCB Compact Products (mini excavators and [[skid-steer loader]]s). [[JCB (company)|JCB]] is based in Staffordshire, near the [[Alton Towers]] colossal leisure park; JCB Heavy Products (excavators), and their World Parts Centre are off the A50 in [[Uttoxeter Rural]] ([[Beamhurst]]). Lafarge Cement UK (former [[Blue Circle Industries|Blue Circle]]) have a large plant at [[Cauldon]] in [[Waterhouses, Staffordshire|Waterhouses]], between the A523 and A52.\n\n[[Michelin]] Tyres are made in [[Sideway]] in Stoke-on-Trent, next to Stoke's only [[St Joseph's College, Stoke-on-Trent|grammar school]] in the south of [[Trent Vale]]. [[Royal Doulton]] and [[Wedgwood]] are based in [[Barlaston]]. [[Emma Bridgewater]] make pottery on the A50 in Hanley. [[Tile Giant]] (owned by Travis Perkins since 2007) is based on the B5039 in Longton, and [[Walkers' Nonsuch]] make toffee on the A5007. [[Portmeirion Pottery]], who own the [[Royal Worcester]] brand, are on the B5041 in Stoke. [[Steelite International]] (pottery) are based at [[Middleport, Staffordshire|Middleport]], in west Burslem, next to the [[Trent and Mersey Canal]]. [[Dudson]] (pottery) is on the A50 in the north end of Burslem, towards Tunstall. [[Johnson Tiles]] and [[Norcros Adhesives]] (owned by [[Norcros]]) is in the west of Tunstall. [[Wade Ceramics]] is in [[Etruria, Staffordshire|Etruria]] to the east of Wolstanton, near the A53/A500 junction off the A53, near the HQ of the Sentinel newspaper ([[DMG Media|Harmsworth Printing]]). [[Swan Products]] ([[teasmade]]s and small appliances, owned by Littlewoods) are based in [[Fenton, Staffordshire|Fenton]]. [[Premier Foods]] make [[Mr Kipling]] slices and [[Bakewell tart|Cherry Bakewells]] in Trent Vale in the south of Stoke-on-Trent.\n\n[[Bet365]] is on [[Stoke-on-Trent Garden Festival|Festival Park]] in [[Etruria, Staffordshire|Etruria]], off the [[A53 road|A53]], and is Stoke-on-Trent's largest private sector employer. [[Goodwin Steel Castings]] make steel [[Casting (metalworking)|casting]]s in the east of Stoke on the A52. [[The Co-operative Pharmacy]] National Distribution Centre is on the A50 at [[Meir, Staffordshire|Meir]], on the former site of [[Cookson Ceramics]] (later [[Johnson Matthey]] until its closure in 2003). [[Dechra Pharmaceuticals]] make [[Veterinary pharmacist|veterinary pharmaceutical]]s at [[Talke]], off the A34. [[Churchill China]] are at Sandyford near [[Tunstall, Staffordshire|Tunstall]] at the A50/[[A527 road|A527]] junction. [[Sumitomo Corporation|Sumitomo Electrical Wiring Systems (Europe)]], who supply wiring for the automotive industry, are in [[Silverdale, Staffordshire|Silverdale]], not far from [[Keele University]]. At [[Kidsgrove]] off the A34, [[Converteam]] (former GEC) make [[Adjustable-speed drive|variable speed drive]]s (VSDs); AAH Pharmaceuticals have their Enterprise and Trident divisions in [[Talke]], in the west of Kidsgrove, off the [[A5011 road|A5011]]. [[AWS Electronics]] have a factory, off the A34 north of Newcastle. [[Phones 4u]] was at [[Knutton]] in the north of [[Borough of Newcastle-under-Lyme|Newcastle-under-Lyme]] until it went bankrupt in 2014. Off the B5500 in [[Chesterton, Staffordshire|Chesterton]] in the north-west of Newcastle, [[Broxap]] are a leading supplier of [[cast iron]] [[street furniture]]. [[Andritz AG|Andritz]] UK (engineering) are at Wolstanton, off the A34 in the north of Newcastle.\n\n[[File:Marmite-Guinness edition.JPG|thumb|right|Marmite is made from the [[Yeast extract|yeast left over]] from the [[Beer in England|brewing industry]] ]]\n[[RoadChef]] are at [[Norton Canes]], near [[Cannock]]. Tallent Automotive (previously [[ThyssenKrupp]], now owned by [[Gestamp Automoci\u00f3n|Gestamp]] since 2011) make [[Suspension (vehicle)|car suspension]]s and [[crossmember]]s at Cannock. [[Electrium]] ([[Wylex]] [[Residual-current device|RCD]]s, and Crabtree and Volex electrical wiring) is on the A460 next to the M6 toll at [[Bridgtown]]. [[Mann+Hummel]] UK, on the A460 south of M54 junction 1 at [[Featherstone, Staffordshire|Featherstone]], make [[Air filter|air]] and [[oil filter]]s. [[Motivair]], who make [[air compressor]]s, is based off the A5190 in [[Burntwood]]; [[Mizkan]] Europe (who now own [[Branston (brand)|Branston Pickle]] in Suffolk) make vinegar. Armitage Shanks (owned by [[Ideal Standard]] International) are in the east of Rugeley off the A513 in [[Armitage with Handsacre]], near the WCML; JCB Cab Systems are next to the A51 on the Riverside Ind Est.\n\nThe UK headquarters of [[Alstom]] Grid (former [[Areva]] T&D UK, and [[General Electric Company plc|GEC]]) is based in [[Stafford]] as well as a factory and the UK headquarters of [[Bostik]] (a subsidiary of [[Total S.A.|TOTAL]]). Alstom Power repair electrical generators. [[Altecnic]], who work with [[Caleffi]] of Italy, is in the north of Stafford in [[Creswell, Staffordshire|Creswell]], off M6 junction 14, and supply [[Piping and plumbing fitting|plumbing fitting]]s. MICROMINIATURES on the B5026 in Stone claim to be Europe's leading supplier of [[ice cream van]] chime equipment.\n\n[[Invotec Group]], a [[Printed circuit board|PCB]] manufacturer, is based off the A51 in [[Dosthill]], south of Tamworth. [[Numark (pharmacy)|Numark Pharmacy]] is in [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]] (former base of [[Reliant]]). JVM Castings make [[crankcase]]s off the A51 at The Leys in Tamworth, and have a site in Worcester. [[Bristan]] (owned by [[Masco]]) based in [[Dordon]] and [[Baddesley Ensor]] on the Birch Coppice Business Park south-west of Tamworth, next to a new [[Ocado]] distribution centre, is the UK's largest supplier of kitchen and bathroom taps; Volkswagen Group (VAG UK) have their main UK distribution facility there, the site of [[Birch Coppice Colliery]] before 1987; nearby [[Maersk]] have their [[Birmingham Intermodal Freight Terminal]] (rail). [[Ansell]] UK ([[medical glove]]s, from Australia) is on Tamworth Enterprise Park, off the A51 next to the West Coast Main Line; they also produce [[Mates condoms]]. [[Lyalvale Express]] make [[Shotgun shell|shotgun cartridge]]s north of Tamworth next to the WCML at [[Fisherwick]]. [[Whittington Barracks]] (DMS Whittington) near to the west is the home of the [[Defence Medical Services]] and [[Defence Dental Service]], and soon the [[Defence Medical Services Training Centre]].\n\n[[Premier Foods]] make [[Bird's Custard]], [[Angel Delight]] and [[Marvel (food)|Marvel]] [[powdered milk]] in [[Knighton, Stafford, Staffordshire|Knighton]], west of [[Eccleshall]] near the Shropshire boundary. [[Static Systems Group]] (SSG) in Wombourne, south Staffordshire, make most of the [[Nurse call button|nurse call]] systems for the NHS. Kerrygold have a large cheese production site on the [[A53 road|A53]] in [[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]] on the [[Barnfields]] Industrial Estate.\n\nOn the Balliol Business Park, in [[Bilbrook, Staffordshire|Bilbrook]] and directly west of Fordhouses in Wolverhampton north of [[Pendeford]], Cargill process poultry (with another site at Hereford), and next door is [[Moog Inc.|Moog Aircraft]] ([[GE Aviation]] Systems before September 2009, which had bought [[Smiths Aerospace]] in May 2007) which makes [[Aircraft flight control system|flight control]] actuation systems (for the hydraulics on Boeing and Airbus), to move to the [[I54]] Business Park in Bilbrook; the Balliol Business Park was formerly the site of [[Boulton Paul Aircraft]], that made the [[Boulton Paul Defiant|Defiant]].\n\n===Warwickshire===\n[[File:Dennis Eagle works entrance, Heathcote Industrial Estate, Warwick-Leamington - geograph.org.uk - 1414920.jpg|thumb|left|Dennis Eagle bin wagon works at Warwick]]\n[[Bridgestone]] UK, [[Telent]] (near the A46 bypass), [[Calor Gas|Calor]] (on Tachbrook Park off the [[A452 road|A452]]), next to [[Co-operative Energy]] and near [[Magna Powertrain]] UK, [[Baxi]] (now owned by [[BDR Thermea]], and on the A429 near [[Warwick railway station]]) with [[Potterton (company)|Potterton]], [[Volvo Trucks]] UK (next to the A46 bypass) and a large data centre of [[IBM]] are in [[Warwick]]. [[Dennis Eagle]], who make bin wagons, are headquartered off the A452 on the [[Heathcote, Warwickshire|Heathcote]] Ind Estate, south of Calor Gas, in east Warwick towards Leamington. [[Godiva Fire Pumps|Godiva]] (former Hale Products Europe, part of the [[IDEX Corporation]]) are the UK's leading manufacturer of [[fire pump]]s off the [[A445 road|A445]] in [[Emscote]], east Warwick.\n\n[[File:IBM Warwick - geograph.org.uk - 1588694.jpg|thumb|right|IBM at Warwick]]\n[[Aga Rangemaster Group]] is on the north of Leamington Spa Business Park, and directly south is [[Wolseley UK]]; [[Gruppo Raicam|Raicam Clutches]] ([[Automotive Products]]) is south of Wolseley; to the west [[Grupo Antolin]] UK make vehicle interiors; on the same estate is Caparo AP Braking, and [[Delphi Automotive]] have an electronics centre. On the [[Warwick Technology Park]], south of Warwick on the [[A425 road|A425]], are [[Phillips 66]] UK (former ConocoPhillips) who own [[Jet (brand)|JET UK]] (petrol); to the east is [[McKesson Corporation|McKesson]]'s European HQ (who produce the software for the NHS's 1.4&nbsp;million employees' payroll \u2013 the largest payroll in the UK),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electronicstaffrecord.nhs.uk/|title=Electronic Staff Record|author=|date=|website=www.electronicstaffrecord.nhs.uk|access-date=19 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150629110106/http://www.electronicstaffrecord.nhs.uk/|archive-date=29 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and to the west is Tulip (who produce [[Spam (food)|SPAM]], with Plumrose and Danepak) in the UK and are owned by [[Danish Crown AmbA|Danish Crown Group]] \u2013 Europe's largest pork producer, near [[Midcounties Co-operative]] which is next to the wireless division of [[Arqiva]]; [[National Grid plc]] is in the centre of the park, and [[Allinea]] Software is at the Innovation Centre.\n\n[[File:NFU Mutual Headquarters, Tiddington - geograph.org.uk - 1727835.jpg|thumb|left|NFU Mutual headquarters at Tiddington, east of Stratford-upon-Avon]]\n[[NFU Mutual]] is in [[Tiddington, Warwickshire|Tiddington]] near Stratford and the [[National Farmers Union (England and Wales)|NFU]] is in [[Stoneleigh, Warwickshire|Stoneleigh]]; [[The Pony Club]] and other parts of the [[British Equestrian Federation]] are in Stoneleigh. [[AGCO]] Limited UK and its European Operations Centre is nearby at [[Stareton]], who own [[Massey Ferguson]] with [[Valtra]] UK; the large factory at Coventry closed in 2002. The [[British Horse Society]] is in [[Kenilworth]]. At [[Cubbington]] is the UK headquarters of [[Joma]], and has the Thwaites [[dumper]] manufacturer. [[Caparo Vehicle Technologies]] is off the [[B4087 road]] towards Leamington Spa. [[Codemasters]] is off the A425 in [[Long Itchington]], east of Leamington, opposite the 600-acre [[RLS Polo Club]]; directly east of Leamington on the A425 is Ricardo's [[Midlands Technical Centre]]. [[Recaro]] UK (car seats) is off the [[A4177 road|A4177]] next to a [[RAF Honiley|former airfield]] (now a proving ground), west of Kenilworth. Further north, the University of Warwick, on the Coventry/Warwickshire boundary, is home to the [[WMG (formerly Warwick Manufacturing Group)|Warwick Manufacturing Group]] technology consultancy and the [[Tata Motors]] European Technical Centre.\n\n[[SRS Frigadon]], off the [[A3400 road|A3400]] (former A34) at [[Atherstone on Stour]], is an Anglo-Swedish refrigeration company that makes [[chiller]]s and heat exchangers.\n\n[[File:Entrance to Daw Mill Colliery - geograph.org.uk - 210862.jpg|thumb|right|In 2008, the former [[Daw Mill]] colliery produced 3.2&nbsp;million tonnes of coal, a UK record]]\n[[BMW]] have their main European [[Straight-4|four-cylinder engine]] plant at [[Hams Hall]] near the M42. [[Subaru]] UK and [[Isuzu]] UK (IM Group) are sandwiched between the M6 and the M42 (south of junction 8) at the Coleshill Manor Office Campus, west of [[Coleshill, Warwickshire|Coleshill]]. Off the B4117 in the north of Coleshill is [[Thomas & Betts]] UK (former [[Adaptaflex]]), which makes [[Electrical conduit|flexible conduit]]s. [[TNT N.V.|TNT]] UK is off the B4116 in the west of [[Atherstone]], and [[Aldi]] UK is on the other side of the road; Aldi opened its first UK store on 17 July 1990 in Stechford, Birmingham, and now has around 700 UK stores. [[3M]] have an [[abrasive]] products ([[sandpaper]]) factory in the east of the town. [[Daw Mill]], next to the [[Birmingham to Peterborough Line|railway]], was Britain's biggest coal producer near the B4098/B4114 junction at [[Arley, Warwickshire|Arley]] and [[Over Whitacre]]. [[Holland & Barrett]] are Europe's largest health food chain, with 1,400 stores.  [[Triton Showers]] (the UK's largest shower company) are based in [[Nuneaton]]; [[Adams Childrenswear]], formerly on the A4254 on the [[Attleborough, Warwickshire|Attleborough]] Fields Ind Est, closed most of its stores in 2010.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nSouth of Nuneaton, at the [[A444 road|A444]]/B4113 roundabout is the national distribution centre of [[Dairy Crest]], where it also packages [[Cathedral City Cheddar|Cathedral City]] cheese. North of Coventry, [[Oleo International]] (its name is from the [[Oleo strut]]) is a world leader in [[Buffer (rail transport)|railway buffer]]s based on the B4113 in [[Exhall]], next to the M6. The [[London congestion charge]] is operated by Capita, based at Prologis Park (Bedworth) in the west of Exhall. [[Rolls-Royce plc|Rolls-Royce]] have a large engine overhaul plant (former [[Armstrong Siddeley]]), near [[Ansty, Warwickshire|Ansty]] and the M6/M69 junction in [[Coombe Fields]], which also makes their engine casings, built on a [[RAF Ansty|former airfield]]; [[Ansty Park]] is a new development on the same former airfield.\n\n[[Aston Martin]] and [[Jaguar Land Rover Gaydon Centre|Land Rover]] have their headquarters in [[Gaydon]]. Nearby to the south in the same area as the [[Battle of Edgehill]] (1642) west of the M40 is [[MoD Kineton]] (former [[Defence Storage and Distribution Agency]] or DSDA Kineton, now part of [[Defence Equipment and Support]] or DE&S), home of the Army School of Ammunition and [[Defence Explosive Ordnance Disposal, Munitions and Search Training Regiment]] which teaches [[bomb disposal]] (Improvised Explosive Device Disposal); on the opposite site of the B4086 is [[Marlborough Barracks]] and [[Defence Munitions Centre]] Kineton.\n\n[[File:Rugby-Millbuck House - geograph.org.uk - 1012751.jpg|thumb|right|Morgan Sindall Construction HQ on Corporation Street (B4632) in Rugby]]\n[[GE Power Conversion]] UK (former Alstom, then Converteam) and [[Morgan Sindall]] Construction & Infrastructure (former [[Morgan Est]]) are in [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]]. [[Alstom]] have their Power and Transport division in the north of Rugby on the [[A426 road|A426]], where they service [[steam turbine]]s; on the Swift Valley Ind Estate [[Premier Foods]] have their national distribution centre; on the same estate [[Ball Corporation|Ball Packaging Europe]] UK have a main plant ([[tin can]]s), and nearby are [[Mors\u00f8 (company)|Mors\u00f8]] UK ([[wood-burning stove]]s). The European HQ of [[Gap (clothing retailer)|Gap]] is in the north of Rugby, alongside the M6 in [[Churchover]]; Gap is the world's third-biggest fashion retailer, with 118 stores in the UK. [[CEMEX]] have the country's largest cement works, west of Rugby at the junction of the A428 and the [[A4071 road|A4071]] western bypass towards [[Long Lawford]] (former [[Rugby Cement]]).\n\n===West Midlands county===\n{{more footnotes|date=December 2018}}\n;In Central Birmingham\n*[[Mitchells and Butlers]] in [[pub chain|pubs, inns and restaurants]].\n*The [[Insolvency Service]]'s Intelligence and Enforcement Directorate.<ref>Intelligence and Enforcement Directorate, The Insolvency Service, 18 The Priory Queensway, Birmingham</ref>\n*[[Stamp duty in the United Kingdom|Stamp Duty Land Tax and stamp duty on shares]]<ref>HMRC Stamp Duty Taxes, [[City Centre House]], Birmingham</ref>\n*[[Ofwat]] in water;<ref>Ofwat, [[Centre City Tower (Birmingham)|Centre City Tower]], Birmingham</ref> relatedly in subject: the [[Consumer Council for Water]].<ref>The Consumer Council for Water, [[Victoria Square, Birmingham|Victoria Square]], Birmingham</ref>\n*National Debtline<ref>Tricorn House, 51\u201353 Hagley Rd, Birmingham \u2013 specifically near [[Five Ways, Birmingham|Five Ways]].</ref>\n*The [[Solicitors Regulation Authority]]<ref>SRA, [[The Cube (building)|The Cube]], Birmingham part of the Mailbox.</ref>\n*[[H. Samuel]], jewellers.<ref>H. Samuel, Hunters Road, [[Hockley, Birmingham|Hockley]] within the [[Jewellery Quarter]], Birmingham since 1912 http://www.hsamuel.co.uk/about_us {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180114183930/http://www.hsamuel.co.uk/about_us/ |date=14 January 2018 }}</ref>\n*[[J Hudson & Co]] the world's largest producer of [[whistle]]s make [[Acme Whistles]].<ref>J Hudson & Co 244 Barr Street, Boulton Middleway, Birmingham, namely in the Jewellery Quarter where the A41 and A4540 meet.</ref>\n*Deakin & Francis make [[cufflink]]s.<ref>Founded 1786, headquarters: Deakin & Francis, 15\u201317 Regent Pl, Birmingham</ref>\n*[[National Express]] and [[CrossCountry]] in transport.<ref>The latter at [[Cannon House, Birmingham|Cannon House]]</ref>\n\n;Car Manufacturers\n[[File:Jaguar sign 19o06.jpg|thumb|right|The leaping jaguar mascot outside the car company's head office south of Coventry]]\n*[[Land Rover]] [[Solihull plant|main factory]]<ref name=sh>[[Solihull]]</ref>\n*[[Jaguar Cars]], [[Peugeot]] UK (inc. [[Peugeot Technical Centre]]) and Citroen UK & Ireland<ref>Head office, B4110 at [[Stoke Aldermoor]]</ref> [[Whitley plant|Jaguar Land Rover Engineering Centre]]; [[Jaguar Land Rover]] have a large manufacturing plant at [[Castle Bromwich Assembly]] making the [[Jaguar XJ|XJ]], [[Jaguar XF|XF]] and [[Jaguar XK|XK]]. The Jaguar Veneer Manufacturing Centre.<ref>Jaguar Land Rover, [[Whitley, Coventry]]</ref>\n\n;Nearest Birmingham\n[[File:Cadbury Factory, Bournville - geograph.org.uk - 1266844.jpg|thumb|right|Cadbury in Birmingham]]\n*[[Cadbury]]'s main plant and [[Cadbury World]] remains in [[Bournville]], Birmingham; since 2012 owned by [[Mondel\u0113z International]]; today many executive functions are in [[Zurich]]; some milk chocolate is output from Fabryka w Jankowicach, Poland; [[Bournville (chocolate bar)|most dark]] for more than 10 years from France. \n*[[Dollond & Aitchison]] opticians and optical products [[Aston]]<ref>D&A, Aston Cross Business Park, 50 Rocky Lane, Aston, Birmingham, B6 5RQ</ref>\n*[[ATS Euromaster]] automotive repairs are in<ref>ATS Euromaster, [[Aston]], Birmingham</ref>\n*B Mason & Sons produce rolled copper and [[cupronickel]] alloy precision strips; applications include [[submarine communication cable]]s, coaxial cables and associated waveguides, contacts and heatsinks.<ref>Wharf Street, Aston, Birmingham</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bmason.co.uk/internet/media/training/quality/data_sheets/C103_Datasheet.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=12 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113035550/http://www.bmason.co.uk/internet/media/training/quality/data_sheets/C103_Datasheet.pdf |archive-date=13 January 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[Kiepe Electric]] UK (former Vossloh-Kiepe)<ref>Kiepe Electric, Aston Science Park, Birmingham</ref>\n*[[Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company|Goodyear Tyres]]<ref>Goodyear, 2920 Trident Court, Solihull Parkway, Birmingham Business Park, Birmingham</ref>\n*[[Dunlop Aircraft Tyres]] manufacture and retread<ref>40 Fort Pkwy, Birmingham</ref> \n*[[Claire's]] (accessories) European head office is off the A4040 at Erdington. \n*[[Royal Society for the Prevention of Accidents]] in training, surveying and policy advice.<ref>RoSPA, 28 Calthorpe Rd, Birmingham \u2013 specifically in [[Calthorpe Fields]] in north Edgbaston, next to [[St George's School, Birmingham|St George's School]]</ref>\n;Outskirts of County\n*[[GKN Driveline]] produce [[constant-velocity joint]]s<ref>Headquartered in Redditch, GKN Driveline its UK plant at the A38/[[A452 road|A452]] roundabout in [[Tyburn, West Midlands|Tyburn]], north of the JLR plant.</ref>\n*Stadco UK, metal pressing<ref>at [[Bromford]] off the A47.</ref>\n*Concentric UK produce [[Oil pump (internal combustion engine)|oil]] and water pumps for small diesel engines, off the A38 in [[Gravelly Hill]].\n*[[HiQ (tyres)|HiQ]], tyre merchants.\n*[[VDO (company)|VDO]] make fuel systems.\n*[[UK Mail]]<ref>Office/depot at the A47/A4040 junction next to the River Tame at [[Ward End]] near M6, and next to the former [[LDV Group|LDV]] factory.</ref>\n*[[Genting Group]] UK casinos<ref>Genting Group, [[Star City (entertainment complex)|Star City]] near Washwood Heath.</ref>\n*[[Dana Holding Corporation|Dana Traction Technologies]] make axles (including that of the [[Ford Transit]] and [[Range Rover]]) and [[limited slip differential]]s<ref>Dana Traction Technologies, [[Witton, West Midlands|Witton]]</ref>\n*[[Titanium Metals|TIMET]] UK. \n*[[SCC (Specialist Computer Centres)]] (computing)<ref>A41 at the [[River Cole, West Midlands|River Cole]] bridge</ref>\n*[[Goodrich Corporation|Goodrich Engine Controls]] make [[Engine control unit|engine control systems]] for jet engines<ref>Goodrich Engine Controls, [[Hall Green]], Birmingham</ref>\n*[[Pilkington]] Automotive make [[Triplex Safety Glass]]<ref>in [[Kings Norton]]</ref>\n*[[Alcoa]] plant<ref>[[Kitts Green]] (towards Solihull), next to the [[River Cole, West Midlands|River Cole]].</ref>\n*Small-scale production of [[MG (car)|MG]] by [[Nanjing Automobile (Group) Corporation|Nanjing Automobile Group]] on part of the former [[MG Rover Group]] site<ref>at [[Longbridge]].</ref>\n*Webasto Roof Systems<ref>is on the A4097 in Minworth</ref>\n*[[Hozelock]] make [[hose coupling]]s, sprayguns, sprinklers and rain/grey water pumps<ref>Hozelock, Midpoint Park Birmingham</ref>\n*[[Schaeffler Group]] UK (inc. [[INA (company)|INA]]) make [[timing belt (camshaft)|timing belt]]s and [[Automobile wheel bearing|wheel bearing]]s)for wind turbines, passenger cars and aircraft<ref>Maypoint Business Park, next to the railway on the opposite side of the A38</ref>\n*[[The Works (retailer)]] distribution centre, books, puzzles, toys and games<ref>Midpoint Park, south of A38</ref> \n*The [[Defence Infrastructure Organisation]] (former Defence Estates)<ref>[[Sutton Coldfield]]</ref>\n*[[Legrand (company)|Legrand]] UK make electrical switches)<ref>Legrand based at the A41/A4540 junction at [[Newtown, Birmingham|Newtown]] south of Aston.</ref> \n*[[Delcam]] ([[Computer-aided technologies|CAD/CAM]] software)<ref>at [[Small Heath, Birmingham|Small Heath]] Trading Est off the A45.</ref> \n*[[Eaton Corporation|Eaton Electric]] make [[residual-current device]]s<ref>Birmingham</ref> \n*[[Cutler-Hammer]] and [[Switchgear]]<ref>[[Tyseley]]</ref>\n*TRW Automotive Electronics<ref>TRW Automotive Electronics, A453 north of the M6 at [[Perry Barr]].</ref> \n*[[Highways England]] [[National Traffic Control Centre]]<ref>Highways England, [[Quinton, Birmingham|]], Birmingham.</ref> \n*[[Ishida (company)|Ishida]] Europe makes industrial [[multihead weigher]]s and food processing equipment<ref>Ishida, [[Woodgate, Birmingham|Woodgate]] Business Park</ref>\n*[[Lander Automotive]] make pipes for automotive cooling systems;\n*[[Aisin Seiki Co.|Aisin Europe Manufacturing]]\n*[[Keiper]] UK automotive seating\n\n;Near other main towns\n*[[Severn Trent]] (water)<ref>Severn Trent, 2 St John Street, Coventry</ref>\n*[[Saint-Gobain]] UK is based at Binley Business Park, in the same building as [[Jewson]] (owned by Saint-Gobain, who also own [[Graham Group]]). \n*[[Coventry Building Society]] nearby [[Jewson]], off the B4428, is in the east of the city at [[Binley, Coventry|Binley]]. \n*[[E.ON UK]] (former Powergen)\n*[[Molins (company)|Molins]] [[Innovative Technology for Custom Machinery|ITCM]] research centre\n*[[Chartered Institute of Housing]]\n*[[PCMS]] (retail software)\n*[[Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors|RICS]] UK<ref>Westwood Business Park in [[Westwood Heath]]</ref>\n*[[Bladon Jets]] develop micro [[gas turbine]]s and were the first to develop an [[Axial compressor|axial flow]] micro example in 1994.<ref>Bladon Jets, Pinley</ref>\n*[[Halfords Autocentre]]<ref name=sh/>\n*[[Motaquip Limited]] UYT [[body in white]] automotive components.\n*[[Axeon]] UK distributes [[lithium-ion battery|litium-ion batteries]]<ref>Axeon UK, Coventry</ref>\n\n[[Speciality Fibres and Materials]] developed [[Lyocell]] (Tencel) in the 1980s.<ref>SFM, [[Foleshill]]</ref>\n*[[Morgan Advanced Materials Composites and Defence Systems]], make the [[British Army]]'s helmet \u2013 the [[Mk 7 helmet]] and electronics for the [[Cougar (vehicle)]], as well as body armour for the police.<ref>[[Edgwick]] and [[Great Heath]]</ref>\n*[[Bystronic]] UK makes [[laser cutting]] equipment<ref>Wayside Business Park, [[Longford, Coventry]]</ref>\n*Magnetto-Topy make car wheels<ref name=wp>[[Whitmore Park]], Coventry</ref>\n*[[Stadco]] UK design division<ref name=wp/>\n*Pailton Engineering make [[steering column]]s and [[steering linkage]]s<ref name=wp/>\n*[[Meggitt Aircraft Braking Systems]] (MABS) see [[List of aircraft braking systems|Braking Systems]]; related [[Meggitt Thermal Systems]] produce aircraft [[ice protection system]]s.<ref name=wp/> \n*[[Brose (company)|Brose]] UK makes [[Mechatronics|mechatronic]] [[Power window|window regulator]]s and seat adjustors<ref>Bayton Road</ref>\n*The [[Education and Skills Funding Agency]], and [[National Apprenticeship Service]]. \n*[[AAH Pharmaceuticals]] and [[Lloyds Pharmacy]], owned by [[Celesio]].<ref name=wt>At [[Walsgrave]] Triangle</ref>\n*[[Sainsbury's]]: ''TU'' clothing distribution.<ref name=wt/>\n*[[Georg Fischer (Swiss company)|+GF+ AgieCharmilles]] (machine tools).<ref name=wt/> \n*[[Rohm and Haas]] UK makes materials for [[printed circuit board]]s<ref>[[Binley, Coventry|Binley]]</ref>\n*[[British Chambers of Commerce]], a representative and awards-giving corporate membership organisation. \n*[[Walkers (snack foods)]] within their corn and wheat products ranges<ref>Middlemarch Business Park, [[Baginton]] next to Coventry Airport</ref>\n*[[Gefco]] UK (owned by Peugeot); \n*[[Webasto]]-Edscha Cabrio UK make [[convertible]] car roofs. \n*[[Terex]] Construction makes [[backhoe loader]]s, [[Telescopic handler|telehandler]]s, site dumpers and other construction equipment.<ref name=pp>Prologis Park, Coventry</ref> \n*Co-op National Distribution Centre for the bulk of England<ref name=pp/>\n\n[[File:MuedaGas 0126.jpg|thumb|left|A [[Land Rover Defender]] in eastern Africa, made in Solihull]]\nThe [[Forensic Science Service]], [[Linpac]], [[Lafarge (company)|Lafarge Cement UK]] and [[IMI plc]] (former [[ICI Metals Division]]) are on the Birmingham Business Park in [[Bickenhill]], near the airport; the [[National Exhibition Centre]] (NEC) is just north, between the airport and the M42. [[Lafarge Tarmac]] is in Marston Green, [[Bickenhill]]; [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF Lemf\u00f6rder UK]]'s site at Bickenhill makes axle modules for Land Rover off the B4438 north of the NEC, near the new site of [[Tarmac (company)|Tarmac]] (after the Lafarge merger). [[Newey and Eyre]], Britain's largest electrical wholesaler and part of [[Rexel]] UK, is at Sheldon on the [[A45 road|A45]] near the airport. [[Neopost]] UK is off the A452. [[Goodrich Corporation|Goodrich UK]] is in [[Shirley, West Midlands|Shirley]]. [[Prologis]] UK, [[Intersport]] UK (on the Cranmore Ind Est), and [[Enterprise Inns]] are on the A34 in [[Monkspath]]; next door is [[Trelleborg Sealing Solutions]] UK; [[TRW Automotive|TRW Conekt]] have a main automotive engineering research centre (with Girling Brakes, at the former Lucas Research Centre) at the A34/B4102 roundabout at The Green Business Park in Shirley Heath, further north on the A34 from Enterprise Inns, on other side of the road. The Mormons (Latter Day Saints) have their European HQ in Solihull near the [[Heart of England NHS Foundation Trust|hospital]], on the B4025 opposite Morrisons. [[Amtico]] (flooring) is based in the south of Solihull, with a main factory in [[Foleshill]], Coventry. [[Compin]] UK, with [[Fainsa]], are in Solihull, and make train and bus seats.\n\n[[File:Former Staffordshire Building Society Offices.jpg|thumb|right|Carillion head office in Wolverhampton]]\n[[Carillion]] in construction<ref>Wolverhampton [[Wolverhampton Ring Road|ring-road]] (A4150)</ref>\n[[Tarmac Group]] was on the A4039 south-east of the city centre in [[Ettingshall]] until 2012 when it merged with Lafarge. [[Marston's Brewery|Marston's]] is headquartered west of the ring road, on the A41, and have the [[Park Brewery]] on the A4124, east of the city centre. The UK's [[VAT Registration Service]], for [[Value Added Tax (United Kingdom)|Value Added Tax]] is at HMRC in Wolverhampton on the opposite side of the [[Wolverhampton Ring Road]] (A4150) to the HQ of Marstons, on the west side of the town centre. [[Flint Group|Flint Ink]] UK in the east of the town centre, former [[Mander Brothers]], was the largest ink supplier in the [[British Empire]], before being bought in 1998. [[BAE Systems Land & Armaments]] (former [[Alvis plc|Alvis]] Bridging and Vickers Armstrong) formerly on the A4126 in [[Ettingshall]], near the former Tarmac site, closed at the end of 2011. In [[Fordhouses]], along the [[A449 road|A449]] to the north, are [[HS Marston]] (part of the former [[Hamilton Sundstrand]], now [[UTC Aerospace Systems]]) makes [[heat exchanger]]s, [[Goodrich Corporation|Goodrich Actuation Systems]] (the former Actuation Division of Lucas Aerospace and [[H. M. Hobson]]), and a new engine plant for JLR. Goodrich in the UK, is what became of Lucas before a takeover by Goodrich; Lucas Aerospace was a world leader in flight control actuation for civil aircraft.\n\n[[File:Steel Distribution Depot - geograph.org.uk - 236054.jpg|thumb|left|Wednesfield Steelpark in September 2006]]\nOn the Staffordshire boundary, to the west on the Pendeford Business Park, are [[ADAS (company)|ADAS]] (previously on the A41 in [[Wergs]]), [[Gunnebo Security Group|Gunnebo]] UK ([[Automated cash handling|cash handling]]) and [[Birmingham Midshires]]. [[Turner Powertrain Systems]] is the world market leader for transmissions for [[backhoe loader]]s, mini [[excavator]]s [[telescopic handler]]s, and site dumpers is further south, to the west of the A449 near [[Dunstall Hill]]. [[Hampson Industries]] is in [[Brierley Hill]]. Wednesbury Tube (part of [[Mueller Industries]]) make [[Copper tubing|copper pipe]] on the A41 in Bilston at the Key Ind Est near the [[Loxdale tram stop]], and its sister company [[Primaflow]] makes brass fittings in Nechells. On the A4124, Tata Steel (former site of British Steel Seamless Tubes until 1995) have their [[Wednesfield Steelpark]] (the UK's biggest steelyard, built by Corus in 1999) on the Walsall boundary.\n\n[[Boss Design]] is a furniture manufacturer in Blowers Green, Dudley at the [[A461 road|A461]]/A459 roundabout. [[KUKA]] Robotics UK, a maker of industrial robots, and [[Joseph Ash]] (galvinizers) are off the A459 at [[Mucklow Hill]] in Halesowen, with [[Floors-2-Go]] based off the [[A458 road|A458]]; [[Sandvik]] Coromant UK (Swedish machine cutting tools, who provide Birmingham's [[Christmas tree]]) are off junction 3 of the M5 on the A456. Hingley Trailers (former M+G Trailers before 2009) makes [[Semi-trailer|trailer]]s on the [[A458 road|A458]] in [[Lye, West Midlands|Lye]]. [[Marcegaglia]] UK make electrical-resistance welded steel tubes off the [[A461 road|A461]] in Dudley. [[Essar Group|Essar Steel]] UK (former [[Servosteel]]) on the A4101 Pensnett Road in west Dudley, is the largest independent steel toll processor in the UK. [[Rentokil Initial|Initial Cleaning Services]] (Facilities) is based on the Ashmore Ind Estate, at the [[A461 road|A461]]/A459 Castle Gate Island roundabout, opposite the [[Showcase Cinemas|Showcase]] cinema on the Castle Gate Leisure Park. The [[Merry Hill Shopping Centre]], similar to [[Meadowhall (shopping centre)|Meadowhall]] in [[Sheffield]], is built on a large former steelworks, the [[Round Oak Steelworks]].\n\n[[Avery Weigh-Tronix]] is on the site of James Watt's [[Soho Foundry]] in [[Smethwick]]; [[Interlink Express]] (and its parent [[GeoPost]] UK) is on Summit Crescent Ind Estate off the [[A4252 road|A4252]], north of [[Smethwick Galton Bridge railway station]], next to the M5. [[Hadley Group]] near the Soho Foundry is the largest [[Rolling (metalworking)|cold roll forming]] manufacturer in the UK. J. B. & S. Lees makes [[Strip steel|steel strip]] at the Trident Steel Works in Albion, West Bromwich off the B4166 and also by [[Firth Cleveland]] at the B4517/B4163 junction in Tipton further up the Birmingham Canal. Caparo Precision Tubes between the M5 and A4182 in Oldbury, is the UK's largest producer of [[Electric resistance welding|electric resistance welded]] (ERW) steel tubes, and [[Wellman Group]] make boilers off the A457 to the west. [[Metsec]], east of Oldbury (owned by [[Voestalpine]]), is one of the UK's largest [[Rolling (metalworking)|cold roll-forming]] companies. [[Conex B\u00e4nninger]] (former IBP Conex), on the B4166 in New Town, west of West Bromwich on Birmingham Canal, make pipe and [[compression fitting]]s. [[Rhodia (company)|Rhodia]]'s Oldbury site on the B4170 in [[Langley Green, West Midlands|Langley Green]], south of Oldbury and east of the M5 is a world-leading site (former [[Albright and Wilson]]) in phosphorus-based chemistry. The AA have a main office on the A4123 at the A4034 roundabout in [[Rounds Green]], west of Oldbury. [[BIP Chemicals]] (former British Cyanides) at Oldbury are the oldest polymer manufacturer in the UK. STILL UK ([[KION Group]]) is in [[Harvills Hawthorn]], [[Golds Hill]] at the A461/A41 roundabout, north-west of West Bromwich; further along the A41 is [[2 Sisters Food Group]], Britain's largest processor of chicken. Nesbit Evans in the east of Wednesbury, off the A41, are a main manufacturer of hospital beds, owned by [[ArjoHuntleigh]].\n\n[[File:Chubb building.jpg|thumb|left|Willenhall is the lockmaking capital of the UK, and the home of Chubb]]\nThe national headquarters of [[One Stop]] is on the A4124 in [[Brownhills]], at [[Clayhanger, West Midlands|Clayhanger]]. [[Homeserve]] is in the north of Walsall on the [[A34 road|A34]], opposite Walsall Retail Park; next door to the north, on the other side of the [[Wyrley and Essington Canal]] on the B4210, on the edge of [[Blakenall Heath]], is [[Eagle Envelopes]], part of [[Mayer-Kuvert]], Europe's leading envelope manufacturer. [[Imperial Bathroom Company]], on the Empire Ind Est off the B4152 in [[Leighswood]], is in the north of Walsall borough; next door is [[RMD Kwikform]] (scaffolding) on the opposite side of [[Rushall Canal]]; to the south was GKN Driveline Walsall from 1953 until 2010, which was the largest independent manufacturer of [[Constant-velocity joint|CV-jointed]] [[Drive shaft|propshaft]]s in Europe. [[Poundland]] is in [[Willenhall]], on the side of the [[Black Country Route]] ([[A454 road|A454]]) towards the M6 junction 11. [[Wedge Group]], based on the B4484 in Willenhall, is the largest [[Hot-dip galvanizing|hot dip galvanising]] company in the UK. [[Assa Abloy]] UK (and [[Yale (company)|Yale]] UK, former Yale & Towne), owned by a Swedish company, is off the A454 at the B4464 roundabout in Willenhall, as the town is known for manufacture of locks; close by is [[A.F. Blakemore]], which supplies most of the [[Spar (retailer)|SPAR]] shops in the UK. [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF Lemf\u00f6rder UK]] make chassis components (a main competitor to GKN), in the east of Darlaston, with [[Caparo]] Atlas Fastenings off the A4038.\n{{clear}}\n\n===Worcestershire===\n{{see also|Manufacturing in Worcester}}\n[[File:Worcester Bosch - geograph.org.uk - 57948.jpg|thumb|right|Worcester Bosch; Bosch Thermotechnology are in [[Warndon]] ]]\nIn Redditch are [[Halfords]], on the B4497 to the south in [[Washford, Worcestershire|Washford]], and [[GKN]] (it has the second largest turnover in the West Midlands) is on the [[A441 road|A441]] in [[Riverside, Worcestershire|Riverside]]. CompAir Hydrovane, who make [[Rotary vane pump|rotary vane]] compressors, are on the [[Districts of Redditch|Washford]] Ind Estate near the B4497/A453 junction in Redditch. [[Mettis Aerospace]] are on the B4184 in Enfield, north Redditch, and make light metal components (the former [[High Duty Alloys Ltd.|High Duty Alloys]], which made most of the [[Forging|forged]] pistons for Britain's aircraft engines in WWII). [[Hymatic]] (part of Honeywell Defense and Space) make world-leading [[cryocooler]]s, on Moon's Moat Ind Est, in the north-east of Redditch; on same site the [[KAC Alarm Company]], also part of Honeywell, make [[Manual fire alarm activation|break glass call points]] for [[Fire alarm system|fire alarm]]s; they innovated them in the 1970s, and are global leaders. [[Magna International|Magna Interior Systems]] make the cockpit module ([[dashboard]]) for the MINI. [[Henry Milward & Sons|Entaco]] make needles for hand sewing and medical purposes in the south of Redditch on the Washford Ind Est. Directly east of Redditch in [[Beoley]] is [[Lear Corporation]] UK, who make car seats. [[Phoenix Group (company)|Phoenix Group]] (non-public [[Life insurance|life assurance]] schemes) is off the A435 in the north-east of the county near the Warwickshire boundary, at [[Wythall]], and has a large turnover; nearby to west [[Metalrax]], headquartered in [[Alvechurch]] near the M42, make (via subsidiaries) most of the [[Cookware and bakeware|bakeware]] sold in the UK.\n\n[[File:Lea & Perrins worcestershire sauce 150ml.jpg|thumb|right|The factory opened in 1897; the recipe for [[Worcestershire sauce]] came from [[Marcus Sandys, 3rd Baron Sandys|Lord Sandys]], and was only discovered accidentally when initially discarded and left to mature for months]]\nRoger Dyson Group manufactures [[Vehicle recovery|auto-recovery]] vehicles off the A442 in north Droitwich, near [[Vax (vacuum)|Vax]] and [[Koito Industries|Koito Europe]] (car [[headlamp]]s). South of Bromsgrove, on the B4091 at [[Stoke Prior, Worcestershire|Stoke Prior]], [[L.G. Harris & Co]] make [[paintbrush]]es. [[Lea & Perrins]] is in [[Worcester]]. [[Joy Mining Machinery]] are on the A44 in the west of Worcester. [[Worcester, Bosch Group]] make 1,200 boilers a day. [[Yamazaki Mazak Corporation|Mazak]] UK have the parent company's European manufacturing facility (for [[Numerical control|CNC]] machine tools) on the B4639 in the north of Worcester, next to the [[Worcester and Birmingham Canal]]; nearby on the Blackpole Ind Est, [[Froude Hofmann]] have their world headquarters, who make [[dynamometer]]s, originated from [[William Froude]] (formerly [[Heenan & Froude]]).\n\n[[Sealine]] make boats at the [[A442 road|A442]]/A451 roundabout in Kidderminster, owned by [[Brunswick Boat Group]]. Also in Kidderminster off the A451, Stourport Road are [[Brintons]] Carpets and [[Beakbane]]. [[Roxel]] UK (equally owned by [[Safran]] and [[MBDA]]), develops [[solid-fuel rocket]]s for missiles at the A449/A442 junction south of Kidderminster and in [[Hartlebury]], on the former site of [[Royal Ordnance Rocket Motors]]. The [[West Midland Safari Park]] is off the [[A456 road|A456]] in [[Bewdley]], west of Kidderminster. [[Morgan Technical Ceramics]] is headquartered on the B4195 at [[Lickhill]] in [[Stourport-on-Severn]], south of Kidderminster; at the B4193/A4025 roundabout, [[XTA Electronics]] make [[audio amplifiers]]. [[Egbert H. Taylor]] off the A442 in [[Elmley Lovett]], near [[Hartlebury]] is the world's leading manufacturer of metal bins.  Leigh Sinton was the home of [[Biffa Waste Services]] Worcester depot until the closure in July 2013.\n\n[[File:Qinetiq, Malvern - geograph.org.uk - 728922.jpg|thumb|left|Qinetiq at the [[Malvern Hills Science Park]], or Malvern Technology Centre; the integrated circuit was invented here in 1952]]\n[[Liquid crystal display]]s were developed in 1972 in conjunction with the [[Royal Radar Establishment]], where [[Geoffrey Dummer]] invented the idea of the [[integrated circuit]] in 1952. It was based in [[Malvern, Worcestershire|Malvern]], and became the [[Royal Signals and Radar Establishment]], which developed [[Thermography|thermal imaging]] and [[Pyroelectricity|pyroelectric]] [[infrared detector]]s, and is now a large site owned by [[QinetiQ]]. [[Morgan Motor Company]] is in [[Malvern Link]]; nearby is [[Desire Petroleum]]. [[Commsoft RMS]] is in [[Evesham]]. [[Allen Gears]] supply industrial-sized gears off the A4104 in [[Pershore]]. For many years [[Group 4 (company)|Group 4 Security]], which was the largest security company in Europe, had its headquarters in [[Broadway, Worcestershire|Broadway]] off the A44, on the edge of the [[Cotswolds]]; [[G4S]] Integrated Services now has its HQ there.\n\n==Education==\n[[File:KEASTON Main.jpg|right|thumb|[[King Edward VI Aston School]]]]\n\n[[File:ShrewsburySixthFormCollege.JPG|right|thumb|[[Shrewsbury Sixth Form College]] ]]\n{{More citations needed section|date=January 2017}}\n\n===Secondary education===\nSelective schools are in low numbers as follows: Birmingham (8), Walsall (2), Wolverhampton (1), Warwickshire (6), Stoke-on-Trent (1), and Telford and Wrekin (2). The highest proportion per head therefore is Warwickshire (its population is between 550,000 and 600,000 people). The other counties and metropolitan boroughs have none, their public education systems are comprehensive in intake. The grammar and independent schools tend to produce pass-rate examination results among the top twenty ranked regionally. Many pupils compete for entrance examinations to attend such long-established [[Grammar schools in England|Grammar Schools]] and most have significant parent sponsorship. In 2016 two of the top ten such schools nationally were in Warwickshire, where in the [[CV postcode area|CV37 postal district]] prices were 34% higher than the county as a whole.<ref>https://www.lloydsbank.com/assets/media/pdfs/press-releases/2016/160907-house-prices-near-schools-press-release.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212074021/http://www.lloydsbank.com/assets/media/pdfs/press-releases/2016/160907-house-prices-near-schools-press-release.pdf |date=12 December 2017 }} Press Release \"Parents willing to pay \u00a353,000 more to live near a top school\n\", Lloyds Bank, 2016</ref> The top 20 schools at A-level rarely change from year to year; slightly lower in the table pass-rate boosts and top grades regularly occur among the schools receiving industrial funding, with similar frequency to London, the North East, and the North West, particularly in [[free school (England)|schools]] and [[Academy (English school)|academies]] which have some of the most advanced facilities.\n\nAround 275,000 secondary schools are in the region, the greatest number after the [[South East England|South East]], Greater London and [[North West England|North West]].\n\nAt [[GCSE]] based on % of entrants' pass rates, the best performing local government area in 2010 was [[Solihull]], closely followed by Warwickshire and Shropshire. Dudley, Herefordshire, Telford and Wrekin, Birmingham and Staffordshire (in descending order) are above the English average, at which rate, is approximately Worcestershire. The area consistently having fewest passes is [[Sandwell]], followed by Stoke-on-Trent.  Struggling pupils in Wolverhampton and Walsall also attain fewer passes than the English average in most GCSE years, sometimes by a very narrow margin.  For metropolitan boroughs, Solihull then Dudley perform best. Dudley is the best metropolitan borough at A-level passes and has a consistent post-2000 history of being better than Solihull.\n\nSchools have been [[off-rolling]] pupils.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Adams |first1=Richard |title='Off-rolling' hides true extent of disadvantage gap in schools \u2013 study |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2019/dec/05/off-rolling-hides-true-extent-of-disadvantage-gap-in-schools-study |accessdate=19 December 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=5 December 2019}}</ref>  Pupils likely to do badly in examinations are expelled before the examinations to improve the school performance in league tables.  Expelled pupils then disproportionately get involved in gangs and in crime.  [[Knife crime in the West Midlands]] is the highest outside London.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/dec/05/west-midlands-schools-fuelling-violent-by-excluding-pupils West Midlands schools 'fuelling violent crime by excluding pupils'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205204909/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/dec/05/west-midlands-schools-fuelling-violent-by-excluding-pupils |date=5 December 2018 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nAt A-level in 2010, the consistently best performing area was Herefordshire where most A-level candidates attend Hereford [[sixth form college]]. Dudley is also above the English average; the other metropolitan boroughs have low-to-average A-level pass or high mark proportions. Shropshire is at the English average.\n\nRegionally in persistent [[truancy]] at secondary school, Sandwell had the highest rate at 6.9%; [[Bromsgrove (district)|Bromsgrove]] had the lowest at 2.3%.<ref>2010 statistics (approx.)</ref>\n\n===Tertiary education===\nThere are thirty-seven FE colleges (FECs).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aoc.co.uk/en/aoc_regions/regions.cfm/region/WM/region/WM/page/1|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130817212236/http://www.aoc.co.uk/en/aoc_regions/regions.cfm/region/WM/region/WM/page/1|url-status=dead|title=Directory of AoC member Colleges|archivedate=17 August 2013}}</ref> There are six LSCs for the area (which fund FECs), and the [[Learning and Skills Council]] head office is based in [[Coventry]]. The five largest FE colleges in the region \u2013 [[Bournville College]], [[North Warwickshire and Hinckley College]], [[Solihull College]], [[South & City College Birmingham]] and [[Stoke-on-Trent College]] \u2013 each have more than 25,000 students.\n\nSchool children in Shropshire and Solihull are most likely to attend university, followed by Herefordshire, Worcestershire and Warwickshire.\n\n===School league tables===\nBelow is a list of the top thirty state schools in the West Midlands by 2010 A level results:\n* 1. [[King Edward VI Camp Hill]] School for Girls, Kings Heath (1212)\n* 2. [[Sutton Coldfield Grammar School for Girls]]\n* 3. [[King Edward VI Five Ways]], [[Bartley Green]]\n* 4. [[King Edward VI Camp Hill]] School for Boys, [[Kings Heath]]\n* 5. [[Stratford-upon-Avon Grammar School for Girls]]\n* 6. [[Queen Mary's Grammar School]], Walsall\n* 7. [[King Edward VI College, Stourbridge]]\n* 8. [[Newport Girls High School]]\n* 9. [[King Edward VI Handsworth]]\n* 10. [[King Edward VI School, Stratford-upon-Avon]]\n* 11. [[King Edward VI Aston]]\n* 12. [[Bishop Vesey's Grammar School]], [[Sutton Coldfield]]\n* 13. [[Wolverhampton Girls' High School]]\n* 14. [[Thomas Telford School]], [[Telford]]\n* 15. [[St. Joseph's College, Stoke-on-Trent]]\n* 16. [[Queen Mary's High School]], Walsall\n* 17. [[Rugby High School for Girls]]\n* 18. [[St Augustine's High School, Redditch]]\n* 19. [[Hereford Sixth Form College]]\n* 20. [[Moorlands Sixth Form College]], [[Cheadle, Staffordshire]]\n* 21. [[King Edward VI Sheldon Heath Academy]]\n* 22. [[Southam College]]\n* 23. [[Shrewsbury Sixth Form College]]\n* 24. [[King Edward VI School (Lichfield)]]\n* 25. [[Plantsbrook School]], Sutton Coldfield\n* 26. [[Colyton Grammar School]]\n* 27. [[Kings Norton Girls School]]\n* 28. [[Old Swinford Hospital]], [[Stourbridge]]\n* 29. [[St Francis of Assisi Catholic Technology College]], Aldridge\n* 30. [[William Brookes School]], [[Much Wenlock]] (880)\n\n===Universities===\n[[File:University of Birmingham - Aston Webb.jpg|thumb|right|University of Birmingham]]\n[[File:Medical teaching centre WU 4g07.JPG|thumb|right|University of Warwick \u2013 Medical Teaching Centre]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! University\n! Students\n! National Ranking (2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings|title=Top UK University League Tables and Rankings 2019|author=|date=|website=thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk|access-date=17 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013231901/https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings|archive-date=13 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[University of Birmingham]]\n| 34,835\n|15\n|-\n|[[Coventry University]]\n| 31,690\n|50\n|-\n|[[University of Warwick]]\n| 25,615\n| 8\n|-\n|[[Birmingham City University]]\n| 24,130\n|95\n|-\n|[[University of Wolverhampton]]\n| 19,560\n| \u2013\n|-\n|[[Staffordshire University]]\n| 14,910\n|101\n|-\n|[[Aston University]]\n| 14,162\n|30\n|-\n|[[University of Worcester]]\n| 10,745\n|97\n|-\n|[[Keele University]]\n| 10,600\n|46\n|-\n|[[Harper Adams University]]\n| 5,410\n|46\n|-\n|[[University College Birmingham]]\n| 4,935\n| \u2013\n|-\n|[[Newman University, Birmingham|Newman University]]\n| 2,830 \n| \u2013\n|}\n\nThe University of Birmingham is the main university in the region<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hefce.ac.uk/pubs/hefce/2007/07_18/outputWM.pdf|title=HEFCE|author=|date=|website=hefce.ac.uk|access-date=29 March 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091112183521/http://www.hefce.ac.uk/pubs/hefce/2007/07_18/outputWM.pdf|archive-date=12 November 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> and has the most funding. It has a large research grant, as does the University of Warwick, which is the next largest in terms of funding. Birmingham and Warwick are members of the [[Russell Group]] of public research universities. Keele and Aston have a moderate research grant, but none of the other universities do. Keele, although having the largest campus in the UK (by area), is one of the smallest universities in the region. There are medical schools at [[Warwick Medical School|Warwick]], [[Keele University Medical School|Keele]] and [[University of Birmingham Medical School|Birmingham]]. Birmingham and Warwick receive more than twice as much total income than any other university in the region \u2013 around \u00a3400&nbsp;million each.\n\nAround 45% of students are from the region, and 35% from other parts of the UK, while 20% are from overseas.  The region attracts students from [[South East England]] owing to good access via the [[M40 motorway|M40]] and the [[West Coast Main Line]], but there is a good mix from other regions too, except the North East (especially) and Yorkshire.  Students native to the West Midlands are most likely to study in the region (40%), then the [[East Midlands]] (12%), the [[North West England|North West]] (11%), and then Yorkshire (9%). Very few go to the [[East of England]] or the [[North East England|North East]]. The region has a net export of university students to other regions.\n\nAt time of graduation in 2010 almost 60% of graduates remained in the West Midlands, with 10% going to London, 7% to the South-East, and around 5% to the East Midlands. Very few go to Yorkshire, the North-East, or even (neighbouring) Wales.\n\n==Media==\n{{See also|Media in Birmingham}}\n\n=== Television ===\n[[File:ITV Central TV studios - geograph.org.uk - 1150068.jpg|thumb|right|ITV Central [[Gas Street Studios]] in Birmingham]]\nThe West Midlands region of the [[BBC]] is based at the [[Mailbox Birmingham|Mailbox]] in Birmingham. From there, the regional programme [[Midlands Today]] is produced. [[Central Independent Television|ITV Central]] broadcasts from Birmingham, off [[Broad Street, Birmingham|Broad Street]] on [[Gas Street Basin|Gas Street]] next to the [[Worcester and Birmingham Canal]], with its [[ITV News Central]] regional programme.\n\nSome northern parts of the region, including [[Biddulph]], receive [[BBC North West Tonight]] and [[Granada Reports]] both of which are based at [[Media City UK]] in [[City of Salford|Salford]] and are broadcast from the [[Winter Hill transmitting station|Winter Hill]] transmitter.\n\nThe BBC has its engineering training centre at [[Wood Norton, Worcestershire]], off the A44 north of Evesham in Norton and Lenchwick. [[BBC English Regions]] is based at Birmingham.\n\n=== Radio ===\n\n==== BBC Local Radio ====\nThe West Midlands is served by numerous [[BBC Local Radio]] stations, including [[BBC WM]], [[BBC Coventry & Warwickshire]], [[BBC Radio Stoke]], [[BBC Hereford & Worcester]] and [[BBC Radio Shropshire]].\n\n==== Commercial radio ====\nCommercial radio stations include [[Free Radio (network)|Free Radio]], [[Capital Midlands]], [[Capital Mid-Counties]], [[Heart West Midlands]], [[Smooth Radio West Midlands]], [[Absolute Radio]], [[Signal Radio]], [[Signal 107]], [[Sunshine 855]] and [[Sunshine Radio (FM)|Sunshine Radio Herefordshire & Monmouthshire]].\n\n==== Community Radio ====\n\n[[Community radio]] stations include:\n* The Bridge 102.5 ([[Stourbridge]])\n* [[Youthcomm Radio]] ([[Worcester]]) \n* [[Big City Radio]] ([[Birmingham]]) \n* Radio Plus and Hillz FM in ([[Coventry]]) \n* [[WCR FM]] and Gorgeous Radio ([[Wolverhampton]]) \n* [[Moorlands Radio]] ([[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]]) \n* [[6 Towns Radio]], Cre8 FM and [[Cross Rhythms City Radio]] ([[Stoke-on-Trent]]) \n* The Hitmix ([[Newcastle-under-Lyme]]) \n* [[Cannock Chase Radio]] and [[Stafford FM]] ([[Stafford]])\n\nStafford is also notable for [[Windmill Broadcasting]], the [[United Kingdom|UK's]] only radio station based in a [[Windmill]], in the [[Broad Eye Windmill]].\n\n=== Newspapers ===\nLocal newspapers include:\n* ''[[Berrow's Worcester Journal]]''\n* ''[[Birmingham Mail]]''\n* ''[[Birmingham Post]]''\n* ''[[Burton Mail]]''\n* ''[[Coventry Telegraph]]''\n* ''[[Express & Star]]'' (Wolverhampton)\n* ''[[Nuneaton News]]''\n* ''[[Shropshire Star]]''\n* ''[[The Sentinel (Staffordshire)|The Sentinel]]'' (Stoke-on-Trent)\n* ''[[The Shuttle (Kidderminster)|The Shuttle]]'' (Kidderminster based, reporting on Wyre Forest news, Worcestershire)\n* ''[[Worcester News]]''\n\n===Magazines===\nWilliam Gibbons of Wolverhampton prints ''[[New Scientist]]'', ''[[The Lady (magazine)|The Lady]]'', ''[[Farmers Weekly]]'', ''[[BBC Focus]]'', ''[[Psychologies]]'', ''[[History Revealed]]'', ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'', and ''[[Tractors & Machinery]]''.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nThe Polestar Varnicoat works on the A44 in [[Pinvin]], north of Pershore, for many years{{when|date=August 2016}} printed ''[[Woman's Own]]'', ''[[Heat (magazine)|Heat]]'', ''[[Pick Me Up (magazine)|Pick Me Up]]'', ''[[Chat (magazine)|Chat]]'', and ''That's Life''.\n\n=== Online ===\n[[Channel 4]]'s 4Talent network has a hub in the West Midlands dealing with rising media talent from the region.<ref>[http://4talent.channel4.com/<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{Cite web |url=http://4talent.channel4.com/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=15 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810190536/http://4talent.channel4.com/ |archive-date=10 August 2014 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n{{See also|Sport in Birmingham}}\n[[File:St Georges Park Aerial May 2012.jpg|thumb|right|St George's Park is the training ground of the [[England National Football Team]]]]\nThe [[National Sports Centre]] at [[Lilleshall Hall]] is in [[Sheriffhales]], Shropshire, north-east of Telford; it was largely established by the [[Sport and Recreation Alliance|Central Council of Physical Recreation]] in 1949 as a National Recreation Centre; the south of England had theirs at [[Bisham Abbey]] on the Thames. [[St George's Park National Football Centre]] is at [[Tatenhill]] near [[Byrkley Park]] in [[Needwood Forest]], near former the [[RAF Tatenhill]] off the [[A515 road|A515]], four miles west of Burton upon Trent.\n\nThe [[Tough Guy Competition]], now a widespread sport competition in the US, began in 1987 on a farm at [[Perton]] in Staffordshire. The main British athletics championships are held in Birmingham in late June. The [[International Olympic Committee|Olympic Movement]] started at [[Much Wenlock]], and also to the east of region, where [[Pierre de Coubertin|Baron de Coubertin]] formulated his ideas for sport and the Olympics at [[Rugby School]] in 1883, with the headmaster [[Thomas Arnold]], whose son would be the famous poet [[Matthew Arnold]] and whose great-grandson would be [[Aldous Huxley]].\n\n===Football===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Club\n! League\n! City/Town\n! Stadium\n! Capacity\n|-\n|[[Aston Villa FC]]\n| [[Premier League]]\n| [[Birmingham]]\n|[[Villa Park]]\n| 42,788\n|-\n|[[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.]]\n|Premier League\n| [[Wolverhampton]]\n|[[Molineux Stadium]]\n| 31,700\n|-\n|[[Birmingham City F.C.]]\n|[[EFL Championship]]\n| Birmingham\n|[[St Andrew's (stadium)|St Andrew's]]\n| 30,079\n|-\n|[[Stoke City FC]]\n| Championship\n| [[Stoke-on-Trent]]\n|[[Britannia Stadium]]\n| 28,384\n|-\n|[[West Bromwich Albion FC]]\n| Championship\n| [[West Bromwich]]\n|[[The Hawthorns]]\n| 26,500\n|-\n|[[Burton Albion F.C.]]\n| [[League One]]\n| [[Burton-upon-Trent]]\n|[[Pirelli Stadium]]\n| 6,912\n|-\n|[[Coventry City FC]]\n| League One\n| [[Coventry]]\n|[[Ricoh Arena]]\n| 32,609\n|-\n|[[Shrewsbury Town F.C.]]\n| League One\n| [[Shrewsbury]]\n|[[Prostar Stadium]]\n| 9,875\n|-\n|[[Walsall F.C.]]\n| League One\n| [[Walsall]]\n|[[Bescot Stadium]]\n| 11,300\n|-\n|[[Port Vale F.C.]]\n| [[League Two]]\n| Stoke-on-Trent\n|[[Vale Park]]\n| 19,052\n|-\n|[[Solihull Moors]]\n|[[National League (division)|National League]]\n| [[Solihull]]/Birmingham\n|Damson Park\n|3,050\n|-\n|[[A.F.C. Telford United]]\n|[[National League North]]\n| [[Telford]]\n|[[New Bucks Head]]\n| 6,300\n|-\n|[[Hereford F.C.]]\n|National League North\n| [[Hereford]]\n|[[Edgar Street]]\n| 4,913\n|-\n|[[Kidderminster Harriers F.C.]]\n|National League North\n| [[Kidderminster]]\n|[[Aggborough]]\n| 6,250\n|-\n| [[Nuneaton Town F.C.]]\n|National League North\n| [[Nuneaton]]\n| [[Liberty Way]]\n| 4,314\n|-\n|[[Leamington F.C.]]\n|National League North\n| [[Whitnash]]\n|New Windmill Ground\n| 5,000\n|}\n\n===Rugby===\nIn [[rugby union]], the region is home to professional [[English Premiership (rugby union)|Premiership]] teams [[Wasps RFC]] and [[Worcester Warriors]]. In [[rugby league]], [[Coventry Bears]] play in the third tier [[League 1 (rugby league)|League 1]].\n\n===Tennis===\n{{See also|History of tennis}}\n[[File:Tennis Match, Family Circle Cup 2008.JPG|thumb|right|Tennis was invented in Edgbaston, Birmingham]]\nBritain's first tennis club was founded in 1872 in [[Royal Leamington Spa|Leamington Spa]]. The modern rules of lawn tennis were developed in 1874 by Leamington Tennis Club. Tennis was pioneered in Edgbaston in 1859, and [[Edgbaston Archery and Lawn Tennis Society]] also claims to be the oldest tennis club in the world, where tennis was invented by Major [[Harry Gem]] and the Spaniard [[Augurio Perera]].\n\nA famous 1970s [[Tennis Girl]] picture was taken on 12 September 1976 by Oldbury's [[Martin Elliott]] at the tennis courts of Birmingham University, featuring 18-year-old Fiona Butler, now of [[Stourport-on-Severn]].{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n===Motor sport===\n[[Team Dynamics]] at [[Pershore]], has won the [[British Touring Car Championship]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons and category|West Midlands|West Midlands (region)}}\n{{Portal|England}}\n* [http://www.advantagewm.co.uk/ Advantage West Midlands \u2013 Regional Development Agency]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111026042255/http://www.go-wm.gov.uk/ Government Office for the West Midlands]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140222044235/http://www.wmra.gov.uk/ West Midlands Regional Assembly]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061130220616/http://www.direct.gov.uk/Dl1/Directories/LocalCouncils/LocalGovernmentByRegion/fs/en?CONTENT_ID=4003650&chk=J1Wt8n Government's list of councils in the West Midlands]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100318045124/http://www.mlawestmidlands.org.uk/ MLA West Midlands \u2013 Museums, Libraries and Archives Regional Agency]\n* [http://www.westmidlands.nhs.uk/ NHS West Midlands \u2013 The regional Strategic Health Authority for the West Midlands]\n* [http://www.bclm.co.uk/ Black Country Living Museum, which tells the history of the modern West Midlands areas of Dudley, Sandwell, Walsall and Wolverhampton]\n\n{{United Kingdom topics}}\n{{English regions}}\n{{West Midlands}}\n\n{{coord|52.47|N|2.29|W|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:West Midlands (Region)}}\n[[Category:West Midlands (region)| ]]\n[[Category:Regions of England]]\n[[Category:NUTS 1 statistical regions of England]]\n[[Category:NUTS 1 statistical regions of the European Union]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eScientific heritage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/West_Midlands_(region)"}
